<deck>
  <title>AP CSA Essential Knowledge</title>

  <section>
    <title>Data types</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A type is a set of values (a domain) and a set of operations on them.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two things define a type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A set of values (a domain) and a set of operations on them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A name and an initial value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword and a memory location.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class and a constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the definition of a type, what is the "domain"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of values that belong to that type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The way the type is stored in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class that implements the type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>int</code> considered a different type from <code>double</code>, even though both represent numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They have different domains (sets of possible values) and different operations defined on them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> uses less memory than <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>double</code> is a reference type and <code>int</code> is not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> is built in and <code>double</code> is from a library.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "a type is just a set of values," what part of the definition are they missing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of operations defined on those values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The memory layout of the values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class that the values belong to.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say that operations are part of a type's definition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type is not just its values but also what you can do with them; the allowed operations are integral to what the type is.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It means you must implement all operations in every program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means a type's operations are stored alongside its values in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means every operation creates a new type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Data types in Java are either primitive or reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two broad categories of data types in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive types and reference types.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Numeric types and string types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Built-in types and user-defined types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static types and dynamic types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every Java data type either primitive or reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, every Java data type falls into one of these two categories.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No, some Java types like <code>String</code> are neither.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only primitives; reference types are a different language feature.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only classes we write ourselves are; library types are separate.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a type isn't primitive in Java, what must it be?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It must be a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be an <code>Object</code> subclass that is not a reference type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be a static type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java distinguish primitive types from reference types?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because they are stored and passed around differently: primitive values are held directly, while reference values are references to objects elsewhere in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because primitive types are older than reference types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because reference types are only used for collections.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because primitive types cannot be passed to methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Given a new Java type you've never seen, how would you classify it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether it's one of the built-in primitives (like <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>); if not, it's a reference type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Check whether it starts with a capital letter; if so, it's primitive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Check whether it has a literal syntax; if not, it's primitive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Check whether it extends <code>String</code>; if so, it's a reference type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The primitive data types used in this course, which represent numbers and logical values, are `int`, `double`, and `boolean`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which three primitive types are used in AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>, <code>float</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>char</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents whole numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents numbers with fractional parts?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>decimal</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which primitive type represents logical (true/false) values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>bool</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>bit</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do the primitive types <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code> collectively represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Numbers (whole and fractional) and logical values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Objects and primitive values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whole numbers and text values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Integers only.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The main reference types we use are `String`, arrays, `ArrayList` and other classes that we write ourselves all of which extend `Object`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name the main reference types used in AP CSA.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>, arrays, <code>ArrayList</code>, and classes we write ourselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, <code>boolean</code>, and <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>String</code> and <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code>, <code>Number</code>, and <code>Collection</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What class do all the reference types we use ultimately extend?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Class</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Reference</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>String</code> a primitive or reference type in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A primitive type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; it is a special type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive type that also has methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>ArrayList</code> and our own classes extend <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They inherit from <code>Object</code>, so they automatically get the methods defined on <code>Object</code> and can be treated as <code>Object</code> values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They become primitive types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They replace the behavior of <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They cannot add their own methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are <code>String</code> and an array similar in terms of Java's type system?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are reference types whose values are references to data stored elsewhere in memory, and both ultimately extend <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are primitive types with fixed sizes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are mutable sequences of characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are subclasses of <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The primitive data types and `String`s each have a syntax for writing literal values in Java programs, e.g. `1234`, `9.876`, `true`, and `"foobar"`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "literal" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A piece of syntax that directly represents a value in source code, such as <code>1234</code> or <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A variable that has been declared but not assigned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constant defined with the <code>final</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A value that cannot be changed at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which types have literal syntax in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The primitive types and <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the primitive types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Every class that extends <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>String</code> and <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an <code>int</code> literal and a <code>double</code> literal.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>1234</code> is an <code>int</code> literal; <code>9.876</code> is a <code>double</code> literal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>1234</code> is a <code>double</code> literal; <code>9.876</code> is an <code>int</code> literal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"1234" is an int literal; "9.876" is a double literal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int(1234)</code> and <code>double(9.876)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the difference between the literals <code>true</code> and <code>"true"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> is a <code>boolean</code> literal; <code>"true"</code> is a <code>String</code> literal containing four characters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are the same; both are <code>boolean</code> literals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code> is an identifier and the quoted form is a boolean literal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The quoted form evaluates to <code>true</code> automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write a literal value for an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, <code>ArrayList</code> has no literal syntax; you must construct one. Only primitives and <code>String</code> have literal syntax.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, you can write bracketed lists as an <code>ArrayList</code> literal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, brace-enclosed lists are <code>ArrayList</code> literals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, any reference type can be written as a literal.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Integer values in Java are represented by the data type `int`. `int`s are stored using four bytes (32 bits) of memory. Therefore, an `int` value must be in the range from `Integer.MIN_VALUE` to `Integer.MAX_ VALUE` inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How many bytes (and bits) of memory does an <code>int</code> occupy in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Four bytes, or 32 bits.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Two bytes, or 16 bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Eight bytes, or 64 bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One byte, or 8 bits.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the range of valid <code>int</code> values in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>From 0 to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From <code>-2147483647</code> to <code>2147483647</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any whole number; <code>int</code> has no range limit.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the range of <code>int</code> bounded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because an <code>int</code> is stored in only 32 bits of memory, there are finitely many values it can represent.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java's compiler enforces a maximum size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM chooses a new range on each run.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> values are stored as text.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents integer values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>: which one has a limited range, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both have limits because both use a fixed number of bits, but <code>int</code> in particular is capped by its 32-bit range between <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> and <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>double</code> has a limited range, because of its precision.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither has a limited range; both can represent any number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> is unlimited; <code>double</code> is limited by memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If an `int` expression would evaluate to a numeric value outside of the possible range for `int`, an overflow occur resulting in a mathematically incorrect `int` value. (For instance `Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1` evaluates to `Integer.MIN_VALUE`.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is integer overflow in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When an <code>int</code> expression produces a value outside the legal <code>int</code> range, it wraps around to a mathematically incorrect <code>int</code> value instead of raising an error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When an <code>int</code> variable is assigned a <code>double</code> value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the JVM runs out of memory for integers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When two <code>int</code>s are divided and produce a fractional result.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE + 1</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws an <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an <code>int</code> computation exceeds <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows, producing an incorrect <code>int</code> value rather than throwing an exception.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program crashes with an <code>OutOfMemoryError</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The value is automatically promoted to a <code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error is reported.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does Java throw an exception on <code>int</code> overflow?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the expression silently evaluates to a wrong <code>int</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, it throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, it throws <code>OverflowException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only in debug mode.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Your program multiplies two large <code>int</code>s and gets a negative result. What likely happened?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The mathematically correct result overflowed the <code>int</code> range and wrapped around, producing an incorrect (possibly negative) value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The JVM rounded the result to fit in 32 bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The result was truncated to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One of the operands was secretly a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Numbers with fractional parts are represented by the data type `double`. A `double` is stored in a 64-bit representation that encodes a significand, and exponent, and a sign, similar to the way scientific notation works.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents numbers with fractional parts?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>decimal</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many bits does a <code>double</code> occupy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>64 bits.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>32 bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>128 bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>16 bits.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What three parts encode a <code>double</code>'s value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A significand, an exponent, and a sign.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A numerator, a denominator, and a sign.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A mantissa, a base, and a length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>High bits, low bits, and a parity bit.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>A <code>double</code>'s representation is similar to what mathematical notation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scientific notation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Fractional notation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Roman numerals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Binary notation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> store their values.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> uses 32 bits as a plain two's complement integer; <code>double</code> uses 64 bits split into a sign, an exponent, and a significand, like scientific notation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use 32 bits; <code>double</code> just interprets them differently.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code> uses a string-like representation while <code>int</code> uses bits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> uses scientific notation while <code>double</code> uses two's complement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Logical values (true and false) are represented by the `boolean` data type. There are only two `boolean` values: written as `true` and `false`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which Java type represents logical values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>bool</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>, using 0 and 1.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many distinct <code>boolean</code> values exist in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Exactly two: <code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Three: <code>true</code>, <code>false</code>, and <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Four, including <code>yes</code> and <code>no</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any number; it can be any integer.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are the two <code>boolean</code> values written as literals?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>TRUE</code> and <code>FALSE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code> and <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The quoted string forms of true and false.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>"true"</code> a valid <code>boolean</code> value in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>"true"</code> is a <code>String</code> literal. The <code>boolean</code> literal is just <code>true</code>, with no quotes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it is automatically converted to <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only inside conditions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when Java is in strict mode.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>boolean</code> a useful type to have built into the language?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because logical true/false values are fundamental to control flow (like <code>if</code> and <code>while</code> conditions), so the language gives them a dedicated type with exactly two values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because logical values take less memory than integers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because otherwise every condition would need a helper class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>boolean</code> is faster than comparing integers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All the other data types we will use are reference data types which means the values that are stored in variables and passed to and returned from methods are references to where the real value lives in memory.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "reference" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value that points to where an object actually lives in memory, rather than containing the object itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A primitive value that counts how many variables share an object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A number that uniquely identifies a class in the JVM.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A pointer to a primitive value in the stack.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you assign a reference-type value to a variable, what is actually stored in the variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the object's location in memory, not the object itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the object is stored in the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The object's class name is stored in the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing; reference variables are empty until read.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What gets passed to a method when its parameter is a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the object, so the method can access the same object in memory that the caller has.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the entire object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The name of the variable holding the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class of the object, not the object itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does storing a reference-type value differ from storing a primitive value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A primitive variable directly holds the value; a reference variable holds a reference pointing to where the real value lives in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both hold the value directly; there is no difference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive variable stores a reference; a reference variable stores the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive variable stores a class name; a reference stores data.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two variables hold references to the same object, what happens when one modifies the object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both variables see the change, because they refer to the same underlying object in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the variable that made the change sees it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The change is rolled back because objects are immutable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java makes a copy so the other variable is unaffected.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`null` is a special reference value that represents "no object". It can be written as a literal value as `null`. It is the default value for uninitialized member variables and the unitialized elements of arrays of reference types such as `String[]`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>null</code> represent in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A special reference value meaning "no object."</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The integer value zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An empty <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A placeholder for a primitive that has not been assigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you write <code>null</code> as a literal in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just as <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As <code>NULL</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As the string form of null.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As <code>None</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of an uninitialized reference-type member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An empty string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile-time error to leave it uninitialized.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What values do the elements of a newly created <code>String[]</code> contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>, since the elements of an array of a reference type default to <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Empty strings.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whatever was previously in that memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Zero, because that's the default for all types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>null</code> a primitive value or a reference value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference value: a special one that refers to no object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A primitive value with no numeric meaning.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; <code>null</code> is a keyword, not a value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive value of type <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using the dot operator to call a method or access an instance variable on a `null` value causes a `NullPointerException` to be thrown.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you call a method on a <code>null</code> value?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>NullReferenceException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IllegalArgumentException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>RuntimeException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which operator triggers a <code>NullPointerException</code> when used on <code>null</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The dot operator (<code>.</code>), when used to call a method or access an instance variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The assignment operator (<code>=</code>).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>new</code> operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The equality operator (<code>==</code>).</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>null.length()</code> fail?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>null</code> refers to no object, so there's nothing for the dot operator to call a method on; Java throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>length()</code> is not defined on all reference types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>null</code> has no <code>length()</code> method of its own.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler rejects it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You get a <code>NullPointerException</code> on a line like <code>s.foo()</code>. What does that tell you about <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> was <code>null</code> at that moment, so the dot operator had no object to act on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> was never declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the <code>foo</code> method does not exist.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> held an empty string at that moment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does accessing an instance variable via the dot operator on <code>null</code> also throw a <code>NullPointerException</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; any use of the dot operator on a <code>null</code> reference, whether for a method call or field access, throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; only method calls on <code>null</code> throw it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; field accesses on <code>null</code> return <code>null</code> instead.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for <code>public</code> fields.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Variables</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each variable has associated memory that is used to hold its value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does every variable have associated with it to hold its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where is a variable's value actually stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In memory associated with that variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In the source file where it is declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On the heap, regardless of variable kind.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the variable's name itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you declare <code>int x = 5;</code>, what happens behind the scenes with memory?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Memory is set aside for <code>x</code>, and the value <code>5</code> is stored there.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nothing; <code>5</code> is stored directly in the source file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to <code>5</code> is created on the heap.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x</code> is added to a global symbol table without allocating memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a variable exist without any memory backing it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Every variable has memory associated with it to hold its value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, if it is declared but never used.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, <code>final</code> variables have no backing memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, local variables exist only as names.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the relationship between a variable and memory?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable is a name for a piece of memory that holds its value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A variable is a copy of a region of memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A variable is an address in memory with no value attached.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are unrelated; variables are purely a source-level concept.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The memory associated with a variable of a primitive type holds the actual representation of the primitive value while the memory associated with a variable holding a reference type holds a reference to the actual data which exists somewhere else in the computer's memory.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the memory of a primitive-type variable hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The actual representation of the primitive value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the primitive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class of the primitive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The variable's name and type, but not its value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the memory of a reference-type variable hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the actual data, which lives elsewhere in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The actual object, inline.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the object's class name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the object shared with other references.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do primitive and reference variables differ in what their memory stores?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive variables store the value itself; reference variables store a reference (pointer) to data stored elsewhere.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>There is no difference in how they are stored.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitive variables store a reference; reference variables store the value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitive variables store the value on the heap; reference variables on the stack.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you write <code>int a = 42;</code>, where does the number <code>42</code> live?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Directly in the memory for <code>a</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On the heap, with a reference in <code>a</code>'s memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inside the class file, not in the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a special integer pool shared across the program.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you write <code>String s = "hi";</code>, what exactly is stored in the memory for <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to a <code>String</code> object that exists somewhere else in memory, not the characters themselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The two characters of the string directly inline.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the literal in the source file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length of the string, <code>2</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A minimal variable declaration contains a type and a name.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two required parts of a minimal variable declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type and a name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A type and an initial value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A name and an access modifier.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An access modifier and a type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>int x;</code> a legal variable declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It has both required parts: a type (<code>int</code>) and a name (<code>x</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No, it is missing an initial value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No, it is missing an access modifier.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if it appears inside a class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's missing from the "declaration" <code>x;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type. A declaration needs both a type and a name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The initial value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An access modifier.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a minimal declaration require an initial value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only a type and a name are required; initialization is optional.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, otherwise it is a compile-time error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for reference types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, for member variables but not local variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which parts of <code>double price = 9.99;</code> are the minimum required for a declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type <code>double</code> and the name <code>price</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>, <code>price</code>, and <code>9.99</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>price</code> and <code>9.99</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>price</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The type of a variable determines what kind of values we can assign to the variable and what kind of value it produces when used as an expression.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a variable's type determine?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What values can be assigned to it and what kind of value it produces when used as an expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>How much memory the variable uses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the variable is local or member.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The variable's initial value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you assign <code>"hello"</code> to an <code>int</code> variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the variable's type restricts what values can be assigned to it, and <code>"hello"</code> isn't an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code>s are reference types and <code>int</code>s are not stored on the heap.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the value is longer than an <code>int</code> can hold.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> variables cannot be reassigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is declared <code>double</code>, what kind of value does the expression <code>x</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> value, because <code>double</code> extends <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> representation of the number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to a <code>Double</code> object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>A variable's type controls two things. What are they?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What values may be assigned to the variable, and the type of value the variable produces when used as an expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>How much memory it uses and whether it is <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its name and its scope.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its initial value and its access modifier.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the type of a variable affect how the compiler checks assignments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler only allows assignments of values compatible with the variable's declared type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The compiler ignores types and lets any assignment work at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler only checks types for member variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Types are only checked at runtime, not at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The name of a variable allows us to refer to it in assignment expression and as a value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the purpose of a variable's name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets us refer to the variable in assignments and as a value in expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It tells the compiler how much memory to reserve.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It determines the variable's type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is only used for error messages.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>x = x + 1;</code>, what role does the name <code>x</code> play on each side?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the left, it refers to the variable being assigned; on the right, it refers to the variable's current value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On both sides it refers to the variable's memory address.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On the left it refers to the value; on the right it refers to the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both sides are the same; the name is just repeated.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do variables need names?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So we can refer to them in code to assign to them or use their values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So the JVM can find them in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So they can be displayed in the debugger.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So the compiler can assign them unique addresses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two ways you use a variable's name in code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In an assignment (to set its value) and as a value in an expression (to read it).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Declaring it and deleting it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Reading it and printing it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a method name and as a class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If variables had no names, what would become impossible?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Referring to them in assignments or expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Declaring them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Storing their values in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using them as method parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Two variables can hold references to the same object which allows changes made to the object via one variable to be visible via the other variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is aliasing in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When two variables hold references to the same object, so changes through one are visible through the other.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When two variables have the same name in different scopes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When one variable is copied into another.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a variable refers to itself recursively.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> refer to the same object and you mutate the object via <code>a</code>, what does <code>b</code> see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The same change, because both refer to the same underlying object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>b</code> still sees the old unchanged state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the change if <code>b</code> is reassigned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the change, kept separately from <code>a</code>'s object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two different variables ever affect the same underlying object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, if they both hold references to the same object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; each variable always has its own object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the object is a primitive wrapper.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only through explicit method calls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can changing an object through one variable affect another variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because reference variables can point to the same object, so there is only one object being modified.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java automatically synchronizes variables with the same value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because variable assignment triggers a deep copy by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM broadcasts changes to all variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does this aliasing behavior apply to primitive variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Primitive variables store their own copy of the value, so changing one does not affect another.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, primitive aliases behave the same way.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for <code>int</code> variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when primitives are declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a variable is declared <code>final</code>, its value cannot be changed once it is initialized.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does declaring a variable <code>final</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once the variable is initialized, its value cannot be changed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Its value is fixed at compile time and cannot depend on input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be a primitive type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It cannot be read after initialization.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to assign to a <code>final</code> variable after initialization?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler reports an error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The value silently changes without error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime exception is thrown.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The assignment is ignored and the old value is kept.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a programmer mark a variable <code>final</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To prevent its value from being changed, making the code safer and intent clearer.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make the variable run faster at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To allow the JVM to store it in special memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>final</code> variables use less memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a <code>final</code> variable be given a value at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, exactly once, when it is initialized.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No, <code>final</code> variables can never have a value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if they are member variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the value <code>0</code> or <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a normal variable and a <code>final</code> variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A normal variable can be reassigned any number of times; a <code>final</code> variable can only be assigned once.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A normal variable exists only inside methods; a <code>final</code> variable is a class member.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A normal variable is stored on the stack; a <code>final</code> variable on the heap.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A normal variable holds a reference; a <code>final</code> variable holds a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>There are two kinds of variables in Java: local and member. Member variables, are further divided into instance and static variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two main kinds of variables in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Local variables and member variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Primitive variables and reference variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static variables and instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public variables and private variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Member variables are divided into which two subcategories?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables and static variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Local variables and parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public variables and private variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Final variables and non-final variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where do the three variable categories fit in the hierarchy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Top level: local vs. member. Member variables split further into instance and static.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>All three are at the same level: local, instance, and static.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Top level: static vs. instance. Instance variables split into local and member.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Top level: primitive vs. reference. Each splits into local and member.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an instance variable a local variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Instance variables are member variables, not local variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, all instance variables are local to their instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, if declared inside a method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on whether the class is <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the difference between a member variable and a local variable at a high level?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Member variables belong to a class (instance or static); local variables belong to a method or constructor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Member variables are always <code>final</code>; local variables are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Local variables are stored on the heap; member variables on the stack.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Member variables can only hold primitives; local variables can hold any type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Local variables are declared in the body of methods and constructors. These variables may only be used within the method or constructor where they are declared. They are not marked as either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> because they are not accessible at all outside the method or constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are local variables declared?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the body of a method or constructor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At the top level of a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inside any block, including class bodies.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in the <code>main</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the scope of a local variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only within the method or constructor where it is declared.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The entire class that contains the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The entire package the class belongs to.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the line on which it is declared.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't local variables be marked <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because they aren't accessible outside the method or constructor at all, so access modifiers would be meaningless.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because local variables are always <code>public</code> by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> are reserved for classes only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because access modifiers would make them static.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can one method see a local variable declared in another method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Local variables only exist inside the method or constructor that declares them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, if both methods are in the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as the variable is <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the methods are <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>private int x;</code> declared inside a method body legal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Local variables cannot have <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> modifiers.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>private</code> restricts it to that method only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only inside a <code>static</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the enclosing class is also <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Parameters declared in a method or constructor are also local variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of variable is a method parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A local variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A member variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An instance variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How long does a method parameter exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only while the method or constructor is executing, like any other local variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As long as the program is running.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Until the containing object is garbage collected.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Until the parameter is explicitly set to <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a parameter be marked <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, because parameters are local variables and local variables can't have access modifiers.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, parameters use the same access modifiers as members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method is <code>public</code> itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only <code>public</code> is allowed, not <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>void greet(String name) { ... }</code>, what is <code>name</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A local variable (a parameter) of the <code>greet</code> method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A member variable of the enclosing class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constant, because parameters cannot be reassigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are parameters similar to other local variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are scoped to the method or constructor and are not accessible outside it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are declared at the top of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are stored as instance variables of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are implicitly marked <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When there is a local variable with the same name as a member variable, the name will refer to the local variable instead of the member variable. This is called "shadowing".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is shadowing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a local variable has the same name as a member variable, causing the name to refer to the local variable instead of the member.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When a member variable has the same name as another member variable in a superclass.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a variable is declared but never used.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When two local variables have the same name in nested scopes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method has a local variable <code>x</code> and the class has a member <code>x</code>, which does the unqualified name <code>x</code> refer to inside the method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The local variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The member variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both; Java reads from whichever was assigned most recently.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile-time error to have both with the same name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What takes precedence when a local and member variable share a name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The local variable shadows (hides) the member variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The member variable always wins over a local.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; Java reports a name conflict error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whichever was declared first in the source file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does shadowing remove the member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it just means the unqualified name refers to the local variable within that scope.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the member variable is deleted for the duration of the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the member variable becomes <code>null</code> until the method returns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It removes the member variable permanently from the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can shadowing be confusing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the same name refers to different variables depending on the scope, which can hide the member variable unintentionally.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because shadowing is only allowed with <code>final</code> variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler randomizes which variable is referenced.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because shadowed variables produce a warning and fail to compile.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a instance member variable is shadowed by a local variable it can be referred to with an explicit <code>this.</code> as in <code>this.x</code>. A static member variable can referred to with an explicit <code>ClassName.</code> as in <code>ClassName.SOME_VARIABLE</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you refer to a shadowed instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>this.</code> before the name, as in <code>this.x</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>super.</code> before the name, as in <code>super.x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the class name, as in <code>ClassName.x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You cannot access a shadowed instance variable from within the method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you refer to a shadowed static variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the class name, as in <code>ClassName.SOME_VARIABLE</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>this.</code> before the name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>static.</code> before the name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>super.</code> before the name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a constructor <code>Point(int x) { this.x = x; }</code>, what does <code>this.x</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The instance variable <code>x</code>, as opposed to the parameter <code>x</code> that shadows it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The parameter <code>x</code>, assigning it to itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new local variable <code>x</code> being declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static variable named <code>x</code> of the <code>Point</code> class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>this.</code> needed in some assignments but not others?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's only needed when a local variable (often a parameter) shadows the instance variable with the same name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It's only needed when the instance variable is <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's only needed inside static methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's needed whenever you assign to any instance variable, shadowed or not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare disambiguating a shadowed instance variable vs. a shadowed static variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For an instance variable use <code>this.name</code>; for a static variable use <code>ClassName.name</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use <code>this.</code>, since static members are also part of <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>ClassName.name</code> for instance variables and <code>this.name</code> for static variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Instance variables cannot be shadowed, so only static variables need disambiguation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Member variable are declared at the top-level of a class and can be marked as <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>. Usually variables will be marked <code>private</code> though sometimes classes define important constants as <code>public static final</code> variables, for instance <code>Math.PI</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are member variables declared?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the top level of a class, outside any method or constructor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inside the <code>main</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In any block of the class, including inside methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in the constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What access modifiers can member variables have?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> or <code>private</code> (among others).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>None; member variables cannot have access modifiers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are most member variables marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To hide implementation details and keep object state under the control of the class itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>private</code> variables run faster.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>public</code> variables cannot be changed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler requires it for all member variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is it common to see a <code>public</code> member variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When defining a constant, declared as <code>public static final</code>, like <code>Math.PI</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When you need to access a variable from inside the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the variable is a temporary loop counter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the class extends another class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do the modifiers in <code>public static final double PI</code> each contribute?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> makes it accessible anywhere, <code>static</code> makes it belong to the class (not instances), and <code>final</code> makes it a constant that cannot be reassigned.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code> makes it private to the class, <code>static</code> makes it mutable, and <code>final</code> makes it an instance field.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code> makes it writable, <code>static</code> makes it local, and <code>final</code> makes it visible.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They all just make the variable load faster at startup.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An expression is any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value:</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any part of a program that can be evaluated to produce a value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A statement that performs an action but does not produce a value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any line of code that ends with a semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A sequence of keywords recognized by the compiler.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "evaluate" an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To compute the value that the expression produces.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To compile it into bytecode.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To check whether its syntax is valid.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To print its value to the console.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every part of a program an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only those parts that can be evaluated to produce a value are expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; every line of code is an expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, except for <code>import</code> statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside methods; outside methods, nothing is an expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a piece of code produces no value at all, can it be called an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. By definition an expression must produce a value when evaluated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as the code compiles.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the code has side effects like printing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; statements and expressions are the same thing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the idea of an expression useful when reading Java code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It gives us a uniform way to talk about any chunk of code that yields a value, regardless of how simple or complex it is.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because expressions are always faster than statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because only expressions can be debugged.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because expressions have no side effects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Literal values, e.g. <code>10</code> or <code>"foo"</code>, evaluate to the value they denote.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a literal value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value written directly in the source code, such as <code>10</code> or <code>"foo"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A variable whose value cannot change.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A string that represents a numeric constant.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword reserved by the compiler.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the literal <code>10</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The integer value 10 itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> containing the digits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>double</code> value <code>10.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to an <code>Integer</code> object wrapping 10.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when Java evaluates the literal <code>"foo"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It produces the string value <code>"foo"</code> that the literal denotes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It converts the literal into a character array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It creates a new empty <code>String</code> named <code>foo</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It looks up the variable <code>foo</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a literal to a variable as an expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal always evaluates to the same fixed value it denotes, while a variable evaluates to whatever value it currently holds.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A literal produces a reference; a variable produces a value directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A literal is evaluated only once; a variable is evaluated many times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Literals and variables behave identically when evaluated.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>42</code> by itself an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It is a literal expression that evaluates to the integer 42.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; expressions must contain at least one operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; a single literal is a statement, not an expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if it appears on the right side of an assignment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Variables, e.g. <code>x</code> or <code>Math.PI</code>, evaluate to the current value of of the variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a variable expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The current value stored in that variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the variable as a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The memory address of the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The type of the variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> holds 7 and later holds 12, what does the expression <code>x</code> evaluate to each time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to 7 the first time and 12 the second time, the current value at the moment of evaluation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>7 both times, because expressions cache their first result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>12 both times, because evaluation uses the final value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression produces a compile-time error because it changes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> a literal or a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is a variable (a named constant field), not a literal; it evaluates to the current value stored in that field.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A literal, because its value never changes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; <code>Math.PI</code> is a method call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A literal that is stored in the class file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate a variable that has never been assigned a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In Java, a local variable must be assigned before use or the code will not compile.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates to <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates to <code>0</code> for any type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a runtime <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we say a variable "evaluates" to its value rather than "is" its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the variable is a name, and evaluation is the step that looks up the current value associated with that name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because variables in Java are actually methods in disguise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java uses lazy evaluation for all variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because a variable is assigned a fresh object each time it appears.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method calls to non-<code>void</code> methods, e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code> or <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>, evaluate to the value returned by the method when called with the given arguments.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a non-<code>void</code> method call expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value returned by the method when invoked with the given arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the method itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>boolean</code> indicating whether the call succeeded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The name of the method as a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a call to a <code>void</code> method be used as an expression that produces a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>void</code> methods do not return a value, so such calls cannot be used where a value is required.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>void</code> methods return <code>null</code>, which is a value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the value is the last statement executed in the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only inside conditional expressions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> approximately equal to 1.4142135623730951, the value returned by the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>int</code> value <code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> approximation of the square root.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An exception, because 2 has no exact square root.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>s</code> is <code>"hello"</code>, what does <code>s.substring(1)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The string <code>"ello"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The single-character string containing the first letter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The four-letter string <code>hell</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>char</code> value of the second letter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the type of a method-call expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The declared return type of the method being called.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The types of the arguments passed to it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the call appears inside an assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class on which the method is defined.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Object instantiations via the <code>new</code> keyword, e.g. <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code>, evaluate to a reference to a newly created object that has been initialized by running the appropriate constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a <code>new</code> expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to a newly created object that has been initialized by running the appropriate constructor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The object itself, stored directly in the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the class's static state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The name of the class being instantiated.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the constructor play in evaluating a <code>new</code> expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It initializes the freshly allocated object before the reference is produced.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It allocates memory but does not touch the object's fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It determines the type of the resulting reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It runs after the reference is returned, not before.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</code> produce the object itself or a reference to it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the newly created object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The object itself, copied into the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> representing the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing; <code>new</code> does not produce a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if the constructor throws an exception during a <code>new</code> expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No reference is produced; the expression does not complete normally and the exception propagates.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The partially built object is returned anyway.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The exception is caught silently and <code>null</code> is returned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM retries the constructor up to three times.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a <code>new</code> expression to a literal expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal denotes a fixed value, while a <code>new</code> expression allocates and initializes a fresh object each time it is evaluated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>new</code> expression always produces the same reference on each call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same; literals use <code>new</code> internally.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A literal creates a new object each time; <code>new</code> reuses a cached one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Array access expressions, e.g <code>xs[0]</code>, evaluate to the value stored at the given position in the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does an array access expression evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value stored at the specified index in the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The length of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the array itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index used to access it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>xs</code> is <code>{10, 20, 30}</code>, what does <code>xs[0]</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>10, the element at index 0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>0, because indexing starts at 1 in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>30, the first element in the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the entire array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate <code>xs[i]</code> with an index outside the array's bounds?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>null</code> silently.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>0</code> or the default element value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The array automatically grows to include that index.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an array access expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element type of the array being indexed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Always <code>int</code>, regardless of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Always <code>Object</code>, since arrays are reference types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A special array-element type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the index in an array access itself an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any <code>int</code>-typed expression may be used as the index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; only literal integers are allowed as indices.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; indices must be variables, not expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the expression is a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compound expressions made up of expressions and operators, e.g. <code>x + 2</code>, evaluate to a value determined by the operator and its operands.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression made up of sub-expressions combined with operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An expression that uses more than one variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An expression that contains at least one method call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An expression that appears inside parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the value of a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The operator applied to the values produced by its operands.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The order in which operands were typed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The type of the variable it is assigned to.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of operands involved.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is 5, what does the compound expression <code>x + 2</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>7.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>25.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>52, because <code>+</code> concatenates with 2.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the operands of a compound expression themselves be compound expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Expressions nest, so operands can be arbitrarily complex sub-expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; operands of compound expressions must be literals or variables only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if they are enclosed in parentheses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only up to one level of nesting.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a compound expression different from a literal expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A literal is a single value written in code, while a compound expression combines multiple expressions with operators to compute a new value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A compound expression has no type, while a literal does.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Literals cannot be used inside compound expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compound expression always produces a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each expression has a type which is determined by the types of its sub-expressions and the operators involved. The type describes the kind of values it can produce.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Does every expression in Java have a type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Every expression has a type describing the kind of values it can produce.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; only variables and literals have types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only assignment expressions have types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the expression is used as an argument.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines the type of a compound expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The types of its sub-expressions together with the operators involved.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the type of the leftmost sub-expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The type of the variable the expression is assigned to.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the expression appears inside parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the "type" of an expression describe?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The kind of values the expression can produce when evaluated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The amount of memory the expression occupies.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The name the expression would have if stored in a variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the expression is a statement or not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is an <code>int</code>, what is the type of the expression <code>x + 2</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>, because both operands are <code>int</code> and <code>+</code> on two <code>int</code>s yields an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>, because all arithmetic produces <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>, because <code>+</code> concatenates.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It has no type; only variables have types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java care about the type of every expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So it can check at compile time that expressions are used in contexts where their values make sense.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So it can decide how much memory to allocate for each expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So it can print better error messages at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because types determine the order of evaluation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Anywhere a value of a given type is needed we can use any expression that produces values of that type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When Java needs a value of a given type, what kinds of code can supply it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any expression that produces values of that type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only a variable of that exact type; no other expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any literal of the right kind, but no compound expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any expression, regardless of type, as long as it compiles.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method parameter expects an <code>int</code>, can you pass <code>3 + 4</code> instead of just <code>7</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any <code>int</code>-typed expression, including <code>3 + 4</code>, works anywhere an <code>int</code> value is needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; only literal values can be passed as arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>3 + 4</code> is stored in a variable first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside <code>main</code>; other methods require literals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What principle lets us freely replace a literal with a more complex expression of the same type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Anywhere a value of a given type is needed, any expression producing that type may be used.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The principle of type erasure.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The principle of polymorphism.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The principle of single responsibility.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must match between an expression and the context where it is used?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The type of the expression must match the type required by the context.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The expression must be assigned to a variable before use.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression must be simpler than the context.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression must be a literal value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does this principle make programs composable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because simple expressions can be swapped for more complex ones of the same type without changing where they are used.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because it forces every expression to produce a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it removes the need for types entirely.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it means every piece of code runs in isolation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Arithmetic expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arithmetic expressions are expressions that produce an or <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an arithmetic expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression that produces an <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An expression that produces a <code>boolean</code> result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An expression that uses any arithmetic operator, regardless of the result type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An expression that contains at least one number literal.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two numeric types can an AP CSA arithmetic expression produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> and <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> and <code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> and <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code> only.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a <code>String</code> concatenation with <code>+</code> considered an arithmetic expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Arithmetic expressions produce numeric values, not strings.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>+</code> on strings counts as arithmetic.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because concatenation is a numeric operation internally.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when one operand is a number.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an arithmetic expression evaluate to a <code>boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Arithmetic expressions only produce <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; comparisons are arithmetic expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>true</code> is treated as <code>1</code> and <code>false</code> as <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only with the <code>%</code> operator.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>3 + 4.0</code> an arithmetic expression? What type does it produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, and it produces a <code>double</code> because one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, and it produces an <code>int</code> because the first operand is an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; mixing <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> is illegal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, and it produces a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The arithmetic operators consist of <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the five arithmetic operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>%</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>**</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, and <code>++</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>%</code> operator compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The remainder left after dividing the left operand by the right operand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The percentage of the left operand relative to the right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The integer quotient of dividing the operands.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The greatest common divisor of the operands.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>17 % 5</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>2.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>3.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>12.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>3.4.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>/</code> differ from <code>%</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>/</code> produces the quotient of a division, while <code>%</code> produces the remainder.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both produce the quotient; <code>%</code> is just a shorter form.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>/</code> works only on <code>double</code>s, while <code>%</code> works only on <code>int</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>%</code> produces the percentage; <code>/</code> produces the ratio.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>**</code> a Java arithmetic operator for exponentiation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java has no <code>**</code> operator; use <code>Math.pow</code> instead.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>**</code> raises the left operand to the power of the right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for <code>double</code> operands.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it is a shorthand for <code>Math.pow</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An arithmetic operation on two <code>int</code>s will evaluate to an <code>int</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an arithmetic expression whose operands are both <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>, because arithmetic always widens.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>, to avoid overflow.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whichever operand was written first.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>7 / 2</code> evaluate to in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3, because integer division truncates toward zero.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>3.5, because Java uses floating-point division.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>3, because it rounds up.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code>, because the result is not exact.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>1 / 2</code> give 0 in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both operands are <code>int</code>, so the result is an <code>int</code> and the fractional part is dropped.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because 1 is less than 2, so the division is undefined.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java rounds all divisions down toward negative infinity.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because both are promoted to <code>double</code>, so the result is 0.5.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you force a floating-point division between two <code>int</code> variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Cast at least one operand to <code>double</code>, e.g. <code>(double) a / b</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use the <code>/.</code> operator instead of <code>/</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declare the variables as <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Wrap the expression in <code>Math.div()</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the result type of <code>3 + 4</code> and <code>3 + 4.0</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3 + 4</code> is an <code>int</code>; <code>3 + 4.0</code> is a <code>double</code> because one operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are <code>double</code>, because <code>+</code> always produces a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are <code>int</code>, because addition does not change types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>3 + 4</code> is a <code>double</code>; <code>3 + 4.0</code> is an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An arithmetic operation with at least one <code>double</code> value will evaluate to a <code>double</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of an arithmetic expression that has at least one <code>double</code> operand?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>, unless all operands are <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whichever type has the larger operand.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>, a common supertype of both.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>7 / 2.0</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3.5</code> as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>3</code> as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>3.0</code> as a <code>double</code>, because integer division happens first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you mix an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> with <code>+</code>, what happens to the <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is automatically converted to a <code>double</code> before the addition is performed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>double</code> is truncated to an <code>int</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The operation is performed in <code>int</code> arithmetic and the result is cast to <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error is reported for mixing types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the results of <code>5 / 2</code> and <code>5.0 / 2</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5 / 2</code> is the <code>int</code> 2; <code>5.0 / 2</code> is the <code>double</code> 2.5.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are the <code>int</code> 2.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are the <code>double</code> 2.5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>5 / 2</code> is 2.5; <code>5.0 / 2</code> is 2.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does adding even a single <code>double</code> operand "upgrade" the result type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So no precision is lost: the <code>int</code> can be represented as a <code>double</code>, but not vice versa.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> arithmetic is too slow to be used by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM cannot store mixed-type expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java always promotes to the smaller type to save memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Operators can be used to construct compound expressions.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do operators let you build out of simpler expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compound expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>New variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of using operators to build a compound expression from smaller ones.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(a + b) * c</code> combines <code>a</code>, <code>b</code>, and <code>c</code> using <code>+</code> and <code>*</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>a + b * c</code>, which is just a sequence of simple expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int result = a + b * c;</code>, which is a declaration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>System.out.println(a)</code>, which calls a method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the operands of a compound expression themselves be compound expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, expressions can be nested to any depth.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; operands must be literals or variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for compound expressions using <code>+</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the inner expressions are enclosed in braces.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you combine two <code>int</code> expressions with an arithmetic operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You get another <code>int</code>-typed expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code>-typed expression, because addition widens.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code>, because <code>+</code> concatenates.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing; mixing expressions is not allowed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are compound expressions useful?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They let you compute complex values in a single step rather than breaking every calculation into separate statements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because they always run faster than simple expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM optimizes them specially.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because they remove the need for variables entirely.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>During evaluation, operands are associated with operators according to operator precedence to determine how they are grouped.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What rule decides how operands and operators are grouped during evaluation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Operator precedence.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Left-to-right evaluation order only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The order in which variables were declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length of the sub-expressions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>2 + 3 * 4</code>, which operation happens first, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3 * 4</code>, because <code>*</code> has higher precedence than <code>+</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>2 + 3</code>, because <code>+</code> appears first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>3 * 4</code>, because operators are evaluated right-to-left.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>2 + 3</code>, because addition always happens first in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>14.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>20.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>24.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>9.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you override the default precedence in an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use parentheses to explicitly group sub-expressions, e.g. <code>(2 + 3) * 4</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use curly braces to group sub-expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the <code>first</code> keyword before a sub-expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Precedence cannot be overridden in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>2 + 3 * 4</code> with <code>(2 + 3) * 4</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first evaluates to 14 using operator precedence; the second evaluates to 20 because parentheses force the addition first.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 20; parentheses have no effect.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 14; Java ignores parentheses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first evaluates to 20; the second evaluates to 14.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An attempt to divide an integer by zero will result in an <code>ArithmeticException</code> to occur.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you divide an <code>int</code> by zero in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArithmeticException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It silently returns <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>Infinity</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is integer division by zero a compile-time error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is a runtime error that throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the compiler detects it and refuses to compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only when both operands are literals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on the Java version.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception type signals integer division by zero?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>DivideByZeroException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>NumberFormatException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IllegalArgumentException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>%</code> with a right operand of zero throw the same exception as <code>/</code> does?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>int</code> modulo by zero also throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; <code>%</code> by zero silently returns 0.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; <code>%</code> by zero returns <code>NaN</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for <code>double</code> modulo, not <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare integer division by zero with <code>double</code> division by zero.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Integer division by zero throws <code>ArithmeticException</code>; <code>double</code> division by zero yields <code>Infinity</code>, <code>-Infinity</code>, or <code>NaN</code> instead.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both throw <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Integer division by zero returns <code>Infinity</code>; <code>double</code> division throws.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both silently return <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The casting operators <code>(int)</code> and <code>(double)</code> produce numeric values of the specified type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do the casting operators <code>(int)</code> and <code>(double)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They produce a numeric value of the specified type from their operand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They check whether a value is of the specified type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They create a new variable of the specified type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They round a value to the nearest integer or double.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the syntax for casting a value <code>x</code> to <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(double) x</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x.toDouble()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>cast(x, double)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a cast change the original variable's value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It produces a new value of the target type; the original variable is unchanged.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it permanently converts the variable to the new type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the variable is reassigned to the cast value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for reference-type casts, not numeric ones.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the type of the expression <code>(int) 3.7</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>, because the operand is a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on context.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>, a common supertype.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare casting with automatic conversion.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Casting is an explicit conversion written by the programmer; automatic conversion happens implicitly when Java widens a narrower numeric type to a wider one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are the same thing; just different words.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Automatic conversion is explicit; casting is implicit.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Casting only works on references; automatic conversion only on primitives.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Casting a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code> produces an <code>int</code> with any fractional part (the digits to the right of the decimal point) truncated.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does casting a <code>double</code> to an <code>int</code> do to the fractional part?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It truncates it, dropping any digits to the right of the decimal point.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It rounds the fractional part to the nearest integer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws an exception if there is a fractional part.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It preserves the fractional part by storing it separately.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int) 3.7</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>4, because it rounds up.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>4, because casting rounds to nearest.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>3.7, unchanged.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int) -3.7</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>-3, because truncation drops the fractional part rather than rounding down.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>-4, because casting rounds down.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>-4, because it rounds toward negative infinity.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>-3.7, unchanged.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is truncation the same as rounding?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Truncation simply discards the fractional part, while rounding chooses the nearest integer.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; they are synonyms in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; both discard the fractional part.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for positive numbers; for negatives they differ.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>(int) 3.9</code> and <code>Math.round(3.9)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(int) 3.9</code> truncates to 3, while <code>Math.round(3.9)</code> rounds to 4.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 3.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 4.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>(int) 3.9</code> is 4; <code>Math.round(3.9)</code> is 3.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Casting an <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> produces a double with the same mathematical value since all <code>int</code> values are exactly representable as a <code>double</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does casting an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> with the same mathematical value as the original <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> with the same value, since <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> are interchangeable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code> that has been rounded to the nearest whole number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to a new <code>Double</code> object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is no precision lost when casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because every <code>int</code> value is exactly representable as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM stores both types in the same memory slot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the cast doesn't actually do anything at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>double</code> ignores the sign bit of <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(double) 5</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>5</code> as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error, because 5 is not a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The string form <code>5.0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the safety of casting <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> with casting <code>double</code> to <code>int</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> to <code>double</code> preserves the value exactly; <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> can lose the fractional part through truncation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are equally safe; no information is ever lost.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code> to <code>int</code> is lossless; <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> can lose precision.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither is safe; both require a runtime check.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>a</code> is 5 and <code>b</code> is 2, how does <code>(double) a / b</code> differ from <code>a / b</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(double) a / b</code> evaluates to 2.5, while <code>a / b</code> evaluates to the <code>int</code> 2.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 2.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both evaluate to 2.5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>(double) a / b</code> evaluates to 2; <code>a / b</code> evaluates to 2.5.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using an <code>int</code> where a <code>double</code> is expected, without a cast, causes the <code>int</code> value to be automatically converted to a <code>double</code> value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you use an <code>int</code> where a <code>double</code> is expected?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> is automatically converted to a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error is reported.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>double</code> is automatically converted to an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>int</code> is wrapped in an <code>Integer</code> object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an explicit cast needed to pass an <code>int</code> to a method expecting a <code>double</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java performs the conversion automatically.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; Java always requires an explicit cast between numeric types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the method expects a reference type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in <code>static</code> methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>double d = 5;</code>, what value does <code>d</code> hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5.0</code>, the <code>double</code> value automatically converted from the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>5</code> as an <code>int</code>, because the literal is an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error, because 5 is not a valid <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>, because no <code>double</code> was provided.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java allow automatic <code>int</code>-to-<code>double</code> conversion but not the reverse?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because widening from <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> is lossless, while narrowing from <code>double</code> to <code>int</code> can lose the fractional part.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>double</code> is faster than <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> share the same memory layout.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java prefers floating-point arithmetic by default.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>Math.sqrt(9)</code>, what happens to the <code>int</code> argument?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is automatically converted to the <code>double</code> <code>9.0</code> before <code>sqrt</code> runs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error is reported because <code>sqrt</code> expects a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is rounded to the nearest <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is passed as-is, and <code>sqrt</code> handles the conversion internally.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values of type <code>double</code> can be rounded to the nearest <code>int</code> by <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code> or <code>(int)(x - 0.5)</code> for negative numbers.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How can you round a positive <code>double</code> <code>x</code> to the nearest <code>int</code> using a cast?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>(int) x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>Math.floor(x)</code> cast to <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>(int)(x * 2) / 2</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code> round to the nearest integer for positive <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Adding 0.5 shifts values at or above the halfway point into the next integer before truncation drops the fractional part.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java's cast operator automatically rounds when you add 0.5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because 0.5 is the smallest <code>double</code> value that can affect an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because adding 0.5 makes all values even, which rounds correctly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What expression rounds a negative <code>double</code> <code>x</code> to the nearest <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>(int)(x - 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>(int)(x + 0.5)</code>; the same formula works for negatives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>(int)(-x + 0.5)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-(int)(x + 0.5)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you subtract 0.5 instead of adding it for negative numbers?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because truncation rounds toward zero, so for negatives you need to push the value further from zero before truncating to get nearest-integer rounding.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because adding 0.5 to a negative number has no effect.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the cast operator reverses direction for negative numbers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>double</code>s cannot be negative.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>(int)(3.7 + 0.5)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>4.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>3.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>4.2.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Boolean expressions</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A boolean expression is any expression that results in a `boolean` value. The values used in the expression may be `boolean`s or other kinds of values. For instance, `x &gt; 10` is a `boolean` expression even though `x` must be a number and `a == b` always evaluates to a `boolean` even though `a` and `b` could be any type of values.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What defines a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any expression that results in a <code>boolean</code> value, regardless of the types of the sub-expressions involved.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Any expression whose sub-expressions are all <code>boolean</code> values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any expression that appears as the condition of an <code>if</code> statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any expression that uses the logical operators <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, <code>||</code>, or <code>\!</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>x &gt; 10</code> a boolean expression even though <code>x</code> is a number?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. The operands are numeric, but the result of the comparison is a <code>boolean</code>, so the whole expression is a boolean expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. Because <code>x</code> is numeric, the whole expression is treated as a numeric expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if <code>x</code> has been explicitly cast to a <code>boolean</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. <code>&gt;</code> produces an <code>int</code>, not a <code>boolean</code>, in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you evaluate <code>a == b</code> where <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It still produces a <code>boolean</code> result, so it counts as a boolean expression even though neither operand is a <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It produces a <code>String</code> result representing whether the two match.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile error, because <code>==</code> cannot be applied to reference types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>true</code> only if the two <code>String</code>s have the same characters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Suppose a method is declared to return <code>boolean</code>. Is a call to it a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Any expression whose result is a <code>boolean</code> value qualifies, including method calls that return <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. A method call is a statement, not an expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the call appears directly inside an <code>if</code> condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. You have to compare the return value to <code>true</code> with <code>==</code> first.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a boolean expression with an arithmetic expression.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are expressions that produce values, but a boolean expression specifically produces a <code>boolean</code> (<code>true</code> or <code>false</code>), while an arithmetic expression produces a numeric value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Boolean expressions use only logical operators; arithmetic expressions use only <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, and <code>/</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same thing, just evaluated in different contexts.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Boolean expressions can appear anywhere, but arithmetic expressions can only appear on the right side of an assignment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Boolean expressions are made from `boolean` literals, `boolean` variables, methods that return `boolean`, and expressions involving logical operators, equality operators, relational operators.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the building blocks of a boolean expression in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code> literals, <code>boolean</code> variables, methods returning <code>boolean</code>, and expressions using logical, equality, or relational operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>boolean</code> literals and <code>boolean</code> variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any numeric values combined with arithmetic operators.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only method calls that return <code>boolean</code> combined with <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two <code>boolean</code> literals in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> and <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>TRUE</code> and <code>FALSE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code> and <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>yes</code> and <code>no</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which three categories of operators can produce a <code>boolean</code> result?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Logical operators, equality operators, and relational operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Arithmetic, logical, and assignment operators.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Logical, relational, and arithmetic operators.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Equality, relational, and assignment operators.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method returns an <code>int</code>, can a call to it by itself be a boolean expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Only a method that returns <code>boolean</code> produces a boolean expression on its own; an <code>int</code>-returning call would need to be combined with a relational or equality operator.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Java automatically converts nonzero <code>int</code> values to <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because any method call counts as a boolean expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the returned <code>int</code> is <code>0</code> or <code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a boolean expression that uses a <code>boolean</code> variable combined with a relational operator.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Something like <code>done || x &lt; 10</code>, where <code>done</code> is a <code>boolean</code> variable and <code>x &lt; 10</code> is a relational expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x + 10 &amp;&amp; done</code>, combining an arithmetic expression with a boolean variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>done = x &lt; 10</code>, assigning a relational result to a boolean variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>done &amp;&amp; x + 1</code>, using an int and a boolean together.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Logical operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Logical operators operate on `boolean` values and produce a `boolean` value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values do logical operators take as operands, and what do they produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They operate on <code>boolean</code> values and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They take numeric values and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They take <code>boolean</code> values and produce a numeric value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They take any kind of value and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you apply <code>&amp;&amp;</code> to two <code>int</code> values in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Logical operators require <code>boolean</code> operands; using <code>int</code>s produces a compile error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Java treats nonzero <code>int</code>s as <code>true</code>, like C.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if both <code>int</code>s are <code>0</code> or <code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you first cast each <code>int</code> to <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result type of <code>a || b</code> when <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> are <code>boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Boolean</code> (the wrapper class), not <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on whether either operand is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast a logical operator with a relational operator in terms of input types.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Relational operators take numeric operands and return <code>boolean</code>; logical operators take <code>boolean</code> operands and return <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both take <code>boolean</code> operands and return <code>boolean</code>, but relational operators also allow numeric operands.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Logical operators take numeric operands; relational operators take <code>boolean</code> operands.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both take numeric operands, but logical operators return <code>int</code> and relational operators return <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can logical operators be chained, like <code>a &amp;&amp; b &amp;&amp; c</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each application produces a <code>boolean</code>, which is a valid operand for the next logical operator.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java specially rewrites chained logical operators into a single call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because logical operators have the highest precedence, so they always associate left-to-right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>&amp;&amp;</code> accepts any number of operands, not just two.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The logical operators in Java are `!` (not), `&amp;&amp;` (and), and `||` (or).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name the three logical operators in Java.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> (not), <code>&amp;&amp;</code> (and), and <code>||</code> (or).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;</code> (and), <code>|</code> (or), and <code>^</code> (xor).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>and</code>, <code>or</code>, and <code>not</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!</code>, <code>?</code>, and <code>:</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which logical operator is unary?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> (not); it takes a single <code>boolean</code> operand and flips its value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>||</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>\!</code> are unary.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>true &amp;&amp; false</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>. <code>&amp;&amp;</code> is true only when both operands are true.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>. <code>&amp;&amp;</code> is true if either operand is true.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>true</code> and <code>false</code> cannot be combined.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>, because the first operand is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>false || true</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>. <code>||</code> is true when at least one operand is true.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code>, because the first operand is <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code>. <code>||</code> requires both operands to be true.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> differ conceptually?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> requires both operands to be true to produce true; <code>||</code> requires only one operand to be true.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> is for comparing numbers; <code>||</code> is for combining boolean results.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are exactly the same; <code>||</code> is just a synonym for <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> requires exactly one operand to be true; <code>||</code> requires both.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`!` is the highest precedence, followed by `&amp;&amp;`, followed by `||`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the precedence ordering of Java's logical operators?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> is highest, then <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, then <code>||</code> is lowest.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>||</code> is highest, then <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, then <code>\!</code> is lowest.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> have equal precedence, and <code>\!</code> is lowest.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All three logical operators have the same precedence and associate left-to-right.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>!a &amp;&amp; b</code> parsed given precedence rules?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As <code>(!a) &amp;&amp; b</code>, because <code>!</code> binds tighter than <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As <code>\!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code>, because <code>\!</code> applies to the whole following expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As <code>\!(a) &amp;&amp; \!b</code>, distributing the <code>\!</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is ambiguous and requires parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>a || b &amp;&amp; c</code> parsed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As <code>a || (b &amp;&amp; c)</code>, because <code>&amp;&amp;</code> has higher precedence than <code>||</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As <code>(a || b) &amp;&amp; c</code>, because <code>||</code> has higher precedence than <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Left-to-right, as <code>(a || b) &amp;&amp; c</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is ambiguous without parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you want <code>||</code> to be evaluated before <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, what do you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use parentheses, e.g. <code>(a || b) &amp;&amp; c</code>, to override the default precedence.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Rewrite the expression using De Morgan's Laws.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Put the <code>||</code> expression on the left side of the <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the <code>\!</code> operator to change precedence.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the precedence of <code>!</code> to the precedence of <code>||</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!</code> has the highest logical precedence and <code>||</code> the lowest, so <code>!</code> is applied to its operand long before any surrounding <code>||</code> is evaluated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They have equal precedence, so they associate left-to-right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>||</code> has higher precedence because it is a binary operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are lower than <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, which sits between them.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When the result of a logical expression using `&amp;&amp;` or `||` can be determined by evaluating only the first operand, the second is not evaluated. This is known as short-circuited evaluation.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is short-circuited evaluation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a logical expression using <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code> can be decided from the first operand, Java skips evaluating the second operand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When Java evaluates both operands of <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code> in parallel to save time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compiler optimization that replaces <code>&amp;&amp;</code> with <code>&amp;</code> when the operands are constants.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a boolean expression is evaluated right-to-left instead of left-to-right.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>false &amp;&amp; someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Since the left side is <code>false</code>, the whole <code>&amp;&amp;</code> must be <code>false</code>, so the right side is skipped.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Java always evaluates both operands of <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>someMethod()</code> has no side effects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but its return value is discarded because the left side is <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>true || someMethod()</code>, is <code>someMethod()</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. The left side being <code>true</code> determines the <code>||</code> result, so the right side is not evaluated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Java evaluates both operands of <code>||</code> before combining them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only to check its return type at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>someMethod()</code> is marked as pure.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is short-circuiting useful when the second operand might crash?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can guard a risky expression with a safe check, e.g. <code>s != null &amp;&amp; s.length() &gt; 0</code>, so the risky call only runs when it is safe.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It causes the risky call to throw a silent exception that you can catch later.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It reorders the operands automatically to put the safe one first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It logs a warning instead of running the risky expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code> short-circuit behavior.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> short-circuits when the first operand is <code>false</code>; <code>||</code> short-circuits when the first operand is <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&amp;&amp;</code> short-circuits when the first operand is <code>true</code>; <code>||</code> short-circuits when it is <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both operators short-circuit whenever the first operand is <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither operator short-circuits in Java; that's only true in C.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>De Morgan's Laws allows us to transform some boolean expressions into equivalent expressions. `!a &amp;&amp; !b = !(a || b)` `!a || !b = !(a &amp;&amp; b)`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do De Morgan's Laws let you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Transform certain boolean expressions into equivalent forms, specifically by distributing a <code>!</code> across <code>&amp;&amp;</code> and <code>||</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Prove that any boolean expression is equivalent to <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Convert any logical operator into an equality operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Combine two <code>if</code> statements into a single one without changing behavior.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>State De Morgan's Law for <code>!(a || b)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!(a || b)</code> is equivalent to <code>!a &amp;&amp; !b</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a || b)</code> is equivalent to <code>\!a || \!b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a || b)</code> is equivalent to <code>a &amp;&amp; b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a || b)</code> is equivalent to <code>\!(a) || \!(b)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>State De Morgan's Law for <code>!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> is equivalent to <code>!a || !b</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> is equivalent to <code>\!a &amp;&amp; \!b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> is equivalent to <code>a || b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!(a &amp;&amp; b)</code> is equivalent to <code>\!(a) &amp;&amp; \!(b)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Rewrite <code>!(x &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; y &gt; 0)</code> without the outer <code>!</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using De Morgan's Laws: <code>x &lt;= 0 || y &lt;= 0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x &lt; 0 &amp;&amp; y &lt; 0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x &gt;= 0 || y &gt;= 0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x &lt;= 0 &amp;&amp; y &lt;= 0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful to transform a boolean expression with De Morgan's Laws?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can make conditions easier to read, remove a confusing outer negation, or expose a form that matches existing code.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It always makes the expression shorter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It can turn any boolean expression into a constant.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It lets the compiler skip evaluating some operands at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Truth tables can be used to prove `boolean` identities, i.e. different expressions that are equivalent in the sense that for all possible combinations of values for the variables in the expressions they evaluate to the same value. A trivial example of a pair of equivalent expressions is: `a &amp;&amp; true` and `a`. More complex identities include things like De Morgan's Laws. For more details see [Boolean algebra summary]</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a truth table used for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To prove that two boolean expressions are equivalent by checking that they produce the same result for every combination of input values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To list every possible value a single variable can take.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To evaluate a single boolean expression for one particular input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To show the order in which Java evaluates logical operators.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean for two boolean expressions to be equivalent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For every possible combination of values of their variables, both expressions evaluate to the same <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They produce the same result for at least one combination of inputs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They use the same operators in the same order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They both evaluate to <code>true</code> for every input combination.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> equivalent to <code>a</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether <code>a</code> is <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>, <code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> has the same value as <code>a</code>, so they match in every row of the truth table.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>&amp;&amp;</code> always returns its left operand when the right is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>true</code> is the identity element for <code>||</code> as well as <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java optimizes <code>a &amp;&amp; true</code> by removing the <code>true</code> at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many rows does a truth table need for an expression in three boolean variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Eight rows: one for each combination of <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> across the three variables (2 to the 3rd power).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Six rows: 3 variables times 2 values each.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Three rows: one for each variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nine rows: 3 squared.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you make a truth table for both sides of a De Morgan's Law?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both sides yield identical columns for all input combinations, proving the identity.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The two sides differ in exactly one row, proving they are not equivalent.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One side has more rows than the other because of the extra <code>\!</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They match only when all variables are <code>true</code>, proving partial equivalence.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Equality operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Both primitive and reference values can be compared for equality using the equality operators `==` and `!=`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which operators are the equality operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> and <code>!=</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>=</code> and <code>\!=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>eq</code> and <code>neq</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code> and <code>&lt;&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you use <code>==</code> on reference values like objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>==</code> can compare both primitive and reference values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. <code>==</code> only works on primitive values in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the objects override the <code>==</code> operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the objects implement the <code>Equatable</code> interface.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>!=</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Not equal." It returns <code>true</code> when the two operands are not equal using <code>==</code>'s notion of equality.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>"Not." It flips a <code>boolean</code> value to its opposite.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"Almost equal." It allows a small margin of difference between numeric values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"Assignment with negation." It stores the negated right-hand value into the left.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compare an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> with <code>==</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is allowed because both are primitives; Java compares their numeric values after any needed conversion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile error, because <code>==</code> cannot compare different primitive types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>double</code> is truncated to an <code>int</code> before comparison.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java always returns <code>false</code> because the types are different.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>==</code> on primitives versus on references.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On primitives <code>==</code> compares values directly; on references it compares whether the two variables refer to the same object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On primitives <code>==</code> compares memory addresses; on references it compares values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On both, <code>==</code> compares values using the class's <code>equals</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code> works only on primitives; on references you must use <code>.equals</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>However two object references are only `==` when they both reference the same object or when they are both `null`. This may not, however, be the notion of "the same" that you care about when you are comparing two objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are two object references <code>==</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only when they refer to the same object in memory, or when both are <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When the two objects have the same field values, regardless of where they live in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When both references point to objects of the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the objects' <code>equals</code> methods both return <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two <code>String</code> objects have the same characters but were created separately, what does <code>==</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It may return <code>false</code>, because they are different objects even though their contents match.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>, because <code>String</code> overrides <code>==</code> to compare characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>, because Java automatically interns all <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>NullPointerException</code> because <code>==</code> is undefined for <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>==</code> always the right way to compare objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>==</code> tests identity; often you want to test whether the objects are "the same" in terms of content, which is a different question.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. <code>==</code> always checks whether two objects are "the same."</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the objects are of the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. <code>==</code> tests content equivalence and is almost never what you want.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens with <code>null == null</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code>, since both references are <code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>NullPointerException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates to <code>false</code>, because <code>null</code> is not equal to anything, including itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile error, because <code>null</code> has no type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the meaning of <code>==</code> for primitives versus objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For primitives it asks "are the values the same?"; for objects it asks "are these references to the very same object?".</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>For primitives it compares memory addresses; for objects it compares field values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>For primitives it calls <code>equals</code>; for objects it compares values directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>For both, it asks whether the two operands contain the same data.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All classes have an `equals` method inherited from `Object` and often overridden by classes to provide a way to determine if two instances of the class are equivalent. For example, two `String` objects with the same character content are `equals` even when they are not `==`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does every class get its <code>equals</code> method from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>Object</code>, the superclass of all classes in Java.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>From the <code>Equatable</code> interface, which every class automatically implements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From the class itself; <code>equals</code> must be defined in every Java class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From the <code>String</code> class, which every other class extends.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do many classes override <code>equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To give a meaningful, content-based notion of equivalence for their instances rather than the default reference comparison.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the default <code>equals</code> throws an exception if you don't override it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To make the <code>==</code> operator work correctly on their instances.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler requires every class to override <code>equals</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compare two <code>String</code>s with the same characters using <code>.equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns <code>true</code>, even if <code>==</code> would return <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>false</code>, because <code>.equals</code> on <code>String</code> compares references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>NullPointerException</code> unless both strings are interned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>true</code> only if the two <code>String</code>s are also <code>==</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>String a = new String("hi"); String b = new String("hi");</code>. What do <code>a == b</code> and <code>a.equals(b)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>a == b</code> is <code>false</code> (different objects); <code>a.equals(b)</code> is <code>true</code> (same content).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both <code>a == b</code> and <code>a.equals(b)</code> are <code>true</code>, because the characters match.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both <code>a == b</code> and <code>a.equals(b)</code> are <code>false</code>, because they are different objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a == b</code> is <code>true</code> (interned); <code>a.equals(b)</code> is also <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>==</code> and <code>.equals</code> for objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> checks whether two references point to the same object; <code>.equals</code> checks whether two objects are equivalent by whatever rule the class defines.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They always give the same answer, so you can use either one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code> checks value equivalence; <code>.equals</code> checks reference identity.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code> works on any object; <code>.equals</code> only works on <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `==` operator is sometimes pronounced "equals equals" to distinguish it from the `equals` method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>==</code> sometimes pronounced out loud?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Equals equals."</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>"Double equals sign."</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"Equivalent."</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"Equals dot."</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why use the pronunciation "equals equals" for <code>==</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To distinguish it in speech from the <code>equals</code> method, which has a different meaning.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because it is shorter to say than "the equality operator."</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it sounds more technical than just "equals."</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To emphasize that <code>==</code> works on two values rather than one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "a dot equals b" versus "a equals equals b", which refers to the method and which refers to the operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"a dot equals b" refers to the <code>equals</code> method; "a equals equals b" refers to the <code>==</code> operator.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>"a dot equals b" refers to the <code>==</code> operator; "a equals equals b" refers to the <code>equals</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They both refer to the <code>equals</code> method, just pronounced differently.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"a dot equals b" is an assignment; "a equals equals b" is a comparison.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you confuse <code>==</code> with <code>.equals</code> on objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You may end up checking reference identity when you meant to check value equivalence, leading to subtle bugs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You may end up checking content equivalence when you meant to check reference identity, causing unnecessary overhead.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You get a compile error that is easy to fix.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java throws a <code>ClassCastException</code> at runtime whenever they disagree.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the syntactic forms of the two kinds of equality checks on objects.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The operator form is <code>a == b</code>; the method form is <code>a.equals(b)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The operator form is <code>a.equals(b)</code>; the method form is <code>a == b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both forms are written the same way; only the meaning differs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The operator form is <code>a === b</code>; the method form is <code>a.equals(b)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Relational operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Relational operators operate on numeric values and produce a `boolean` value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values do relational operators take, and what do they produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They take numeric operands and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They take <code>boolean</code> operands and produce a numeric value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They take any kind of operand and produce a numeric value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They take <code>boolean</code> operands and produce a <code>boolean</code> value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you use relational operators directly on two <code>boolean</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Relational operators require numeric operands.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. <code>true</code> is treated as <code>1</code> and <code>false</code> as <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only <code>==</code> and <code>\!=</code> are allowed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if both operands are <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result type of <code>5 &lt; 10</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code> — specifically <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> — specifically <code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>boolean</code> — specifically <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>&lt;</code> needs variables, not literals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to combine the result of a relational comparison with another condition. What kind of operator do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A logical operator like <code>&amp;&amp;</code> or <code>||</code>, because the relational expression produces a <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Another relational operator like <code>&lt;</code> or <code>&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An equality operator like <code>==</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The assignment operator <code>=</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare relational operators with logical operators in terms of input types.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Relational operators consume numbers and produce <code>boolean</code>; logical operators consume <code>boolean</code>s and produce <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both consume numeric operands and produce <code>boolean</code> results.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Relational operators consume <code>boolean</code>s; logical operators consume numbers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both consume <code>boolean</code>s, but only logical operators produce <code>boolean</code> results.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Numeric values can be compared using the relational operators `&lt;`, `&gt;`, `&lt;=`, and `&gt;=` which evaluate to `true` if their left hand operand is less than, greater than, less than or equal to, or greater than or equal to the right hand operand. E.g. `10 &lt; 20` evaluates to `true`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the four relational operators in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;=</code>, and <code>&gt;=</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>==</code>, and <code>\!=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>=&lt;</code>, and <code>=&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>lt</code>, <code>gt</code>, <code>le</code>, and <code>ge</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>a &lt;= b</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code> when <code>a</code> is less than or equal to <code>b</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code> only when <code>a</code> is strictly less than <code>b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It assigns the smaller of <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> to the left operand.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates to <code>true</code> only when <code>a</code> equals <code>b</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>10 &lt; 20</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>10</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because you can't compare two literals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to check that <code>x</code> is strictly greater than <code>y</code>. Which operator do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&gt;</code>, as in <code>x &gt; y</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>&gt;=</code>, as in <code>x &gt;= y</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!=</code>, as in <code>x \!= y</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;</code>, as in <code>y &lt; x</code>, which means the same thing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>&lt;</code> is true only when the left side is strictly less than the right; <code>&lt;=</code> is also true when the two sides are equal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are the same operator; <code>&lt;=</code> is just a shortcut for <code>&lt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code> both include equality; they differ only in associativity.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;</code> allows equality; <code>&lt;=</code> is strictly less than.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You can't chain relational operators in Java the way you can in math. So rather than writing `0 &lt;= x &lt; 10` you have to combine two relational expressions with the logical operator `&amp;&amp;`, writing instead `0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java the way you would in math?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Java does not allow chained relational operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, Java supports chained relational operators just like math.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you put parentheses around the middle variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only with <code>==</code> and <code>\!=</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the correct way to express "x is between 0 and 10" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Combine two relational expressions with <code>&amp;&amp;</code>: <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code>, which Java interprets mathematically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the <code>between</code> method: <code>x.between(0, 10)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Combine two relational expressions with <code>||</code>: <code>0 &lt;= x || x &lt; 10</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to compile <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You get a compile error, because the first comparison yields a <code>boolean</code>, and <code>&lt;</code> cannot compare a <code>boolean</code> to an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles fine and works the way it does in math.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but always returns <code>false</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a warning, not an error; Java rewrites it as <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java reject chained relational operators?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each relational operator produces a <code>boolean</code>, and relational operators require numeric operands, so chaining leads to a type mismatch.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because chaining would make expressions too hard to read.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because relational operators are not associative.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the Java parser does not support three-operand expressions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the math notation <code>0 &lt;= x &lt; 10</code> with the Java equivalent.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The math form uses implicit conjunction; Java makes the conjunction explicit with <code>&amp;&amp;</code>, as in <code>0 &lt;= x &amp;&amp; x &lt; 10</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The math form is ambiguous; the Java form always binds to the right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java's form is shorter because it does not need the conjunction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two forms are identical in Java; the <code>&amp;&amp;</code> is implicit.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Assignment operators</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Assignments in Java are technically expressions that produce a value but normally we care more about their side effect, namely changing the value the variable or array element being assigned to.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Are assignments in Java statements or expressions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are technically expressions that produce a value, though we usually care about their side effect.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are statements only; assignments have no value in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are expressions whose value is always <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are neither — assignments are a special construct that is neither statement nor expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "side effect" of a Java assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Changing the value stored in the variable or array element being assigned to.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Returning the new value so it can be used in larger expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Triggering any observers registered on the variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Clearing the variable's previous value without storing anything new.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you write <code>x = y = 0;</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because assignment is an expression that produces a value, so <code>y = 0</code> yields <code>0</code>, which is then assigned to <code>x</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java has a special rule allowing multiple targets on the left of <code>=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>=</code> distributes over its operands like <code>&amp;&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>y = 0</code> is a statement, and statements can be embedded in other statements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When we use an assignment, do we usually care about its value or its side effect?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its side effect - updating the variable or array element.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Its value — the right-hand expression is what we usually want.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; assignments are usually just ignored by the surrounding code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both equally, in every situation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do assignment expressions differ from, say, arithmetic expressions like <code>a + b</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Arithmetic expressions are evaluated purely for their value, while assignment expressions are evaluated mainly for the side effect of storing a new value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Arithmetic expressions have side effects, while assignment expressions only produce values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same: both produce values and have side effects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Assignment expressions produce <code>boolean</code> values, while arithmetic expressions produce numbers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The only assignable places in Java are variables (local or member) and array access expressions, e.g. `x`, `obj.someField`, and `nums[0]`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What three kinds of "places" can appear on the left side of an assignment in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Local variables, member (field) variables, and array access expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Literals, variables, and method calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Local variables, parameters, and return values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Variables, constants, and array access expressions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an array access expression that is assignable.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>nums[0]</code> - or any <code>array[index]</code> expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>nums.length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>nums[0] + 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Arrays.get(nums, 0)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>obj.someField</code> a legal target for assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, member field access is one of the assignable places in Java.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — only local variables can appear on the left of <code>=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>someField</code> is declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>obj</code> is the current class's <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to assign to something like <code>x + 1</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is a compile error - <code>x + 1</code> is not an assignable place; only variables and array elements are.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It assigns <code>1</code> to <code>x</code> as a side effect.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is allowed, but the assignment is silently discarded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It increments <code>x</code> by <code>1</code>, similar to <code>x++</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an assignable place to a regular expression - what distinguishes them?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An assignable place names a storage location (variable or array element) that can be updated, while a regular expression just produces a value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An assignable place must be a primitive type, while a regular expression can be any type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Assignable places can only appear on the right side of <code>=</code>, while regular expressions can appear on either side.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>There is no difference; any expression can be assigned to.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The assignment operator `=` allows a program to initialize or change the value stored in a variable or an array element. The value of the expression on the right of the `=` is stored in the variable or array element referenced on the left. The value of of an assignment expression is the value that was assigned.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>=</code> operator do in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It initializes or changes the value stored in a variable or array element, storing the right-hand value into the left-hand location.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compares the left and right sides for equality.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It copies the left-hand value into the right-hand location.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It declares a new variable with the given name and value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>x = 5 + 3;</code>, which side is evaluated first and what gets stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The right side is evaluated first, producing <code>8</code>, which is then stored in <code>x</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The left side is evaluated first, locking in the target, and then <code>8</code> is stored in it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both sides are evaluated simultaneously in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The assignment happens before the addition, so <code>x</code> is briefly set to <code>5</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the value of the expression <code>x = 10</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value that was assigned - in this case, <code>10</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>, because assignments have no meaningful value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The old value of <code>x</code> before the assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>, indicating the assignment succeeded.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>int a = b = c = 0;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>c</code> is assigned <code>0</code> (value <code>0</code>), then <code>b</code> is assigned that value, then <code>a</code> is assigned that value - all three end up as <code>0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>a</code> is assigned <code>0</code>; <code>b</code> and <code>c</code> are left uninitialized.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile error, because you can only assign one variable at a time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a</code> gets <code>0</code>, but <code>b</code> and <code>c</code> get each other's old values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the <code>=</code> operator flow right-to-left or left-to-right?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The right-hand expression is evaluated and its value flows into the left-hand location.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Left-to-right: the left operand is evaluated first and its value is stored on the right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither; both sides are evaluated at the same time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It flows left-to-right for primitives and right-to-left for objects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compound assignment operators (`+=`, `−=`, `*=`, `/=`, `%=`) can be used to assign a new value to a variable or array element computed from the old value. For instance `x += 2` is equivalent to `x = x + 2`. The value of a compound assignment expression is the new value of the variable or array element.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a compound assignment operator?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An operator like <code>+=</code>, <code>-=</code>, <code>*=</code>, <code>/=</code>, or <code>%=</code> that computes a new value from the old value and assigns it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An operator that assigns to two variables at once, like <code>a, b = 0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An operator that combines assignment with a comparison, like <code>&lt;=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An operator like <code>==</code> that both compares and assigns.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>x += 2</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x = x + 2</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x = 2 + x</code>, but only if <code>x</code> is a primitive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x + 2</code>, without storing the result back into <code>x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x++</code> applied twice.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>10</code>, what is the value of the expression <code>x *= 3</code>, and what is <code>x</code> afterward?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The expression's value is <code>30</code> (the new value), and <code>x</code> is now <code>30</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>10</code> (the old value), and <code>x</code> is now <code>30</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>3</code> (the right operand), and <code>x</code> is now <code>30</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>30</code>, but <code>x</code> is still <code>10</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the value of a compound assignment differ from the value of a plain assignment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are the same kind of thing: both yield the value that was stored in the variable. For a compound assignment that's the newly computed value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Compound assignments yield the old value of the variable, while plain assignments yield the new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compound assignments have no value, while plain assignments yield the new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compound assignments yield a <code>boolean</code> indicating success; plain assignments yield the new value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to reduce <code>score</code> by <code>5</code>. Write it using a compound assignment.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>score -= 5;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>score =- 5;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>score--5;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>score = score -= 5;</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The increment operator (`++`) and decrement operator (`−−`) are used to add 1 or subtract 1 from the value of a variable or an array element. For instance `x++` equivalent to `x += 1` or `x = x + 1`. The value of a `++` or `--` is the value of the variable or array element before it was incremented or decremented.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>++</code> and <code>--</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They add 1 to or subtract 1 from the value of a variable or array element.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They compare a variable to <code>1</code> and return a <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They duplicate or discard the value of a variable or array element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They double or halve the value of a variable or array element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p><code>x++</code> is equivalent to which longer forms?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x += 1</code> or <code>x = x + 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x = x++</code> or <code>x++ + 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x = 1</code> or <code>x += x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>++x</code> or <code>x = x - 1</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>x</code> is <code>5</code>, what is the value of the expression <code>x++</code>, and what is <code>x</code> afterward?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The expression's value is <code>5</code> (the value before), and <code>x</code> is now <code>6</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>6</code> (the new value), and <code>x</code> is now <code>6</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>5</code>, and <code>x</code> is still <code>5</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression's value is <code>1</code> (the increment amount), and <code>x</code> is now <code>6</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the value of <code>x++</code> differ from the value of <code>x += 1</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>x++</code> yields the old value of <code>x</code>, while <code>x += 1</code> yields the new value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They yield the same value — the new value of <code>x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x++</code> yields the new value; <code>x += 1</code> yields the old value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x++</code> yields <code>1</code>; <code>x += 1</code> yields the new value of <code>x</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to <code>nums[i]</code> when you write <code>nums[i]--</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The array element at index <code>i</code> is decreased by 1; the expression's value is the element's value before the decrement.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The array element at index <code>i</code> is decreased by 1; the expression's value is the new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a compile error — <code>--</code> cannot be applied to array elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The entire array is shifted down by 1, and the expression's value is the old <code>nums[i]</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Note that `=` (one equals sign) is the assignment operator and `==` (two equals signs) is the equality comparison operator. If you mix them up, you'll get either compiler errors or incorrect and confusing behavior from your program.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the difference between <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>=</code> assigns a value to a variable; <code>==</code> compares two values for equality.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>=</code> compares values; <code>==</code> assigns a value to a variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are synonyms in Java and can be used interchangeably.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>=</code> works on primitives; <code>==</code> works on objects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What goes wrong if you write <code>if (x = 5)</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's a compile error because <code>x = 5</code> produces an <code>int</code>, not the <code>boolean</code> an <code>if</code> requires.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles and always evaluates to <code>true</code> because <code>5</code> is nonzero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles and sets <code>x</code> to <code>5</code>, then tests whether <code>x</code> is nonzero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a runtime error, because <code>=</code> cannot appear inside an <code>if</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is mixing up <code>=</code> and <code>==</code> dangerous?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can cause compiler errors or, worse, silently incorrect behavior that is hard to debug.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>=</code> is slower than <code>==</code>, causing performance problems.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the Java compiler always silently replaces one with the other.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is not dangerous; Java always catches the mistake.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which operator would you use to check whether two <code>int</code>s are equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code>, the equality comparison operator.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>=</code>, the assignment operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>.equals</code>, the equality method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>\!=</code>, the not-equal operator.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you meant to compare <code>count</code> to <code>0</code> but wrote <code>count = 0</code>. What are the consequences?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You overwrite <code>count</code> with <code>0</code> instead of comparing, changing the program's state and likely causing confusing, incorrect behavior.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nothing — Java treats a bare assignment as a comparison inside <code>if</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You get a compile error, which makes the mistake easy to catch.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program runs but always takes the <code>else</code> branch.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Methods</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Procedural abstraction means hiding how a value is computed or how an effect is achieved allowing a programmer to use a method without needing to know exactly how the method is written.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Hiding how a value is computed or how an effect is achieved, so a programmer can use a method without knowing exactly how it's written.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing methods that take no parameters so they are easier to reuse.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Organizing methods into abstract classes so they can be overridden.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Replacing concrete values in code with variable names to make it more general.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does procedural abstraction let a programmer avoid thinking about?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The internal details of how a method computes its value or achieves its effect.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing the same method twice in different classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Calling the method at all; once abstracted, the code runs automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Thinking about the method's name and parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When you call <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>, how does procedural abstraction help you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can use the result without knowing the algorithm Java uses internally to compute the square root.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It lets you call <code>Math.sqrt</code> without importing the <code>Math</code> class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means Java automatically computes square roots faster than you could write by hand.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It guarantees that <code>Math.sqrt</code> returns an exact value, not an approximation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is procedural abstraction different from just reusing code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Reuse is a benefit, but abstraction specifically refers to hiding implementation details so the caller doesn't need to know them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Abstraction only matters when code is reused; if code runs once, there is no abstraction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Abstraction means making code shorter; reuse means running it multiple times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same thing; both describe calling a method more than once.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is procedural abstraction important for managing complexity?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets programmers reason about a method by its behavior alone, without keeping all of its implementation details in mind.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It reduces the number of methods a program needs by combining them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It makes Java programs run faster by caching method results.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It eliminates the need to test methods once they are abstracted.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In Java the unit of procedural abstraction is the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the unit of procedural abstraction in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In Java, where does procedural abstraction live?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In methods - each method packages up some computation or effect behind a name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In classes — each class packages up some computation or effect.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In variables — each variable hides a value behind a name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In interfaces — each interface describes an abstract behavior.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that the method is Java's "unit" of procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods are the building blocks Java gives you for hiding how something is computed or done.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Every Java program must contain at least one method called <code>abstract</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods are the only place in Java where you can use the <code>abstract</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods have a fixed "unit size" that limits how much they can abstract.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone asks "how do I create a new abstraction in Java?" what's a basic answer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write a method that hides some computation or effect behind a named, reusable interface.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Declare a new variable and give it a descriptive name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Create a subclass that inherits from <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the <code>abstract</code> keyword on a class definition.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare: in Java, methods are to procedural abstraction as what are to data abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes (and their fields/objects) are the unit of data abstraction, while methods are the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Variables are the unit of data abstraction; methods are the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Interfaces are the unit of data abstraction; methods are the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitives are the unit of data abstraction; methods are the unit of procedural abstraction.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods allow us to "decompose" or break down a large problem into smaller sub-problems by writing methods that call other methods that each solve various sub-problems.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "decompose" a problem using methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Breaking a large problem into smaller sub-problems, each solved by its own method, which may call other methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing one large method that contains every step of the solution.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Splitting a method into individual statements, each on its own line.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Replacing all methods with inline code for efficiency.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is decomposition helpful when solving big problems?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Smaller sub-problems are easier to understand, solve, test, and reason about than one giant monolithic problem.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the Java compiler cannot handle methods longer than a certain size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because smaller sub-problems run faster at runtime than big ones.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because decomposition automatically generates test cases for each piece.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when methods call other methods during decomposition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each method handles a piece of the work and delegates other pieces to helper methods, building up the full solution.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The called methods run in parallel, speeding up the overall computation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Each method must duplicate the work of the others to ensure correctness.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java inlines all calls at compile time, so no actual delegation happens.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you need to compute the average grade per student from a list. How might you decompose it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write one method to sum a student's grades, another to count them, and another that uses both to compute the average.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Write one big method that loops over students, grades, and totals all at once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write a method named <code>average</code> that handles all the work, and call it once per student.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write a method for each student individually, hard-coding their grades.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does method decomposition relate to procedural abstraction?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each decomposed sub-problem becomes a method, and procedural abstraction lets callers use it without worrying about its internal details.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are unrelated; decomposition is about files, and procedural abstraction is about methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Decomposition hides details, while procedural abstraction exposes them to the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Procedural abstraction only matters for library methods; decomposition only matters for your own code.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can use methods provided to us by Java (as in the `Math` methods such as `Math.sqrt`) and also methods that we write ourselves.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two kinds of methods can a Java program use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods provided by Java (like <code>Math.sqrt</code>) and methods that we write ourselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static methods and instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public methods and private methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods that return values and methods that don't.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a Java-provided method.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.sqrt</code>, or any method in the <code>Math</code> class such as <code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, etc.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>print</code>, which writes output to the console.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>main</code>, which starts every Java program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>run</code>, which executes any method by name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a difference in how you call a library method versus one you wrote yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the calling syntax is the same; the only difference is who wrote the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — library methods use a dot, while your own methods do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — library methods require an <code>import</code> statement, while your own methods never do.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — library methods are slower because they involve cross-package lookups.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that you can mix library methods and your own methods freely?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can build on top of Java's provided functionality instead of reinventing everything, while still writing custom behavior where needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It lets Java programs run faster because library methods are pre-compiled.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It ensures that all methods have consistent naming conventions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It forces you to understand how every library method is implemented.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What class in Java provides common mathematical methods like <code>sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>Math</code> class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>java.util</code> class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Number</code> class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Arithmetic</code> class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can use methods without knowing exactly how they are implemented but it is also useful to write our own method to hide details in one part of our code even though we have to deal with those details elsewhere.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Do you have to know how a method is implemented in order to use it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - you can use methods based only on what they do, without understanding their implementation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — you must read the source code of every method you call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for methods that return <code>void</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for library methods, not for ones you wrote yourself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might you write a method to hide details even when you're the one who has to write those details?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that the details appear in only one place and the rest of your code can stay clean and focused on its own concerns.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler runs faster when details are spread across multiple methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because hidden details don't need to be tested.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires every block of code to live inside a method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the benefit of writing your own method to hide details you still have to handle?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It isolates complexity to one place, making the rest of your code simpler and easier to understand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It lets you skip writing those details entirely.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It automatically documents the details for other programmers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It moves the details to a place where they will never need to change again.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you have messy string parsing logic scattered throughout your program. What should you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Extract the parsing into its own method so the details are handled in one place and callers just use the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Copy the parsing logic into each place to make sure it works everywhere.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rewrite the parsing using a single long expression to avoid needing a method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Leave it as is; extracting it into a method would only add overhead.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare using a library method versus writing your own method for abstraction.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both hide details from the caller; with library methods someone else already wrote them, while with your own methods you write the details once and then forget about them elsewhere.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Library methods provide abstraction, but your own methods do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Your own methods provide abstraction, but library methods do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Library methods are always faster and more reliable than your own methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The code in one method can call other methods, allowing us to build layers of abstractions.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What can code inside one method do with other methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can call them, which lets us build layers of abstractions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nothing — each method is isolated and cannot interact with others.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It can redefine them, but it cannot call them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It can inline their code, but only at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "build layers of abstractions"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Higher-level methods are built by calling lower-level methods, each hiding more detail from the layer above.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing many copies of the same method at different levels of the program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nesting methods inside other methods so they share local state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Organizing methods alphabetically so they are easy to find.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>printReport</code> method calls <code>formatRow</code>, which calls <code>formatNumber</code>. What does this illustrate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Layered abstractions - each method is expressed in terms of lower-level helpers, hiding details from the higher-level methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Recursive methods — each method calls a simpler version of itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Method overloading — each method has the same name but different arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inheritance — each method overrides one in a parent class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are layered abstractions useful for managing complex programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each layer only has to understand the layer directly below it, keeping any individual piece of code simple.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They make programs run faster by reducing the total number of methods called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They eliminate the need for comments, because the layers document themselves.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They let Java automatically generate higher layers from lower ones.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does method-to-method calling relate to problem decomposition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Decomposition produces sub-problems solved by methods, and methods calling other methods is exactly how those pieces fit back together.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Decomposition splits a method into statements; method-to-method calling links statements together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are opposites: decomposition breaks code apart, while calling methods puts code together in a way that undoes decomposition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Method-to-method calling is what you do when decomposition fails.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Method structure</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method signatures must specify three things: the return type, the name of the method, and the method's parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What three things does a Java method signature specify?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The return type, the method's name, and its parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The return type, the method body, and its local variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class name, the method's name, and the return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The access modifier, the name, and the number of statements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int add(int a, int b)</code>, identify the three parts of the signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return type: <code>int</code>; name: <code>add</code>; parameters: <code>int a, int b</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Return type: <code>add</code>; name: <code>int</code>; parameters: <code>a, b</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return type: <code>int</code>; name: <code>add(int a, int b)</code>; parameters: none.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return type: <code>int a</code>; name: <code>add</code>; parameters: <code>int b</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does a method signature need the return type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So the compiler and callers know what kind of value the method produces.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So the JVM knows how much memory to allocate for the method's body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So the method can be invoked without parentheses by its callers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So the method is automatically added to the class's list of constructors.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's missing from this "signature": <code>add(int a, int b)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The return type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The parameter names.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The access modifier.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a method signature to a function's contract - what does the signature tell a caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It tells the caller the method's name, what types of arguments to pass, and what type of value (if any) to expect back.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It tells the caller exactly which lines of code will run and in what order when the method is invoked.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It tells the caller the class of the object that will be returned and the memory address of the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It tells the caller how long the method will take to execute and what exceptions it throws.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The return type specifies the kind of value the method returns. The special return type `void` indicates that a method does not return any value. All non-`void` methods must return a value of the specified type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the return type of a method specify?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The kind of value the method returns to its caller.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The type of the first parameter the method accepts.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The type of the object on which the method must be invoked.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of values the method returns to its caller.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the special return type <code>void</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That the method does not return any value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That the method returns an empty string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the method returns <code>null</code> by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the method can return any type the caller expects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must every non-<code>void</code> method do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return a value of the type declared as its return type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Declare at least one parameter of the same type as its return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>return</code> exactly once, at the very end of the method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return a <code>String</code> representation of its result.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if an <code>int</code> method has a path that doesn't return anything?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The code won't compile - non-<code>void</code> methods must return a value of the specified type on every path.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It runs fine and returns <code>0</code> by default on that path.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but throws a <code>NullPointerException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler inserts an implicit <code>return -1;</code> for you.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>void</code> and <code>int</code> as return types.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> means the method must return an <code>int</code> value; <code>void</code> means the method returns no value at all.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both require a <code>return</code> statement, but <code>void</code> returns <code>null</code> and <code>int</code> returns <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> returns an empty integer; <code>int</code> returns a non-empty integer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> methods can be called only for effect; <code>void</code> methods can be used in expressions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods with `void` as their return type are called "`void` methods" and are called only for the effects they have, such as printing to the screen or changing the state of an object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "<code>void</code> method"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method whose return type is <code>void</code>, meaning it returns no value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that has no parameters and no body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns a <code>null</code> value of any type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that cannot be called from outside its class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why would you call a <code>void</code> method if it doesn't return anything?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For its side effects - like printing to the screen or changing an object's state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To reserve a slot in the call stack for later use.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To make the program run faster by skipping the return step.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To create a new object of the method's class as a side effect.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give two examples of side effects a <code>void</code> method might perform.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Printing text to the screen and changing the state of an object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Returning a <code>String</code> and returning an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Allocating memory and freeing memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declaring a local variable and computing an expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write <code>int x = printHello();</code> where <code>printHello</code> is <code>void</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - you can't assign the result of a <code>void</code> method to a variable because it produces no value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The variable <code>x</code> is assigned <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The variable <code>x</code> is assigned <code>0</code> as a default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program runs but <code>x</code> has an undefined value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how you'd use a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Non-<code>void</code> methods can be used anywhere a value is needed; <code>void</code> methods can only be called as statements for their effects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> methods are called with parentheses; non-<code>void</code> methods are called without parentheses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both kinds of methods can appear on the right side of an assignment, but only <code>void</code> methods can be used as arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> methods must be called first in a program; non-<code>void</code> methods can be called anywhere afterward.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method parameters are variables and thus must be specified with a type and a name.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are method parameters in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Variables declared in the method's signature, each specified with a type and a name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Values returned by the method to its caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Names of other methods that the method is allowed to call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Constants declared before the method's signature.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two things must you specify for each parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its type and its name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Its name and its default value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its type and its access modifier.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its position and its return type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's wrong with the parameter list <code>(a, b)</code> in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's missing the types - each parameter needs both a type and a name, like <code>(int a, int b)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nothing - Java infers the types from the caller's arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It uses parentheses instead of square brackets.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's missing the comma between parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do parameters need names as well as types?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So code inside the method can refer to the passed-in values using those names.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So the compiler can tell different parameters with the same type apart at compile time only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So the caller can pass arguments by name instead of by position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So the JVM can allocate a unique memory address for each parameter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a parameter to a local variable.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Parameters are essentially local variables that are initialized automatically from the caller's arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Parameters can be reassigned inside a method, but local variables cannot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters live on the heap, while local variables live on the stack.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters are shared across all calls to the method; local variables are not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that take no arguments are written with an empty parameter list consisting of just a pair of parentheses.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you write a method that takes no arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an empty parameter list - just a pair of parentheses, like <code>foo()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Omit the parentheses entirely, like <code>void foo;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>void</code> inside the parentheses, like <code>foo(void)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>()</code> only if the method is <code>static</code>; otherwise omit them.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you simply omit the parentheses for a method with no parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the parentheses are required even when there are no parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, the parentheses are optional when the parameter list is empty.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for <code>static</code> methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when calling the method, not when declaring it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>void greet()</code> tell you about the method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns nothing and takes no parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns an empty <code>String</code> and takes no parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns nothing and takes one parameter named <code>greet</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns a <code>void</code> value and takes an unspecified number of parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a method that prints the current time. What would its parameter list look like?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An empty pair of parentheses, since the method needs no inputs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single <code>String</code> parameter for the format.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>void</code> parameter placeholder.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A parameter of type <code>Time</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>foo()</code> and <code>foo(int x)</code> in terms of argument requirements.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>foo()</code> takes no arguments, while <code>foo(int x)</code> requires one <code>int</code> argument.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both take one argument, but <code>foo()</code> uses a default value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>foo()</code> takes any number of arguments; <code>foo(int x)</code> takes exactly one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>foo()</code> requires an <code>int</code> argument; <code>foo(int x)</code> takes none.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of the method follows the signature and is enclosed in a pair of `{}`s.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does a method's body go relative to its signature?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body follows the signature and is enclosed in a pair of <code>{}</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The body comes before the signature.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body is written inside the parameter list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body goes on the line above the signature, separated by a blank line.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What delimits the start and end of a method body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Curly braces: <code>{</code> and <code>}</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Parentheses: <code>(</code> and <code>)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Square brackets: <code>[</code> and <code>]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The keywords <code>begin</code> and <code>end</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you omit the braces if the method body is just one statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - unlike some constructs, method bodies always require braces.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, just like with a single-statement <code>if</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for <code>void</code> methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as the statement fits on the same line as the signature.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the overall shape of a Java method declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A signature followed by a body enclosed in <code>{}</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A body followed by a signature enclosed in <code>()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A name, a return type, and a semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A signature and a body separated by a semicolon.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a method body to an <code>if</code> block visually.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both use curly braces to enclose code, but a method body always needs braces while a single-statement <code>if</code> technically doesn't.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both always require braces and a trailing semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Method bodies use parentheses while <code>if</code> blocks use braces.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither requires braces when they contain only one statement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Code within the body of a method can refer to the parameters declared in the method signature as well as any local variables declared in the method and any `static` variables declared in the class. Code in instance methods can also refer to any instance variables defined in the class and the special variable `this` which refers to the object on which the method was invoked.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What variables can any method body refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its parameters, its local variables, and any <code>static</code> variables declared in the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only its parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters, local variables, and instance variables of any class in the program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Local variables and <code>this</code>, but not parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What additional things can an instance method access that a <code>static</code> method cannot?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables of the class and the special variable <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Local variables declared in other instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters of the enclosing class's constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Private <code>static</code> variables of other classes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>this</code> refer to inside an instance method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object on which the method was invoked.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The class in which the method is defined.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The most recently created object of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first argument passed to the method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're in a <code>static</code> method and try to use <code>this</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - <code>this</code> is only available in instance methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It refers to the class itself instead of an instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles, but <code>this</code> is always <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It refers to the object that called the <code>static</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the variable access of a <code>static</code> method vs. an instance method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can access parameters, locals, and <code>static</code> variables; only instance methods can also access instance variables and <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>static</code> methods can access <code>static</code> variables; only instance methods can access instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both can access <code>this</code>, but only instance methods can access parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code> methods can access everything instance methods can, plus the class itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Method calls</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Method calls consist of a reference to the method and a possibly empty argument list consisting of a comma-separated list of expressions, e.g. `foo(10, "some string")`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two parts of a method call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the method and a (possibly empty) argument list of comma-separated expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The return type and the argument list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method name and a semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the class and the method's body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>foo(10, "some string")</code>, what is the argument list?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>10, "some string"</code> - a comma-separated list of two expressions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>foo</code> - the name of the method being called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>(10, "some string")</code> - the entire parenthesized part including the parens.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Just <code>10</code> - the first expression in the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the argument list of a method call be empty?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - you just write an empty pair of parentheses like <code>foo()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No - every method call must pass at least one argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method is declared with no parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but you must write <code>void</code> inside the parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of things can appear in an argument list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Expressions - literals, variable references, arithmetic, other method calls, anything that evaluates to a value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only literal values like numbers and strings.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only variable references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Type declarations and variable names, like in a method signature.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are multiple arguments separated in a method call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By commas.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By semicolons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By spaces.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By the keyword <code>and</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The expressions in the argument list are evaluated to get the values that are passed as the arguments to the method. When the method runs the parameters declared in the method signature are initialized to the values of the corresponding arguments, with the first parameter getting the value of the first argument, and so on.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the expressions in an argument list at call time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are evaluated, and the resulting values become the arguments passed to the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are passed to the method as-is, and evaluated inside the method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are converted to strings and passed as text.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are stored in a temporary array and passed by reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are a method's parameters initialized when it runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each parameter is initialized to the value of the corresponding argument, in order - first parameter from first argument, and so on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They all start with their type's default value (<code>0</code>, <code>null</code>, etc.) until assigned in the body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are initialized alphabetically by parameter name from the arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are initialized by the caller after the method begins executing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>add(2 + 3, x * y)</code>, what exactly gets passed to <code>add</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The values produced by evaluating <code>2 + 3</code> and <code>x * y</code>, not the expressions themselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The expressions <code>2 + 3</code> and <code>x * y</code>, which are evaluated lazily inside the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>References to the variables <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> plus the literal <code>2 + 3</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A string representation of each expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does argument order matter when matching up with parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - the first argument goes to the first parameter, the second to the second, and so on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No - Java matches arguments to parameters by type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No - Java matches arguments to parameters by name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the method has more than two parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare passing <code>foo(x)</code> to <code>foo(x + 0)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate their argument expression and pass the resulting value; the method can't tell the difference.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>foo(x)</code> passes <code>x</code> by reference; <code>foo(x + 0)</code> passes by value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>foo(x + 0)</code> is slower because the addition must happen inside the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They differ because <code>x + 0</code> creates a new variable the method can modify.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The arguments passed to a constructor or method call must be compatible with the types identified in the parameter list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What must be true about the types of arguments in a method or constructor call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They must be compatible with the types declared in the parameter list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They must exactly match the declared parameter types - no widening allowed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They must all be of the same type as each other.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They must be reference types, never primitives.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you pass a <code>String</code> to a parameter declared as <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile error - the types are not compatible.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>String</code> is automatically parsed into an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method receives <code>0</code> as the parameter value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime <code>ClassCastException</code> is thrown.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you pass an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> parameter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - <code>int</code> is compatible with <code>double</code> because it can be automatically widened.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No - you must explicitly cast the <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>int</code> value fits within a <code>double</code>'s integer range.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No - <code>int</code> and <code>double</code> are not compatible types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method takes <code>(int, String)</code> and you call it with <code>("hello", 5)</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - the argument types don't match the parameter types in order.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The arguments are automatically reordered to match the parameter types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The call succeeds and the method receives the arguments in the given order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime error occurs when the method tries to use the values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does Java enforce type compatibility at call sites?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To catch mistakes at compile time and guarantee the method receives values of the kinds it knows how to work with.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make methods run faster by avoiding runtime type checks.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM cannot execute code with mismatched types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To force programmers to write explicit casts for every argument.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arguments are passed to methods by copying values. This means that there is no way for code in a method to change the value of local variable in the method that called it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are arguments passed to methods in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By copying values - the parameter gets a copy of the argument's value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By reference - the parameter is an alias for the caller's variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By name - the parameter name is bound to the caller's variable name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By pointer - the parameter holds the address of the caller's variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a method change the value of a local variable in its caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - because arguments are passed by copying, reassigning a parameter inside the method has no effect on the caller's variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as the variable is declared <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, if the method and caller are in the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, by reassigning its parameter to a new value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>void zero(int n) { n = 0; }</code> called as <code>zero(x)</code>. What happens to <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing - <code>x</code> still has its original value because only a copy of its value was passed in.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>x</code> becomes <code>0</code> after the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x</code> becomes <code>null</code> after the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The call fails to compile because <code>n</code> cannot be reassigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does "pass by copying values" prevent a method from modifying caller locals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The parameter is a separate variable that just starts with a copy of the caller's value; changes to the parameter never touch the caller's variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not allow reassignment of parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because parameters are <code>final</code> by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler inserts a copy-back step that discards changes to the parameter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare pass-by-value to a hypothetical pass-by-reference for primitives.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With pass-by-value (Java's approach), the method can't change the caller's variable; with pass-by-reference, changes inside the method would be visible to the caller.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Pass-by-value is slower than pass-by-reference because the value must be copied.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both allow the method to modify the caller's variable, but pass-by-reference is more efficient.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Pass-by-value uses more memory than pass-by-reference for primitives.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recall, however, that the value of a reference type is the reference itself; this means code in a method or constructor that is passed a reference to a mutable object can use the reference to alter the state of the object and those changes will be visible to other code that also has a reference to that object. As a matter of good coding practice, methods should not modify mutable objects passed as arguments unless doing so is an inherent part of the method's purpose.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "value" of a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The reference itself - essentially a pointer to the object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the object being referenced.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class name of the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of fields in the referenced object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Even though Java passes arguments by copying, how can a method still affect the caller's data?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If the argument is a reference to a mutable object, both method and caller hold references to the same object, so state changes made through the method's copy of the reference are visible to the caller.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By declaring its parameter as <code>final</code>, which enables modification of the caller's variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By reassigning its parameter, which updates the caller's variable as well.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By using the <code>static</code> keyword, which shares the variable with the caller.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the good-coding-practice rule about modifying mutable objects passed as arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Methods shouldn't modify them unless doing so is an inherent part of the method's purpose.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Methods should always make a defensive copy before modifying any argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods should never modify any argument, regardless of purpose.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods should modify arguments whenever it simplifies the code.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method takes an array and sorts it in place. Is that acceptable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, if sorting the array is the method's inherent purpose - otherwise it would be a surprising side effect and bad practice.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No - modifying a passed-in array is always bad practice.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because arrays in Java are passed by value so the caller is unaffected.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method also returns a new sorted array as well.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare passing an <code>int</code> vs. passing an array reference to a method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an <code>int</code>, the method can't affect the caller's variable; with an array reference, the method gets its own copy of the reference but can still mutate the underlying array the caller can see.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>With both, the method receives a copy of the data, so the caller is never affected.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With both, the method can modify the caller's data because Java uses pass-by-reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>int</code> is passed by reference; the array is passed by value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Calling a method causes the flow of control to jump to the start of the method after initializing the parameters. When the method returns, the flow of control returns to the point where the method was called. No code executes in a method after a `return` statement.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the flow of control when a method is called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the parameters are initialized, control jumps to the start of the method body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The caller continues executing in parallel while the method runs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Control stays with the caller until the method finishes, then jumps to the method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM creates a new thread to run the method body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method returns?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Flow of control returns to the point in the caller where the method was called.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method's local variables become visible in the caller's scope.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Control jumps to the start of the enclosing class's first method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program terminates unless another method is already running.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is executed in a method after a <code>return</code> statement runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing - no code in the method executes after a <code>return</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The remaining statements, but their results are discarded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only cleanup code like <code>finally</code> blocks in the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The statements are executed but the return value is locked in.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method has <code>return x;</code> followed by <code>System.out.println("hi");</code>. Does "hi" print?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - the <code>return</code> exits the method immediately, and the compiler will actually flag the <code>println</code> as unreachable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes - statements after <code>return</code> still execute before control returns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the method is <code>void</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>x</code> is <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare calling a method to a "jump and come back" operation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Control jumps into the method body, runs until <code>return</code> (or the end), then comes back to the caller right after the call site.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It's more like a permanent jump - control never returns to the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's like a one-way jump, and the caller must poll for the result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's like a conditional jump that only happens if the method returns a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values are returned from a method using a `return` statement consisting of the keyword `return` followed by an expression that evaluates to a value of the correct type which is then returned from the method. (In a `void` method `return` is only used with no following expression to return early from a method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you return a value from a non-<code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With a <code>return</code> statement: the keyword <code>return</code> followed by an expression of the correct type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By assigning the value to a special variable named <code>result</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By declaring the value as the last statement in the method body, with no keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By using the keyword <code>yield</code> followed by the value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type must the expression after <code>return</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A value of the method's declared return type (or something compatible with it).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Any type - Java converts it automatically to match the declared return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code>, which is then parsed into the correct type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The same type as the method's first parameter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>return</code> used in a <code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With no following expression, to exit the method early.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It cannot be used at all in a <code>void</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With the value <code>null</code>, like <code>return null;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With an empty expression, like <code>return ;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>void</code> method writes <code>return 5;</code>. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile error - a <code>void</code> method can't return a value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method returns <code>5</code>, which is silently discarded by the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method compiles but throws a runtime error on that statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>5</code> becomes the method's side-effect value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>return</code> in a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In non-<code>void</code> methods <code>return</code> must be followed by a value of the right type; in <code>void</code> methods <code>return</code> stands alone and is only used to exit early.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> methods can't use <code>return</code>; non-<code>void</code> methods must use it at the end of the body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both require <code>return</code> followed by a value of the declared return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In <code>void</code> methods <code>return</code> is used to return <code>null</code>; in non-<code>void</code> methods to return a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The value returned by a method is copied, just like method arguments. Again, this means a reference returned by a method can be used to modify object it references.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is a method's return value passed back to the caller?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is copied, just like method arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is passed by reference, so the caller shares the method's value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is boxed into an <code>Object</code> and then unboxed by the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is written to a special return register and read by the caller.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method returns a reference, what can the caller do with it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the reference to modify the object it points to, since both method and caller now hold references to the same object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only read the object's fields - the caller cannot modify it through the returned reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing - the returned reference becomes invalid as soon as the method exits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only create a new object that is a copy of the returned one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does "return value is copied" mean the entire object is copied when returning a reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - only the reference (the pointer) is copied; the underlying object is not duplicated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes - Java always makes a deep copy of the returned object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for mutable objects; immutable ones share a single copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the returned object is of a primitive wrapper type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method returns an internal <code>ArrayList</code>. What's the risk?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller can use the returned reference to modify the list's contents, affecting the object's internal state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>ArrayList</code> becomes unmodifiable after being returned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The returned list is a deep copy, so the caller can't affect the original.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The original <code>ArrayList</code> is garbage-collected as soon as it's returned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare returning an <code>int</code> vs. returning a reference to a mutable object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Returning an <code>int</code> copies a value the caller can't use to affect the method's data; returning a reference copies a pointer the caller can use to mutate the shared object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Returning an <code>int</code> gives the caller a copy; returning a reference gives the caller the only remaining reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Returning a reference is faster because only a pointer is copied, while the <code>int</code> is boxed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both return a copy of the full value, so neither lets the caller affect the method's data.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A method call to a non-`void` method is a kind of expression whose value is the value returned by the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a call to a non-<code>void</code> method, as a language construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression whose value is the value returned by the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A statement whose only purpose is to execute side effects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A declaration that introduces the method into the current scope.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A directive that tells the compiler to inline the method body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the value of the expression <code>Math.sqrt(9)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value returned by <code>Math.sqrt</code> - in this case, <code>3.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>9</code> - the argument that was passed in.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>9.0</code> - the argument converted to a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code> - because <code>Math.sqrt</code> is a <code>static</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you write <code>int x = add(2, 3) + 1;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>add(2, 3)</code> is an expression whose value is the method's return value, so it can be used in arithmetic.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>+ 1</code> is applied to the arguments before the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java automatically adds <code>1</code> to the result of every <code>add</code> call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>add(2, 3)</code> is a statement that modifies <code>x</code> directly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to use a method's result directly as an argument to another method. Can you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes - since non-<code>void</code> calls are expressions, you can nest them like <code>foo(bar())</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No - you must always store the result in a variable first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if both methods return the same type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the outer method is <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a non-<code>void</code> method call to a literal like <code>42</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are expressions that have a value; a literal's value is written directly, while a method call's value is whatever the method returns.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A literal is an expression; a method call is a statement, so they can't be used the same way.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Method calls have side effects while literals do not, which is the key difference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Literals can be used in arithmetic; method calls cannot.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A call to a `void` method can only be for effect and not part of an expression since the method doesn't return any value. They typically do not need a `return` statement and simply return when execution reaches the end of the method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a <code>void</code> method call be used as part of an expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it doesn't return any value, so there's nothing to plug into an expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>void</code> methods cannot be called from outside their class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>void</code> methods always return <code>null</code>, which isn't a valid expression value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java prohibits any method call from being nested inside an expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the only reason to call a <code>void</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For its side effects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To check whether it compiles.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To use its return value in an expression.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To initialize its parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do <code>void</code> methods typically need a <code>return</code> statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No - they usually just return automatically when execution reaches the end of the method body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes - every method in Java requires at least one explicit <code>return</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes - <code>void</code> methods must return <code>null</code> at the end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method has parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might a <code>void</code> method still use <code>return</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To return early from the method before reaching the end of the body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To return a default value like <code>0</code> or <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To skip the next statement in the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To restart the method from the beginning.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what happens at the end of a <code>void</code> method vs. a non-<code>void</code> method with no explicit <code>return</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>void</code> method just returns; a non-<code>void</code> method without a <code>return</code> on some path is a compile error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both implicitly return the last computed value in the method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>void</code> method throws an error; the non-<code>void</code> method returns a default value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both compile fine and return without issue.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Naming methods in method calls</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Within a class, code can reference other methods in the same class simply by their name with the exception that `static` methods cannot call instance methods without an explicit object to invoke the method on. But in non-`static` methods, invoking a method by its simple name is the same as invoking it on `this`, i.e. on the same object the current method was invoked on.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a non-<code>static</code> method, what does calling another method by its simple name (e.g., <code>foo()</code>) implicitly do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It invokes the method on <code>this</code>, the same object the current method was invoked on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It invokes the method on a new instance of the class created just for the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It invokes the method statically, without any object reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It invokes the method on the first parameter of the current method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a <code>static</code> method call an instance method using just the instance method's simple name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>static</code> method has no <code>this</code>, so there is no implicit object to invoke the instance method on; an explicit object reference is required.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>static</code> methods are prohibited from calling any other methods by simple name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because instance methods are not visible to <code>static</code> methods in the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM does not load instance methods until after <code>static</code> methods finish.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Within a class, how do you reference another method defined in the same class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Simply by its name, with the caveat that <code>static</code> methods can't call instance methods without an explicit object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Using <code>this.</code> followed by the method name, even from <code>static</code> methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the class name, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>MyClass.foo()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By importing the method at the top of the file first.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>static</code> method tries to call an instance method by its simple name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile-time error occurs because there is no implicit <code>this</code> object on which to invoke the instance method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The call succeeds, and the instance method runs on a new default object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The call compiles, but throws a <code>NullPointerException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>static</code> method is automatically converted to an instance method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how instance methods and <code>static</code> methods can refer to other methods in the same class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance method can call any other method by simple name (instance calls go through implicit <code>this</code>), but a <code>static</code> method can only call other <code>static</code> methods by simple name; calling instance methods requires an explicit object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both kinds can call any method by simple name; the <code>static</code>/instance distinction only matters across classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Instance methods can call only other instance methods by simple name; <code>static</code> methods can call any method by simple name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither can call methods by simple name - both always require an explicit object or class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Outside a class, `static` methods are typically referenced using the class name, the dot operator, and the name of the method, e.g. `Math.sqrt(2)` to invoke the `static` `sqrt` method in the class `Math`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you typically invoke a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using the class name, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Using the keyword <code>static</code> followed by the method name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By creating an instance of the class and calling the method on that instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using just the method name, since <code>static</code> methods are globally accessible.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code> illustrate about calling <code>static</code> methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>static</code> methods are invoked via the class name (<code>Math</code>) rather than an instance of the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That <code>static</code> methods must be invoked on an instance of the class, like <code>new Math().sqrt(2)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>static</code> method calls always require the <code>this</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the argument to a <code>static</code> method must match the class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is no object needed to call a <code>static</code> method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>static</code> methods belong to the class itself, not to any particular instance, so the class name is enough to locate them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM creates a temporary instance automatically when the call is made.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>static</code> methods ignore their implicit <code>this</code> reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the caller's <code>this</code> is implicitly used as the receiver.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to call a <code>static</code> method <code>max</code> defined in class <code>Helper</code> from a different class. How do you write the call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Write <code>Helper.max(...)</code>: class name, dot, method name, arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>new Helper().max(...)</code>: create an instance, then call the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>max(...)</code>: just the method name, since <code>static</code> methods are globally available.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Write <code>Helper::max(...)</code> using the method reference syntax.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the dot operator play in <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It separates the class name from the <code>static</code> method being invoked on that class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It multiplies the class name by the method's return value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It converts <code>Math</code> into an instance before invoking <code>sqrt</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It separates the arguments from the method name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods in other classes are invoked on a particular object using an expression that evaluates to a reference to the object, the dot operator, and the name of the method, e.g. `s.substring(1)` to invoke the `substring` method on an instance of `String` referenced by the variable `s`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are instance methods in other classes invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using an expression that evaluates to an object reference, the dot operator, and the method name, e.g. <code>s.substring(1)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Using just the class name, the dot operator, and the method name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the keyword <code>new</code> followed by the method name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the <code>this</code> keyword, the dot operator, and the method name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>s.substring(1)</code>, what does <code>s</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression (here, a variable) that evaluates to a reference to a <code>String</code> object on which <code>substring</code> is invoked.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the class that defines <code>substring</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first character of the string being operated on.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An argument to be passed as part of the method call.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the key difference between invoking a <code>static</code> method and an instance method from outside its class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>static</code> methods are invoked via the class name (e.g., <code>Math.sqrt(2)</code>), while instance methods are invoked on an object reference (e.g., <code>s.substring(1)</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code> methods require an object reference; instance methods are called on the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both require an object reference, but <code>static</code> methods also require the class name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither requires any receiver - the dot operator is purely decorative.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the left side of the dot in an instance-method call have to be a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it can be any expression that evaluates to a reference to an object, such as a method return value or a field access.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; only simple variable names are allowed on the left side of the dot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it must be a variable, and it must be declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; it can be any primitive value as well as an object reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you write <code>s.substring(1)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The runtime looks up the object referenced by <code>s</code> and invokes its <code>substring</code> method with argument <code>1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The compiler rewrites the call to <code>String.substring(s, 1)</code> and invokes it statically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new <code>String</code> object is created from <code>s</code>, and <code>substring</code> is called on the copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The value <code>1</code> is assigned to <code>s</code>, and then <code>substring</code> is called with no arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Control constructs allow us to control the flow of execution other than by calling and returning from methods. They fall into to two kinds: conditional control constructs and and looping control constructs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Language features that control the flow of execution beyond just calling and returning from methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Statements that declare variables used across multiple methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Classes that manage the execution of other classes in a program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Comments that the compiler uses to optimize the flow of execution.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the two kinds of control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditional control constructs and looping control constructs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sequential and parallel constructs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitive and reference constructs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code> and instance constructs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Besides control constructs, what other mechanism affects the flow of execution in a program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Calling methods and returning from them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Declaring variables and assigning values to them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Importing classes from other packages.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Adding comments to the source code.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we need control constructs in addition to method calls?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because we need to make decisions and repeat actions within a method, not just transfer control between methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because method calls alone can't express even the simplest sequential logic.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM cannot call methods without a surrounding control construct.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java syntax requires at least one control construct per method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare conditional and looping control constructs at a high level.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditionals choose whether (and which) statements to execute based on a boolean; loops repeat statements zero or more times based on a boolean.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals repeat statements; loops choose whether to execute statements once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both repeat statements, but conditionals are based on integers and loops on booleans.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals affect method calls; loops affect variable assignments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Conditional control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Conditional statements interrupt the normal sequential flow of control from one statement to the next by allowing some code to execute or not depending on the values of a `boolean` condition.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a conditional statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A statement that interrupts sequential flow by executing code only if a <code>boolean</code> condition has a particular value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A statement that runs the same code repeatedly until a <code>boolean</code> condition becomes <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A statement that transfers control to another method based on a <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A statement that declares a <code>boolean</code> variable and assigns it a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "normal" flow of control that conditionals interrupt?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Executing statements sequentially, one after the next, in the order they are written.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Executing statements in parallel across multiple threads.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Executing statements in random order until the method returns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Executing statements repeatedly until a condition becomes <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What determines whether a conditional's body runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of its <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The return type of the enclosing method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of statements inside the body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether any local variables have been assigned values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Could a program that never makes decisions be written without conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; conditionals are only needed when some code should run or be skipped depending on a <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; every Java program requires at least one conditional statement to compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No; even programs that don't make decisions need conditionals to terminate.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the program has no methods at all.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of value must a conditional's condition evaluate to in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>boolean</code> value (<code>true</code> or <code>false</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> - <code>0</code> is false and any nonzero value is true.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> - <code>"true"</code> or <code>"false"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any value - Java converts it to <code>boolean</code> automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A simple `if` statement affect the flow of control by executing the statements in the `if`'s body only if the `if`'s `boolean` condition evaluates to `true`. This provides a one-way selection where a set of statements either is or is not executed, depending on the condition.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "one-way selection"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A conditional in which a set of statements either executes or is skipped, with no alternative branch — provided by a simple <code>if</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A conditional with two branches, where exactly one is always executed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A conditional that can only be entered once per program run.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A conditional whose condition can only be evaluated in one direction.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does a simple <code>if</code>'s body execute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only when the <code>if</code>'s <code>boolean</code> condition evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whenever the enclosing method is called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the <code>if</code>'s condition evaluates to <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When no other <code>if</code> statement has already executed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a simple <code>if</code>'s condition is <code>false</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body is skipped and execution continues with the statement after the <code>if</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The body executes once and then control moves on.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program terminates with an error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body executes as an <code>else</code> branch.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a simple <code>if</code> called "one-way"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because there's only one branch — the body — with no alternative block to run when the condition is <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because its condition can only be tested once per program run.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it has exactly one statement in its body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it only affects one variable in the program.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does a simple <code>if</code> differ from an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A simple <code>if</code> has no alternative path; an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> always executes one of two branches.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A simple <code>if</code> can test multiple conditions; an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> can only test one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> executes both branches; a simple <code>if</code> executes only the body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A simple <code>if</code> runs its body when the condition is <code>false</code>; an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> runs it when the condition is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A two-way selection, written with an `if`/`else`, causes either one set of statements or another to be executed, one when the boolean condition is true and the other when it is false.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a two-way selection?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A conditional that always executes exactly one of two branches depending on a <code>boolean</code> condition, written as <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A conditional that tests two conditions in sequence and runs whichever matches first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A conditional that can be entered from two different points in the program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A conditional whose body contains exactly two statements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, when does the <code>else</code> branch run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the <code>if</code>'s <code>boolean</code> condition evaluates to <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whenever the <code>if</code>'s body has finished executing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the <code>if</code>'s condition is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>if</code>'s body throws an exception.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can both branches of an <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> execute in the same run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; exactly one branch runs based on the condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, if both conditions are <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, the <code>if</code> body always runs, and the <code>else</code> runs afterward if the condition is <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> is inside a loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want to print "even" or "odd" based on a number. Which conditional structure fits?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A two-way selection (<code>if</code>/<code>else</code>), since exactly one of the two messages should print.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A simple <code>if</code>, because only one of the two messages should print.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A multi-way selection with two <code>else if</code> branches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No conditional at all - Java prints the correct label automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare one-way and two-way selection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>One-way (simple <code>if</code>) runs its body or does nothing; two-way (<code>if</code>/<code>else</code>) always runs one of two alternative blocks.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>One-way selection runs its body when the condition is <code>false</code>; two-way runs its body when the condition is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One-way selection can use <code>else</code>; two-way cannot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both always run exactly one branch; the difference is how many conditions they test.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A multi-way selection, written with an `if`, one ore more `else if`s, and optionally a final `else`, chooses one of several sets of statements to execute based on a number of different `boolean` conditions. The code that executes is the body of the first `if` or `else if` whose condition is `true` or the body of the `else` if all the conditions are `false`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a multi-way selection?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>if</code> followed by one or more <code>else if</code>s, and optionally a final <code>else</code>, that selects one of several branches based on multiple conditions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A conditional that runs every branch whose condition is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A conditional that can be entered from multiple points in the program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that tests multiple conditions on each iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which branch of an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body of the first <code>if</code> or <code>else if</code> whose condition is <code>true</code>; if none are <code>true</code>, the final <code>else</code> runs (if present).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Every branch whose condition is <code>true</code>, in order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The last <code>else if</code> whose condition is <code>true</code>, or the <code>else</code> otherwise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the final <code>else</code>, if one is present.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two conditions in an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code> chain are both <code>true</code>, which one's body executes?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only the first one in the chain that evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both - each <code>true</code> condition's body runs in order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The last one in the chain that evaluates to <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither - the chain is ambiguous and no body executes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens in an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain if all conditions are <code>false</code> and there is no final <code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No branch runs; execution just continues after the chain.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error occurs, because every chain must have an <code>else</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first branch runs as a default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime exception is thrown because no branch matched.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare two-way and multi-way selection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two-way chooses between exactly two branches; multi-way chooses among many branches, testing conditions in order and running the body of the first one that's <code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Two-way always runs one of two branches; multi-way always runs every branch in order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Multi-way chooses between exactly two branches; two-way chooses among many branches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both test the same number of conditions; the difference is only in syntax.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Any code can go in the body of an `if` or `else` including other `if`, `if`/`else`, and `if`/`else if`/`else` statements, producing nested conditional statements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are nested conditional statements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditional statements (<code>if</code>, <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>, etc.) that appear inside the body of another <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Conditional statements that share the same <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals that are declared inside a method body rather than at the class level.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals whose bodies are empty but whose conditions are complex.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of code can appear inside the body of an <code>if</code> or <code>else</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any code at all, including other conditional statements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only simple statements, not other conditionals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only method calls and variable assignments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any code except other <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a language-level limit on how deeply you can nest conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; you can nest <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statements arbitrarily deeply because any code is allowed inside their bodies.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; Java allows at most three levels of nesting.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the limit depends on the JVM's stack size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; only <code>static</code> methods can contain nested conditionals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might you nest conditionals?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To make additional decisions only after a prior condition has already selected a branch, expressing more complex decision logic.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make the program run faster by short-circuiting unreachable branches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires every <code>if</code> to contain another <code>if</code> in its body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To combine multiple conditions into a single <code>boolean</code> expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does nesting conditionals relate to the rule that "any code" can go in an <code>if</code> body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Since conditional statements are just code, they are allowed in <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> bodies like any other statement, which is exactly what "nesting" means.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nesting is a special exception to that rule, allowed only for conditionals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nesting is unrelated - it is a separate feature from the general rule about <code>if</code> bodies.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nesting is forbidden by that rule, which only allows non-conditional code inside an <code>if</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Technically `if`/`else if`/`else` statements are just regular `if`/`else` statements with a nested `if`/`else` statement but we write them chained together when we want to express a multi-way selection.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Structurally, what is an <code>if</code>/<code>else if</code>/<code>else</code> chain really?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A regular <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> whose <code>else</code> branch contains another nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> statement.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A brand-new kind of statement that has its own special syntax in the Java grammar.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that tests each condition in turn and runs the first matching body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Several independent <code>if</code> statements written one after another.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do we write <code>else if</code> as if it were its own construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To clearly express a multi-way selection, even though it's really just a nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java has a dedicated <code>else if</code> keyword for multi-way selection.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it's the only way to express more than two branches in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it runs faster than the equivalent nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does Java have a special <code>else if</code> keyword?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>else if</code> is just an <code>else</code> whose body is another <code>if</code> statement, written on the same line by convention.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>else if</code> is a single reserved keyword in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only in newer versions of Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it's an alias for the <code>elif</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does chaining <code>else if</code>s help readability compared to deep nesting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It flattens what would otherwise be increasingly indented nested <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> blocks into a single visually aligned multi-way selection.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It makes the code run faster by avoiding deeply nested method calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It hides the underlying conditionals so readers don't have to understand them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It adds extra braces that make each branch visually distinct.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does writing chained <code>else if</code>s make sense?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you want to express a multi-way selection among several mutually exclusive boolean conditions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When you want all branches to execute if their conditions are <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you need to repeat the same condition several times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the conditions share a common variable on the left side.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Looping control constructs</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Looping control constructs, also called iteration constructs, change the normal flow of control by repeating a sequence of statements zero or more times.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is another name for looping control constructs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iteration constructs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Recursion constructs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Selection constructs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Branching constructs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do loops change the flow of control?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By repeating a sequence of statements zero or more times instead of executing them just once.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By skipping a sequence of statements based on a condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By calling a method that repeats itself automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By running statements in parallel across multiple threads.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a loop's body run zero times?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; if the loop's condition is <code>false</code> on the very first check, the body is never executed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; every loop runs its body at least once before checking the condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>do-while</code> loops can run zero times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the loop uses a <code>break</code> statement on the first iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the minimum and maximum number of times a loop body can run in principle?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero is the minimum; there is no fixed maximum — it can repeat as long as the condition remains <code>true</code>, potentially forever.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>One is the minimum; the maximum is bounded by <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Zero is the minimum and 1000 is the practical maximum imposed by the JVM.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One is the minimum and there is no fixed maximum.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do loops differ from conditionals in how they affect control flow?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conditionals run a block at most once based on a condition; loops can run a block many times, re-checking the condition each iteration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals run a block many times; loops run a block exactly once when the condition is <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals and loops both run their blocks exactly once, but loops always check the condition twice.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Conditionals evaluate the condition after the body; loops evaluate it before the body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In both `while` and `for` loops, a `boolean` expression is evaluated before each iteration of the loop's body, including the first. When the expression evaluates to `true`, the loop body is executed. Then the loop repeats this process until the `boolean` expression evaluates to false.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop's boolean condition evaluated?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before each iteration, including the first one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>After each iteration, but not before the first.</p></distractor>
