      <card>
        <question><p>What happens after a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop executes its body once?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Control returns to the condition; if it's still <code>true</code>, the body runs again, otherwise the loop ends.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Control exits the loop immediately, regardless of the condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Control moves to the next statement after the loop without re-checking.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The condition is evaluated only on every other iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the loop condition in a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop checked after the body or before it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the body, each time — including before the very first iteration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>After the body, so the body always runs at least once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only before the first iteration and never again.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the middle of the body, after the first statement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What ends a <code>while</code> or <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its <code>boolean</code> condition evaluating to <code>false</code> when it is checked.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Reaching the end of the method containing the loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its <code>boolean</code> condition evaluating to <code>true</code> after the body runs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Executing the final statement of the body for the first time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>while</code> and <code>for</code> loops decide whether to run each iteration.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate a <code>boolean</code> expression before each iteration and run the body only when the expression is <code>true</code>; they differ only in how that expression is set up and updated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>while</code> loops check the condition before the body; <code>for</code> loops check it after.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>while</code> loops run the body at least once; <code>for</code> loops may run it zero times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are fundamentally different - <code>while</code> uses boolean logic while <code>for</code> uses integer counters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If the `boolean` expression evaluates to false the first time it is evaluated, the loop body is not executed at all. Conversely, if the `boolean` expression always evaluates to `true`, the loop is an infinite loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a loop's <code>boolean</code> condition is <code>false</code> the first time it's checked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The loop body never executes at all.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop body runs exactly once before the loop exits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error occurs because the loop would be useless.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The loop body runs forever until interrupted.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an infinite loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A loop whose <code>boolean</code> condition always evaluates to <code>true</code>, so the body repeats forever.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A loop that runs exactly <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that has no condition at all.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop whose body contains a <code>return</code> statement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>while (false) { ... }</code> were written, how many times would the body run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero times, because the condition is <code>false</code> on the first check.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>One time, since every loop body runs at least once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>false</code> isn't a valid condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Infinitely, because <code>false</code> is treated as a placeholder.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it possible for a loop body to never run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; if the condition is <code>false</code> the first time it is evaluated, the body is skipped entirely.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; every loop is guaranteed to run its body at least once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the loop contains a <code>return</code> statement on the first line.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for <code>for</code> loops, not <code>while</code> loops.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a loop that runs zero times with an infinite loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A zero-iteration loop has a condition that's <code>false</code> at its first check; an infinite loop has a condition that's always <code>true</code>, so it never stops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A zero-iteration loop has a missing body; an infinite loop has a missing condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A zero-iteration loop uses <code>while</code>; an infinite loop uses <code>for</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are bugs that the compiler will reject.</p></distractor>
