      <card>
        <question><p>How many parts does a <code>while</code> loop have, compared to a <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>while</code> loop has just two parts (condition and body); a <code>for</code> loop has three header parts plus a body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both have exactly two parts: a condition and a body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>while</code> loop has three parts and a <code>for</code> loop has two.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>while</code> loop has one part (the body); a <code>for</code> loop has two (header and body).</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the condition play in a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It's the <code>boolean</code> expression checked before each iteration to decide whether the body runs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It initializes the loop variable before the body runs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It updates the loop variable after each iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's an integer that counts down to zero to stop the loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does a <code>while</code> loop have a built-in initialization or update clause?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it only has a condition and a body, so any initialization or updating must be written separately.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the <code>while</code> keyword implicitly initializes and updates a counter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only the update clause; initialization must be separate.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only the initialization; updates must be separate.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a <code>while</code> loop considered the "simplest" loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it has only two parts — a condition and a body — with no built-in initialization or update mechanism.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because it always runs its body at least once, avoiding condition checks.</p></distractor>
