    <cards>
      <ek>A `while` loop executes by evaluating the condition. If the condition is `true` it then executes the body and repeats, back at the condition. Otherwise the loop ends.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Describe the execution cycle of a <code>while</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate the condition; if <code>true</code>, run the body and go back to evaluate the condition again; if <code>false</code>, end the loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Run the body; then evaluate the condition; if <code>true</code>, exit the loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Evaluate the condition once; then run the body repeatedly forever.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Run the body a fixed number of times, then check the condition.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a <code>while</code> loop do immediately after executing its body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It jumps back to re-evaluate the condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It moves to the statement after the loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It runs the body one more time unconditionally.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It evaluates the condition only every other iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What causes a <code>while</code> loop to terminate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its condition evaluating to <code>false</code> when it is checked.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Reaching a fixed iteration count set by the JVM.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body completing without any errors.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Its condition evaluating to <code>true</code> after the body runs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a <code>while</code> loop's condition starts as <code>false</code>, what is the sequence of steps?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate condition → it's <code>false</code> → loop ends immediately without running the body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Run body once then evaluate condition; it's <code>false</code>, then exit.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Evaluate condition; it's <code>false</code>, then throw an exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Skip the condition, run the body forever until interrupted.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what a <code>while</code> loop does when the condition is <code>true</code> versus <code>false</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On <code>true</code>, it executes the body and re-checks the condition; on <code>false</code>, it exits the loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On <code>true</code>, it skips the body; on <code>false</code>, it runs the body once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On <code>true</code>, it enters an infinite loop; on <code>false</code>, it throws an error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On <code>true</code>, it exits; on <code>false</code>, it re-checks the condition.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Both the condition and the body will usually refer to variables defined before the loop. If the condition depends on the values of one or more variables and the body contains code that changes those variables, the condition can eventually become `false` and the loop will stop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where are the variables referenced by a <code>while</code> loop's condition and body usually defined?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the loop itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inside the loop's body, on the first iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inside the loop's condition itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a separate method called by the loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the body of a <code>while</code> loop usually modify variables that appear in the condition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So the condition can eventually become <code>false</code>, allowing the loop to terminate.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So the condition's initial value is computed correctly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires loop-condition variables to be reassigned each iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To avoid a compile error about unused variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>while</code> loop's body never changes any variable used in the condition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The condition's value never changes, so the loop either runs forever or never runs at all.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs exactly once and then exits automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler detects this and refuses to compile the code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM throws an <code>InfiniteLoopException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the relationship between the condition and body needed for a <code>while</code> loop to stop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body must eventually cause the variables in the condition to take values that make it <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The condition must be evaluated only once, at the start.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body must contain a <code>break</code> statement on every path.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The condition's variables must remain constant throughout the loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>while</code> loop checks <code>i &lt; 10</code> but the body never changes <code>i</code>. What's the result?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An infinite loop if <code>i</code> starts less than 10, or a zero-iteration loop if <code>i</code> starts at 10 or more.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop always runs exactly 10 iterations regardless of <code>i</code>'s initial value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler rejects the loop as unreachable code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs once and then exits no matter what.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`while` loops are most useful when you do not know, before the loop starts, exactly how many times it needs to run.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>while</code> loop most useful?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you don't know ahead of time how many iterations will be needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When you know exactly how many iterations are needed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you want to iterate over every element of an array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you need to run a block of code exactly once.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why prefer a <code>while</code> loop over a <code>for</code> loop for reading input until a sentinel?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you don't know in advance how many inputs there will be, which is exactly what <code>while</code> loops are designed for.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>for</code> loops cannot read user input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>while</code> loops always run their body at least once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>for</code> loops require an array to iterate over.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you already know you need exactly 100 iterations, is a <code>while</code> loop the best fit?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not usually; a <code>for</code> loop is typically a better fit when the number of iterations is known in advance.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>while</code> loops are always preferred.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>for</code> loops can't count to exactly 100.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It doesn't matter - both are equally idiomatic for known counts.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give a scenario where a <code>while</code> loop is more natural than a <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly asking the user for input until they type "quit", since the number of prompts isn't known beforehand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Iterating from 1 to 10 and printing each number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Visiting every element of a fixed-length array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Computing the sum of the first 50 integers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare when to use <code>while</code> versus <code>for</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>while</code> when the number of iterations isn't known in advance; use <code>for</code> when you know how many times to iterate (e.g., over an array).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>while</code> for arrays; use <code>for</code> for user input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>while</code> loops are faster than <code>for</code> loops, so prefer them when performance matters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are identical in every way and the choice is purely stylistic.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `for` loop consists of a header and a body.</ek>

