      <card>
        <question><p>What does the condition of a <code>for</code> loop typically involve?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An expression involving the loop variable, e.g., comparing it to a limit.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An assignment to the loop variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method call with side effects but no return value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constant <code>boolean</code> literal.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)</code>, what does the condition <code>i &lt; n</code> control?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether the loop runs another iteration, checked before each one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether the loop variable gets incremented on each iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The initial value of <code>i</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether <code>n</code> is a valid array length.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare where the condition is evaluated in a <code>for</code> loop versus a <code>while</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both evaluate the condition before each iteration; the difference is only that the <code>for</code> loop's condition is written inside the loop header alongside initialization and update.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for</code> evaluates it after the body; <code>while</code> evaluates it before.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for</code> evaluates it once; <code>while</code> evaluates it on every iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They evaluate at completely different times, making them incompatible.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The update clause runs after the body of the loop and just before the next evaluation of the condition. The update clause usually updates the loop variable, typically by incrementing or decrementing it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When does the update clause of a <code>for</code> loop run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the body runs and just before the next evaluation of the condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Before the body runs, on each iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Once, at the very start of the loop, before initialization.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the condition becomes <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the update clause typically do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Updates the loop variable, often by incrementing or decrementing it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Checks whether the loop should continue.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declares and initializes a new loop variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Runs the body of the loop one extra time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does the update clause run before the first iteration's body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; it runs only after each body execution, before the next condition check.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it runs once before initialization.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; it always runs before the first condition check.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the condition is initially <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++)</code>, when does <code>i++</code> execute relative to the body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After each execution of the body and just before <code>i &lt; 10</code> is checked again.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Before each body execution, immediately after the condition check.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only once, at the very start of the loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only after the loop finishes completely.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the update clause typically change the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that the condition can eventually become <code>false</code> and the loop can terminate.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To reset the loop variable to its initial value for the next iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires the update clause to contain an assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To avoid a warning about unused variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of the `for` loop is executed after the condition is evaluated and before the update clause. Code within the body can refer to the loop variable declared in the loop header.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When does the body of a <code>for</code> loop execute relative to the condition and update clause?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the condition is evaluated (and found <code>true</code>) and before the update clause runs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Before the condition is evaluated and before the update clause.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>After the update clause and before the condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Simultaneously with the update clause.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can the body of a <code>for</code> loop refer to the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; the loop variable declared in the header is in scope inside the body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; the loop variable is only accessible inside the header.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the loop variable is declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only read access is allowed; writes cause a compile error.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the order of operations in a single iteration of a <code>for</code> loop (excluding initialization)?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Evaluate condition → if <code>true</code>, execute body → execute update clause → repeat.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Evaluate condition, execute update, execute body, repeat.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Execute body, evaluate condition, execute update, repeat.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Execute update, execute body, evaluate condition, repeat.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that the body can refer to the loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets the body use the current iteration's value, for example to index into an array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It lets the body modify the loop variable to skip iterations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It avoids a compile warning about an unused variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's required so the update clause can read its current value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the roles of the body and the update clause in a <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The body does the actual work each iteration; the update clause adjusts the loop variable so the condition can eventually stop the loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both do the same work, but the body runs first and the update runs last.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The update does the work; the body just holds a placeholder.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The body runs the update clause as its first statement on every iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`for` loops are typically used when we know, before the loop starts, how many times we want to iterate, e.g. once for every character in a string or element of an array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is a <code>for</code> loop typically preferred?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the number of iterations is known before the loop starts.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When you need to read input until a sentinel value is entered.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the loop might never execute.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the loop body contains a <code>return</code> statement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give two common examples where a <code>for</code> loop is appropriate.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterating once per character in a string and once per element of an array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Reading user input until EOF and waiting for a network response.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Polling a sensor indefinitely and handling an infinite event stream.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Running a background task and waiting on a semaphore.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a <code>for</code> loop a good match for iterating over an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you know the array's length up front, so you know exactly how many times to loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>for</code> loops are the only loops that can use an index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because arrays require a <code>for</code> loop for compile-time type safety.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>while</code> loops cannot access array elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: reading until the user types "quit". Is a <code>for</code> loop the best fit?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the number of iterations isn't known in advance, so a <code>while</code> loop is more natural.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>for</code> loops are always more concise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because you can use a <code>break</code> statement inside the <code>for</code> loop body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; both loops are equivalent so either works perfectly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare typical uses of <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for</code> loops suit known-count iteration like array traversal; <code>while</code> loops suit unknown-count iteration that depends on runtime conditions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for</code> loops are for user input; <code>while</code> loops are for arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for</code> loops are for <code>boolean</code> conditions; <code>while</code> loops are for integer counters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They have identical use cases and the choice is arbitrary.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A `for` loop can be rewritten into an equivalent `while` loop and vice versa, though the `while` loop will need some code before the loop proper to perform the role of the `for` loop's initialization clause and the update clause will need to appear in the body of the `while` loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can any <code>for</code> loop be rewritten as a <code>while</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops are interchangeable in expressive power.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; <code>for</code> loops can do things <code>while</code> loops cannot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>for</code> loop has a simple integer counter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>for</code> loop's body contains no method calls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When rewriting a <code>for</code> loop as a <code>while</code> loop, where does the initialization go?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the <code>while</code> loop, as code that runs once before the loop begins.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inside the <code>while</code> loop's body, at the start.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inside the <code>while</code> loop's condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's omitted because <code>while</code> loops handle initialization automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When rewriting a <code>for</code> loop as a <code>while</code> loop, where does the update clause go?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inside the body of the <code>while</code> loop, typically at the end so it runs before the next condition check.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Before the <code>while</code> loop, so it runs once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inside the <code>while</code> loop's condition itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It's omitted because <code>while</code> loops handle updates automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> are equivalent, why have both?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>for</code> loops bundle initialization, condition, and update together, making known-count iteration more concise and readable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>for</code> loops are faster at runtime than <code>while</code> loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>while</code> loops were added later to support user input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because only <code>for</code> loops can iterate over arrays.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the structural trade-off between <code>for</code> and <code>while</code> loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for</code> loops centralize loop control in the header; <code>while</code> loops spread it out — initialization before the loop and updates within the body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for</code> loops require more lines of code; <code>while</code> loops are always shorter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>while</code> loops bundle loop control in the header; <code>for</code> loops spread it out.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>There is no trade-off - the two are syntactically identical.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The enhanced `for` loop provides a concise way to traverse an array or an `ArrayList` in the common case when we only need to deal with one element at a time and don't care about the index.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the enhanced <code>for</code> loop provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A concise way to traverse an array or <code>ArrayList</code> when you only need one element at a time and don't care about the index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A way to iterate over an array backwards.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that always runs the body exactly once per call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A replacement for <code>while</code> loops that uses fewer keywords.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop a good choice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you need to process each element of an array or <code>ArrayList</code> in order and don't need its index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When you need to modify elements of the array as you traverse it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you need to iterate in reverse order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you need to skip every other element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop a poor choice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When you need the index of each element, or need to modify the collection's structure during traversal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When the collection has fewer than 10 elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the elements are primitives rather than references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When you only want to read each element once without modifying it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of things can you traverse with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop in AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only primitive arrays, not object arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>ArrayList</code>s, not regular arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any <code>Iterable</code>, but that's outside the AP CSA subset.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an enhanced <code>for</code> loop with a traditional <code>for</code> loop over an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traditional <code>for</code> loop gives you an index (and thus access to neighbors); an enhanced <code>for</code> loop gives you each element directly but no index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An enhanced <code>for</code> loop always runs faster than a traditional one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A traditional <code>for</code> loop can only read elements; an enhanced loop can write to them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are completely equivalent in every situation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The enhanced `for` loop consists of a simplified header consisting of just a variable declaration, a colon, and an expression that evaluates to an array or an `ArrayList`, and a body.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the parts of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop header?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable declaration, a colon, and an expression that evaluates to an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An initialization, a condition, and an update clause separated by semicolons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop variable and a length, separated by a semicolon.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Just a collection expression, with the variable declared inside the body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What separates the variable declaration from the array expression in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A colon (<code>:</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A semicolon (<code>;</code>).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A comma (<code>,</code>).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An arrow (<code>-&gt;</code>).</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must the expression to the right of the colon in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array or an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>boolean</code> condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An integer count of iterations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> to iterate character by character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the header of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop with a traditional <code>for</code> loop header.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The enhanced header has just a variable declaration and a collection expression separated by a colon; the traditional header has initialization, condition, and update separated by semicolons.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are identical in syntax but the enhanced version runs faster.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The enhanced header uses semicolons, and the traditional uses colons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The traditional header omits the collection expression, which the enhanced version adds.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the enhanced <code>for</code> loop header called "simplified"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it has fewer parts than a traditional <code>for</code> header — no explicit initialization, condition, or update.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because it can only iterate over primitive arrays, not object arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it requires fewer curly braces than a traditional <code>for</code> loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it automatically parallelizes the loop across multiple threads.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of an enhanced `for` loop is executed once for each element of the array or `ArrayList` with the variable assigned the value of each element in turn.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How many times does the body of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once for each element of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Exactly <code>length - 1</code> times.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Once in total, regardless of the collection's size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Twice per element - once to read and once to update.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does the loop variable take on each iteration of an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of the current element of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The index of the current element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the array itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length of the remaining portion of the array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In what order does an enhanced <code>for</code> loop visit elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the order of the array or <code>ArrayList</code>, from first element to last.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In reverse order, from last element to first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a random order determined by the JVM.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In sorted order based on the element values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to manually increment any index in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the loop automatically advances through the elements on its own.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; you must declare an index variable and increment it manually.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for <code>ArrayList</code>s; arrays handle it automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the array has more than 10 elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how the loop variable is used in a traditional versus enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In a traditional <code>for</code> loop it's typically an index used to access elements; in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop it directly holds each element's value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In both, the loop variable holds the current element directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In both, the loop variable is an index used to access elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a traditional <code>for</code> loop the variable is an element; in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop it is an index.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The loop variable in an enhanced `for` loop is just a regular variable. Assigning a new value to it has no effect on the array itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of variable is the loop variable in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just a regular local variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the underlying array element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>final</code> constant that cannot be reassigned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A special iteration variable that the compiler handles differently.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you assign a new value to an enhanced <code>for</code> loop's loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only the local variable changes; the underlying array or <code>ArrayList</code> is not modified.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The underlying array is updated to reflect the new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error occurs because the loop variable is implicitly <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>UnsupportedOperationException</code> is thrown at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you modify array elements by assigning to the loop variable in an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; the loop variable is a copy of each element's value, so assigning to it doesn't affect the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; assigning to the loop variable overwrites the array element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for primitive arrays, not reference arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you also call <code>array.update()</code> after the assignment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: inside an enhanced <code>for</code> loop <code>for (int x : arr)</code> over an <code>int[] arr</code>, you write <code>x = 0</code> in the loop body. What happens to the array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing; only the local loop variable <code>x</code> changes, and the array is unaffected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Every element of <code>arr</code> becomes 0.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>x</code> is implicitly <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the current element of <code>arr</code> is set to 0; others are unchanged.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the inability to modify array elements via an enhanced <code>for</code> loop's loop variable affect when you'd choose an enhanced <code>for</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You wouldn't choose it when you need to replace elements of the array; a traditional indexed <code>for</code> loop is required for that.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You'd prefer the enhanced <code>for</code> loop because it's more efficient for writes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It doesn't matter; both loops handle element replacement identically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You'd always choose the enhanced loop because it supports both reads and writes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The body of a loop can contain any statements including other loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of statements can go inside a loop's body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any statements, including other loops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only simple expressions, not other statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only statements that don't change any variables in the condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only declarations, not executable statements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are nested loops a special language feature or just a consequence of general rules?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A consequence of the general rule that any statement, including a loop, can appear in a loop's body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A special language feature that must be explicitly enabled.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A special syntax reserved for 2D arrays only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime optimization handled by the JVM automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a limit to how deeply loops can be nested?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No language-level limit — loops can contain other loops arbitrarily deeply.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; Java limits nesting to 8 levels deep.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; only two levels of nesting are allowed in AP CSA.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the JVM throws a <code>StackOverflowError</code> at 100 levels.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a loop's body contain conditional statements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes; a loop's body can contain any statements, including <code>if</code>/<code>else</code> chains and other loops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; loops and conditionals cannot be mixed in the same block.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>if</code> statements are allowed; <code>else</code> clauses are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the conditional is the last statement in the body.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it useful that loop bodies can contain other loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets you express iteration over multi-dimensional structures like 2D arrays or combinations of elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It's a special feature for implementing recursive algorithms.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It lets the inner loop run in parallel with the outer loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It allows loops to share a single loop variable efficiently.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Nested loops are just loops that appear in the body of another loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Loops that appear in the body of another loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Loops that share the same loop variable with another loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Loops that run in parallel alongside other loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Loops that call themselves recursively.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is there a special syntax for nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; they're just ordinary loops written inside another loop's body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; you must use the <code>nested</code> keyword before the inner loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; nested loops must be enclosed in extra curly braces.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; the inner loop must be declared <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give a common use case for nested loops.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterating over a 2D array, with the outer loop over rows and the inner loop over columns.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Reading a single line of user input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Computing the square root of a number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Checking whether a string contains a character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested loop, which loop is "outer" and which is "inner"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer loop is the one that contains the other; the inner loop is written inside the outer loop's body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop is the innermost one; the inner is the outermost.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop is whichever loop runs first; the inner runs second.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop has a longer condition; the inner has a shorter one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does nesting require the inner and outer loops to be the same kind?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; you can nest any kind of loop inside any other — e.g., a <code>for</code> loop inside a <code>while</code> loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; nested loops must both be <code>for</code> loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes; nested loops must both be <code>while</code> loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, unless the outer loop uses an enhanced <code>for</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a loop is nested inside another loop, the inner loop must complete before the outer loop can continue.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In nested loops, what must happen before the outer loop continues to its next iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The inner loop must run to completion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop must complete before the inner loop can start.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both loops run simultaneously, one iteration each.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The inner loop runs only once, on the first outer iteration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If the inner loop runs 5 times and the outer loop runs 3 times, how many times does the inner loop's body execute in total?</p></question>
        <answer><p>15 times — 5 inner iterations for each of the 3 outer iterations.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>5 times - the inner loop only runs once regardless of the outer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>8 times - 5 inner iterations plus 3 outer iterations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>3 times - the outer loop controls the total count.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does nesting loops multiply their iteration counts?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the inner loop restarts and completes fully on every single iteration of the outer loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM optimizes nested loops by multiplying them together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because each iteration of the outer loop skips the inner loop once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler flattens nested loops into a single multiplication.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the order of execution in nested loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outer loop starts an iteration → inner loop runs from start to finish → outer loop advances to its next iteration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inner loop starts an iteration, outer loop runs from start to finish, inner loop advances.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outer and inner loops alternate single iterations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outer loop runs completely, inner loop runs completely, done.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare one iteration of an outer loop with one iteration of an inner loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p>One outer iteration corresponds to the inner loop running in its entirety; one inner iteration is just a single pass through the inner body.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>One outer iteration is a single body pass; one inner iteration runs the entire outer loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both iterations do exactly the same amount of work.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One outer iteration corresponds to one inner iteration, always in lockstep.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Since executing a `return` statement always immediately returns from the current method, it can be used to break out of a loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How can a <code>return</code> statement be used to exit a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By returning from the enclosing method, which immediately stops execution of the loop as a side effect.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By setting the loop's condition to <code>false</code> implicitly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By throwing an exception that the loop catches and handles.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By jumping to the line just after the loop's closing brace.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the effect of <code>return</code> when executed inside a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It immediately exits not just the loop but the entire enclosing method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It exits only the innermost loop, leaving outer loops running.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It exits the current iteration and moves to the next.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It exits the current block but continues the loop from the top.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>return</code> be used to exit only the innermost of several nested loops while continuing the outer one?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No; <code>return</code> exits the entire method, so all enclosing loops stop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; <code>return</code> behaves like <code>break</code> and only exits one loop level.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the inner loop is labeled.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when combined with a <code>continue</code> statement in the outer loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can <code>return</code> be used to break out of a loop even though it isn't a loop-specific construct?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because returning from the method abandons whatever code was running, including any loops in progress.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler rewrites <code>return</code> into a <code>break</code> statement inside loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>return</code> only works when placed at the end of a loop body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>return</code> is a special keyword that only affects the innermost loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're searching an array for a target and want to stop as soon as you find it. How can <code>return</code> help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You can <code>return</code> the found value (or its index) directly from inside the loop, which immediately ends both the loop and the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You can use <code>return</code> to restart the search from the beginning.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You can <code>return</code> before the loop starts to skip it entirely.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>return</code> only ends the loop but the method keeps running.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>"Off by one" errors occur when the iteration statement loops one time too many or one time too few, for instance for (int i = 0; i &lt;= s.length(); i++) rather than for (int i = 0; i &lt; s.length(); i++) when iterating over the characters of a string.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an "off by one" error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A bug where a loop runs one iteration too many or too few.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A bug where the loop variable is declared with the wrong type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime error that occurs when an array is empty.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error caused by mismatched parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt;= s.length(); i++)</code> likely buggy when iterating over a string's characters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because valid character indices are <code>0</code> to <code>s.length() - 1</code>; using <code>&lt;=</code> lets <code>i</code> reach <code>s.length()</code>, which is out of bounds.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>s.length()</code> is a method and can't be compared with <code>&lt;=</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because string indices must start at 1, not 0.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>&lt;=</code> can only be used with integer literals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct loop condition for iterating over every character of a string by index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>i &lt; s.length()</code>, starting from <code>i = 0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>i &lt;= s.length()</code>, starting from <code>i = 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>i &lt; s.length() - 1</code>, starting from <code>i = 0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>i != s.length()</code>, starting from <code>i = 1</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>An off-by-one error can cause either too few or too many iterations — what's a symptom of each?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Too few: the last element is skipped. Too many: an extra iteration runs, often triggering an index-out-of-bounds error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Too few: an extra element is processed. Too many: the last element is skipped.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Too few: the loop never runs. Too many: the loop runs forever.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both cases cause a compile-time error.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the choice between <code>&lt;</code> and <code>&lt;=</code> in a loop condition relate to off-by-one errors?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Switching between them changes the number of iterations by exactly one, which is where off-by-one bugs often come from.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are interchangeable and never cause off-by-one errors.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Switching between them changes the number of iterations by two, not one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>&lt;=</code> is always correct; <code>&lt;</code> always causes off-by-one bugs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Unintended infinite loops occur when the condition never becomes false, often due to a bug in the update code.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What causes an unintended infinite loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A loop whose condition never becomes <code>false</code>, often because of a bug in the code that should be updating the variables it depends on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A loop whose body is empty.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop with a condition that is syntactically invalid.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that contains a <code>return</code> statement on every path.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where do unintended infinite loops usually originate?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the update code — either it's missing, wrong, or not affecting the variables used in the condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In the initialization clause, which sets the variables to invalid starting values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the condition itself, which is always a constant <code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the body, which always throws an exception that is caught by the loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>while (i &lt; 10)</code> loop that forgets to change <code>i</code> in the body. What happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If <code>i</code> starts below 10, it's an unintended infinite loop because the condition never becomes <code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs exactly 10 times regardless of <code>i</code>'s starting value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler rejects the loop because <code>i</code> is never updated.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs once and then exits automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you avoid unintended infinite loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Make sure each iteration makes progress toward the condition becoming <code>false</code> by correctly updating the variables it depends on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Always use a <code>for</code> loop instead of a <code>while</code> loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Add a <code>return</code> statement at the end of every loop body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Set the condition to a constant <code>false</code> as a safety measure.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an intentional infinite loop with an unintended one.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An intentional infinite loop is written knowingly (e.g., for a server loop), while an unintended one is a bug — typically caused by faulty update logic.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An intentional infinite loop uses <code>for</code>; an unintended one uses <code>while</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are bugs that the compiler will reject.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are indistinguishable at runtime and at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Arrays</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arrays are a reference type that collects multiple values of a given type into a single value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type that collects multiple values of a given type into a single value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A primitive type that holds a single value of a given type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns multiple values at once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword that declares a group of related variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is an array a primitive type or a reference type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A primitive type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither - it's a special category of its own.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both, depending on the element type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a single array hold values of different types (e.g. an <code>int</code> and a <code>String</code>)?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. An array collects multiple values of a given (single) type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; any array can hold any mix of types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the types are all primitive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only arrays of <code>Object</code> can hold mixed types safely.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does an array differ from a single variable of a primitive type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single variable holds one value, while an array bundles multiple values of the same type into one reference value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An array holds one value and a single variable holds many; they are opposites.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An array is a primitive type while a single variable is a reference type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>There is no meaningful difference - both store one value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>You want one value that contains 20 <code>double</code>s. What kind of thing do you need?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array of <code>double</code>, which is a reference type collecting all 20 values into a single value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single <code>double</code> variable capable of holding 20 values at once.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> of <code>double</code>, which is the only way to store multiple values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> containing 20 numbers separated by commas.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The values in an array are called the elements of the array or sometimes the components.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the values inside an array called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The elements (or sometimes the components) of the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The indices of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The references to the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The slots of the array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is "component" a valid synonym for "element" when talking about arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, the values in an array are sometimes called components.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; only <code>element</code> is a valid term.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for arrays of objects, not primitive arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in <code>ArrayList</code>, not in plain arrays.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If someone says "the third component of the array", what are they referring to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The third value (element) stored in the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The length of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The type of the array's elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that operates on the array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Fill in the blank: the values in an array are called its ___.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Elements (or components).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Indices.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>References.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Fields.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare: "element" vs. "component" of an array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They refer to the same thing — the individual values stored in the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An element is a primitive value; a component is a reference value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A component is the index, while an element is the value stored at that index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They refer to completely different concepts in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Array elements can be either primitive or reference values.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of values can array elements be?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Either primitive values or reference values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only primitive values, never references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only reference values, never primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only values of type <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you have an array of <code>String</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Array elements can be reference values, including <code>String</code> references.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; <code>String</code>s must be stored in an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>String</code>s are all the same length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the array is declared as <code>Object[]</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an array hold <code>int</code> values directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Array elements can be primitive values like <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; <code>int</code> values must be wrapped in <code>Integer</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the array is declared as <code>Object[]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in an <code>ArrayList</code>, not a plain array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you have an array of arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer array's elements are reference values pointing to other array objects — this is allowed because elements can be references.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer array's elements are copies of the inner arrays' values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java doesn't allow arrays of arrays; you must use a 2D primitive type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer array automatically flattens its elements into a single dimension.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an array of <code>int</code> with an array of <code>Integer</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first stores primitive <code>int</code> values directly; the second stores references to <code>Integer</code> objects. Both are allowed because array elements can be primitive or reference values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int[]</code> stores references to <code>int</code> objects; <code>Integer[]</code> stores primitive values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are identical in every way because Java auto-boxes <code>int</code> to <code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int[]</code> can hold <code>null</code> values; <code>Integer[]</code> cannot.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The size of an array is established at the time of its creation and cannot be changed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When is the size of an array determined?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the time the array is created.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At compile time, based on the variable declaration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first time an element is accessed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the array variable is declared, before any values are assigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you grow an existing array to hold more elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Once created, an array's size cannot be changed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; use the <code>resize</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only by assigning to <code>xs.length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for arrays of primitive types, not reference types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you need more room than the array currently has?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You must create a new, larger array and copy elements over — the original array's size cannot be changed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>xs.grow(n)</code> to expand the array in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Assign a larger value to <code>xs.length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Arrays automatically grow when you assign past the end.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: You create <code>new int[5]</code> and later want it to hold 10 values. What are your options?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Create a new array of size 10 and copy values from the old one. You cannot resize the original.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Assign <code>xs.length = 10;</code> to grow it in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>xs.resize(10)</code> to expand the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use a <code>for</code> loop to append five new elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare array size with <code>ArrayList</code> size.</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array's size is fixed at creation and cannot change; an <code>ArrayList</code> can grow and shrink as elements are added or removed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An array can grow and shrink; an <code>ArrayList</code> has a fixed size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both have a fixed size set at creation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both can grow and shrink, but only <code>ArrayList</code> can shrink to zero.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When an array is created using the keyword `new` and a size (e.g. `new int[10]`) all of its elements are initialized with the standard zero value for the element type: 0 for `int`s, `0.0` for `double`s, `false` for `boolean`s, and `null` for all reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What value do the elements of <code>new int[10]</code> start out as?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All 0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>All uninitialized; reading them throws an exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All 1.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Unspecified values - whatever was in memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default initial value of each element in <code>new double[5]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0.0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Uninitialized; reading throws an exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Double.NaN</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does each element of <code>new boolean[3]</code> contain right after creation?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Uninitialized; reading throws an exception.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the initial values of elements in <code>new String[4]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All <code>null</code>, since <code>String</code> is a reference type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>All empty strings <code>""</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All uninitialized; reading throws an exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All the literal string <code>"null"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the initial element values of <code>new int[3]</code> vs. <code>new Integer[3]</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new int[3]</code> starts with three <code>0</code>s (primitive zero); <code>new Integer[3]</code> starts with three <code>null</code>s (reference default).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both start with three <code>0</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both start with three <code>null</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>new int[3]</code> starts with <code>null</code>s; <code>new Integer[3]</code> starts with <code>0</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Initializer lists can be used to create arrays containing specific values, e.g. `new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }`. Arrays created this way have their length set to the number of elements provided.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an array initializer list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A syntax like <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code> that creates an array already filled with the specific values listed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns a fresh array of a given size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>for</code> loop that assigns each element one at a time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword that declares an array without specifying its size.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the length of the array created by <code>new int[] { 42, 52, 103 }</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>3 — the length equals the number of elements provided.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>0 - initializer lists don't set the length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Unknown until the array is fully initialized at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Always 10, the default length for an initializer list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How else can you create an array besides using <code>new Type[size]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With an initializer list, e.g. <code>new int[] { 1, 2, 3 }</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By assigning a value directly to <code>xs.length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By calling <code>Array.create(Type, size)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By declaring a variable without the <code>new</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the length when you use <code>new String[] { "a", "b", "c", "d" }</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The array's length is set to 4, the number of elements in the initializer list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The length is 0; initializer lists don't affect length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length is unknown until runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length is always 10 for string arrays.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>new int[3]</code> and <code>new int[] { 0, 0, 0 }</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both create a 3-element <code>int</code> array with all zeros. The first relies on default initialization; the second uses an explicit initializer list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the first creates a 3-element array; the second creates a 1-element array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They produce different lengths and cannot be compared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first creates three <code>null</code>s; the second creates three <code>0</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Arrays have a read-only instance variable `length` which gives the number of elements in the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you find the number of elements in an array <code>xs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>xs.length</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>xs.length()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>xs.size()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>xs.count</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>length</code> on an array a method or a field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance variable (field), so you write <code>xs.length</code>, not <code>xs.length()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method, so you write <code>xs.length()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static field, so you write <code>Array.length(xs)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A built-in operator, so you write <code>length xs</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you assign to <code>xs.length</code> to resize an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>length</code> is read-only.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes; assigning to <code>xs.length</code> resizes the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the new length is smaller than the current one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for arrays of primitive types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you write <code>xs.length = 5;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A compile error, because <code>length</code> is a read-only instance variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The array is resized to length 5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime exception is thrown.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The assignment silently fails with no effect.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare getting the size of an array vs. a <code>String</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For an array you use the field <code>xs.length</code>; for a <code>String</code> you call the method <code>s.length()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>For both you use the field <code>.length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>For both you call the method <code>.length()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>For an array you call <code>.size()</code>; for a <code>String</code> you use <code>.length</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The elements of an array are accessed using square brackets ([]) and an index, e.g. `xs[0]` accesses the 0th element of the array `xs`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What syntax is used to access an element of an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Square brackets with an index, e.g. <code>xs[0]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Parentheses with an index, e.g. <code>xs(0)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The dot operator with the index, e.g. <code>xs.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Curly braces with an index, e.g. <code>xs{0}</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>xs[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The 0th (first) element of the array <code>xs</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The length of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element at position 1, since indices start at 1.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the entire array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are array indexes in Java 0-based or 1-based?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0-based — the first element is at index 0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>1-based - the first element is at index 1.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Either, depending on how the array was created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>0-based for primitive arrays, 1-based for object arrays.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you access the element right after <code>xs[0]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using <code>xs[1]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Using <code>xs[0 + 1]</code>, which evaluates to <code>xs[0]</code> again.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using <code>xs.next</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using <code>xs[0].next()</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>xs[0]</code> and <code>xs.length</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[0]</code> uses an index in square brackets to read an element; <code>xs.length</code> reads the read-only field that stores the array's size.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use square brackets to access parts of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>xs[0]</code> reads the length; <code>xs.length</code> reads the first element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are equivalent and interchangeable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The valid indexes for an array are 0 through length - 1, inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the valid indexes for an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0 through <code>length - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>1 through <code>length</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>0 through <code>length</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>1 through <code>length - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For an array of length 10, what is the largest valid index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>9, since valid indexes go from 0 to <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>10, since valid indexes go from 0 to <code>length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>11, since Java arrays include a sentinel element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>1, since only the first element is always valid.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the smallest valid index for any array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>1.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>-1.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Depends on the array's length.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>An array <code>xs</code> has length 5. Is <code>xs[5]</code> valid?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. The valid indexes are 0 through 4 (length - 1).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. The valid indexes are 1 through 5.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Arrays allow access to <code>length</code> as a sentinel.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the range of valid indexes for arrays of length 1 vs. length 100.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Length 1: only index 0 is valid. Length 100: indexes 0 through 99 are valid. In both cases the range is 0 to <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Length 1: indexes 0 and 1 are valid. Length 100: indexes 0 through 100 are valid.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Length 1: no indexes are valid. Length 100: only index 0 is valid.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Length 1 and length 100 both have valid indexes starting at 1.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Using an invalid index (less than 0 or greater than length - 1) will cause an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you use an out-of-range array index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>IndexOutOfRangeException</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>NullPointerException</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IllegalArgumentException</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which indexes count as "invalid" for an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any index less than 0 or greater than <code>length - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only indexes greater than <code>length</code>; negative indexes wrap around.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only negative indexes; indexes past the end silently return <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only indexes that exceed <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens at runtime if you access <code>xs[-1]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The last element of the array is returned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>NullPointerException</code> is thrown.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error occurs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a loop iterates up to <code>xs.length</code> (inclusive) and reads <code>xs[i]</code>. What goes wrong?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the last iteration <code>i == xs.length</code>, which is past the last valid index, so an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop silently stops one iteration early without error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error is raised because the condition is wrong.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs forever until interrupted.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a compile-time error with the error from using <code>xs[xs.length]</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[xs.length]</code> compiles fine but throws an <code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> at runtime — it's a runtime error, not a compile-time error.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It's a compile-time error; the code will not compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws <code>NullPointerException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It silently returns a default value with no error.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An array access expression is like a variable in that it can be used to obtain a value or as a place that can be assigned a value with = or any applicable compound assignment operator (e.g. `+=` or `++` on on an array of numbers).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In what two ways can an array access expression like <code>xs[i]</code> be used?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As a value to read, or as a place to assign a value (the left side of <code>=</code> or a compound assignment).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As a method call or as a field access.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a declaration or as a method definition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a condition or as a loop variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>xs[3] = 7;</code> legal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. An array access can appear on the left side of an assignment, just like a variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No; array elements are read-only after creation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>xs</code> is declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>xs[3]</code> was previously assigned a non-default value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>xs[i]++</code> on an array of <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element at index <code>i</code> is incremented by 1, because array accesses support compound assignment and increment operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>++</code> can't be used on array elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index <code>i</code> is incremented, not the element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both the element and the index are incremented.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to add 5 to <code>xs[2]</code>. Write a compound assignment.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>xs[2] += 5;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>xs + 2 = 5;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>xs[2] = xs + 5;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>xs.add(2, 5);</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how a regular variable and an array access expression are used.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be read to obtain a value and both can be assigned to with <code>=</code> or compound operators like <code>+=</code> and <code>++</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only regular variables can be assigned to; array accesses are read-only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only array accesses can be assigned to; regular variables are read-only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They behave completely differently and cannot be mixed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Looping over the individual elements of an array is also called traversing the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "traversing" an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Looping over the individual elements of the array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Creating a new array that contains the same elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sorting the array's elements in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Copying the array to a different variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What word describes the process of visiting each element of an array one by one?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Indexing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Iterating over the array's length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Accessing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method uses a <code>for</code> loop to examine every element of an array, what is it doing to the array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sorting it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Copying it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Resizing it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to print every element of <code>xs</code>. What general operation are you performing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal of the array <code>xs</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A sorting of <code>xs</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A resize of <code>xs</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A copy of <code>xs</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "looping over an array" with "traversing an array".</p></question>
        <answer><p>They mean the same thing — traversing is just the formal name for looping over each element of an array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Looping over means visiting each element; traversing means copying the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Traversing only applies to <code>ArrayList</code>, while looping only applies to arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are unrelated operations with different outcomes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Traversing an array with a standard `for` or `while` loop requires using an index to access each element of the array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When you traverse an array with a standard <code>for</code> or <code>while</code> loop, how do you get at each element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You use an index variable and access elements with <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The loop automatically provides each element as a variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You call a method like <code>xs.next()</code> on every iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You compare the loop variable directly to each element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does a standard <code>for</code> or <code>while</code> loop need an index when traversing an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because these loops don't automatically pull out each element — you must use an index to access <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the loop variable is itself the element and can't be used as an index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>for</code> loops require three clauses by definition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because array elements can only be accessed through method calls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; xs.length; i++)</code>, what is <code>i</code> used for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As the index to access each element of the array, e.g. <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As the value of each element of the array directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As the running total of the sum.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a <code>boolean</code> flag that stops the loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're writing a <code>while</code> loop to sum an array. What variable must you maintain besides the running sum?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An index variable so you can access each element as <code>xs[i]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>boolean</code> flag to stop the loop when the sum is correct.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A separate array to hold intermediate sums.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the last element of the array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a standard <code>for</code> loop traversal with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop traversal.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A standard <code>for</code> loop uses an index to access <code>xs[i]</code>; an enhanced <code>for</code> loop gives you each element directly without an index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use an index to access elements; neither gives direct access.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both give direct access to elements; neither uses an index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A standard <code>for</code> loop gives direct access; an enhanced <code>for</code> loop uses an index.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>2d arrays</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays. Therefore, the way 2d arrays are created and indexed is similar to 1d array objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are 2d arrays actually stored in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As arrays of arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As a single contiguous block of memory addressed by row and column.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a dedicated <code>Matrix</code> object with rows and columns as fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a linked list of rows, each pointing to a linked list of elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is creating and indexing a 2d array similar to a 1d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a 2d array is really just a 1d array whose elements happen to be 1d arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because a 2d array shares the same underlying memory layout as a 1d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because both are stored as contiguous blocks with a built-in row/column header.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java automatically flattens 2d arrays into 1d arrays at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If 2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays, what is the type of a single "row" of an <code>int[][]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int[]</code> — a 1d array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> — a single primitive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int[][]</code> — still a 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code> — the generic row type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you have <code>int[][] grid</code>. What does <code>grid[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first inner array (row), which is itself a 1d array of <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The first <code>int</code> value in the whole array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the entire <code>int[][]</code> itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first column of the grid as a 1d array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a 2d array and a 1d array structurally.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 2d array is a 1d array whose elements are themselves 1d arrays, so operations on it resemble 1d-array operations applied at two levels.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A 2d array is a completely different data structure from a 1d array and shares no operations with it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 2d array is a 1d array with twice as much memory allocated per slot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 2d array is a single flat 1d array accessed with a computed index <code>r * cols + c</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>It is equally correct to think of a 2d array as a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is another accurate way to describe a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As a grid-shaped object with built-in row and column properties.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a single 1d array of length rows times columns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a tree where each row is a child of a root node.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is it wrong to describe a 2d array as a "1d array of arrays"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. That's an equally correct way to think about it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. A 2d array is strictly rectangular and is not a 1d array of anything.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when every row has the same length; otherwise it is misleading.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the element type is a primitive; for references it is wrong.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you view a 2d array as a 1d array whose elements happen to be arrays, what does that imply about its element type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each element of the outer array is itself an array — the element type is an array type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Each element is a primitive value of the base type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Each element is a reference to the enclosing 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Each element is an <code>Object</code> regardless of the declared type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to swap two rows of a 2d array. How does thinking of the 2d array as a 1d array whose elements are arrays help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Since the outer array's elements are just array references, swapping two rows is the same as swapping two elements of a 1d array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You have to rebuild the 2d array from scratch with the rows in the new order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You must copy every element of both rows individually into a temporary 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You can only swap rows if the 2d array is rectangular.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "2d array" with "1d array of 1d arrays".</p></question>
        <answer><p>They describe the same structure — a 2d array is literally implemented as a 1d array whose elements are 1d arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are only the same when the 2d array is square.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 2d array is a 1d array of values laid out row by row, while a 1d array of 1d arrays is a separate nested structure.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 1d array of 1d arrays requires an extra wrapper class, while a 2d array does not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The square brackets `[row][col]` are used to access and modify an element in a 2d array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What syntax accesses a single element in a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two sets of square brackets: <code>arr[row][col]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single pair of square brackets containing two comma-separated indexes: <code>arr[row, col]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A single index multiplied out: <code>arr[row * cols + col]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A dot between the two indexes: <code>arr.row.col</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you set element at row 2, column 3 of <code>grid</code> to 7?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>grid[2][3] = 7;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>grid[2, 3] = 7;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>grid[3][2] = 7;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>grid.set(2, 3, 7);</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the first pair of brackets select in <code>arr[row][col]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The row — the inner 1d array stored at index <code>row</code> of the outer array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The individual element at row and column zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The column — the inner 1d array stored at index <code>row</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The total number of rows in the outer array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to read the top-left corner of a 2d array <code>arr</code>. What expression do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[0][0]</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[1][1]</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr.first()</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[0, 0]</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare accessing an element of a 1d array vs. a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>1d uses one index in brackets (<code>xs[i]</code>); 2d uses two (<code>arr[row][col]</code>), one for the outer array and one for the inner.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A 1d access uses <code>xs.get(i)</code> and a 2d access uses <code>arr.get(row, col)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 1d access is constant time but a 2d access is linear in the number of rows.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both use a single pair of brackets; 2d arrays just expect a two-part index inside.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays can be initialized with specific values by writing a nested initialization expression like `{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you initialize a 2d array with specific values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With a nested initializer expression, e.g. <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>With a flat list and an explicit shape, e.g. <code>{ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 }</code> of size 2-by-3.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By calling <code>new int[][]</code> and then assigning each cell one at a time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By using a single initializer like <code>{ 1, 2, 3 }</code> that Java automatically reshapes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does each inner <code>{ ... }</code> in <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single row (a 1d inner array) of the 2d array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single column of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A single element of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A separate, unrelated 1d array that is not part of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many rows and columns does the array from <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code> have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>2 rows and 3 columns.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>3 rows and 2 columns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>6 rows and 1 column.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>1 row and 6 columns.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a 2d array representing a 2x2 identity matrix of <code>int</code>. Write an initializer.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>{ { 1, 0 }, { 0, 1 } }</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>{ 1, 0, 0, 1 }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>{ { 1, 1 }, { 0, 0 } }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>{ { 0, 1 }, { 1, 0 } }</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare initializer lists for 1d and 2d arrays.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 1d initializer is a single list like <code>{ 1, 2, 3 }</code>; a 2d initializer nests lists, with each inner list being a row: <code>{ { 1, 2, 3 }, { 4, 5, 6 } }</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A 1d initializer uses parentheses like <code>(1, 2, 3)</code> while a 2d initializer uses braces.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both use a single flat list; the 2d version just has more elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 2d initializer must have commas between rows written as <code>; </code>, not <code>, </code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>2d arrays are typically traversed using nested loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are 2d arrays typically traversed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>With nested loops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>With a single loop and a computed index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With recursion instead of iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With a single enhanced <code>for</code> loop over the whole array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you need more than one loop to traverse a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you need to visit each element in each row — one loop iterates rows and the other iterates within each row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java's <code>for</code> loop can only increment one variable at a time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because each row must be copied into a 1d array before it can be processed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because 2d arrays cannot be accessed with a single index expression.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you use only a single loop over a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You visit only the rows (inner arrays), not the individual elements inside each row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program throws a runtime exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You visit the first element of each row but skip the rest.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You visit each element exactly once, but in an unpredictable order.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: print every element of a 2d <code>int</code> array. What loop structure do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A nested loop — an outer loop over the rows and an inner loop over the columns of each row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single loop that iterates over all elements using a computed index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Three nested loops — one for rows, one for columns, and one for elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A recursive method that calls itself once per row.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare traversing a 1d array with traversing a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A 1d traversal needs one loop; a 2d traversal typically uses nested loops, one for the outer array and one for each inner array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use exactly the same code; 2d arrays are really 1d arrays under the hood.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 1d traversal uses an enhanced <code>for</code> loop while a 2d traversal must use indexed loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A 1d traversal is O(n) but a 2d traversal is O(log n).</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Since 2d arrays are stored as arrays of arrays, the outer loop iterates over the array whose elements are 1d arrays and the inner loop iterates over the elements of the 1d array.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested 2d-array traversal, what does the outer loop iterate over?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer array, whose elements are 1d arrays (rows).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The individual elements of the 2d array, one at a time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The columns of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The total number of elements in the 2d array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the inner loop iterate over when traversing a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The elements of the current 1d inner array (the row selected by the outer loop).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The entire outer array again.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The columns of the 2d array as a whole.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the first element of the current row.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the nested-loop structure used to traverse a 2d array mirror its "array of arrays" storage?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each level of the nested loop matches one level of the nested structure: the outer loop walks the outer array, the inner loop walks an inner array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires two loops for any array access that uses two brackets.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because nested loops are the only kind of loops Java allows inside one another.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the outer array must be copied before the inner array can be read.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: given <code>int[][] arr</code>, what is a natural meaning for the outer-loop variable and inner-loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer-loop variable picks a row (a 1d <code>int[]</code>), and the inner-loop variable picks a column index within that row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer-loop variable picks a column, and the inner-loop variable picks a row.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both loop variables pick individual <code>int</code> values directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer-loop variable is the array itself, and the inner-loop variable is the current row.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare what each level of a nested loop "sees" in a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer loop sees rows (1d arrays); the inner loop sees the individual elements within a single row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop sees columns and the inner loop sees rows.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both loops see individual elements; the nesting just repeats the work.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer loop sees the array as a whole and the inner loop sees rows.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In the outer loop of nested enhanced `for` loops used to traverse a 2d array, the type of the loop variable must be the type of each row, i.e. a 1d array. In the inner loop, the type of the loop variable is the actual element type.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a nested enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>int[][]</code>, what type is the outer loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int[]</code> — the type of each row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code> — each element of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int[][]</code> — the whole 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code> — the generic row type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the same nested enhanced <code>for</code> loop over an <code>int[][]</code>, what type is the inner loop variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> — the element type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int[]</code> — the row type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int[][]</code> — the whole 2d array again.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code> — the boxed element type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why must the outer enhanced-<code>for</code> variable be a 1d array type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the 2d array's elements are themselves 1d arrays, so that's what you get on each iteration of the outer loop.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires the outer variable of any enhanced <code>for</code> to be a reference type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the outer loop actually iterates over columns, which are 1d arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the enhanced <code>for</code> loop can only iterate over arrays of objects, not primitives.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: write the headers of a nested enhanced <code>for</code> over <code>double[][] table</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (double[] row : table) { for (double v : row) { ... } }</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for (double v : table) { for (double[] row : v) { ... } }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for (double[][] row : table) { for (double v : row) { ... } }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; table.length; i++) { for (double v : table) { ... } }</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare outer vs. inner loop variable types in a nested enhanced <code>for</code> over a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outer variable has the row type (a 1d array); the inner variable has the element type of that row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The outer variable has the element type and the inner variable has the row type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both variables have the row type (a 1d array).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The outer variable has the 2d array type and the inner variable has the row type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Typically, and always on the AP exam, 2d arrays are arranged with the outer array holding 1d arrays representing the rows of the 2d array. Thus to access the element at row `r` and column `c`, we use `arr[r][c]`. This form is called "row-major order".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "row-major order" for 2d arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An arrangement where the outer array holds 1d arrays that represent rows, so element at row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code> is <code>arr[r][c]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An arrangement where elements are stored column by column, so <code>arr[c][r]</code> gives row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An arrangement where each row is stored as a separate object, not an array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An arrangement where the first index is the column and the second is the row.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>On the AP exam, how are 2d arrays always arranged?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In row-major order: the outer array holds rows, so <code>arr[r][c]</code> accesses row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In column-major order: the outer array holds columns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a single flat 1d array indexed by <code>r * cols + c</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In whichever order the programmer chooses, with no standard convention.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In row-major order, what does the first index of <code>arr[r][c]</code> select?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The column.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The total number of rows.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element's position in a flattened 1d view of the array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: in row-major order, how do you access the element in the 3rd row and 5th column?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[2][4]</code> — remembering that indexes are 0-based.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[3][5]</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[4][2]</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr(2, 4)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the meaning of the two indexes in row-major order.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first index is the row number and the second is the column number within that row.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The first index is the column number and the second is the row number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two indexes are interchangeable — either one can come first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first index is the flat position and the second is the offset within that position.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>It is, however, possible to think of a 2d array as representing an array of columns in which case to get the element at row `r` and column `c` you would write `arr[c][r]`. This is called "column-major order".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "column-major order" for a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Treating the outer array as holding columns instead of rows, so the element at row <code>r</code>, column <code>c</code> is <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Storing the 2d array as a single flat 1d array laid out column by column.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An arrangement where every column must have the same length as every row.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An arrangement where rows and columns are both stored separately and merged on access.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In column-major order, how do you access the element at row <code>r</code> and column <code>c</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[r][c]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr[r, c]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>arr.get(r).get(c)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the outer array represent in column-major order?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The columns of the 2d array.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The rows of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The individual elements of the 2d array, in column-first order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A single column as a 1d array regardless of which one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: if a 2d array <code>arr</code> is being used in column-major order, what does <code>arr[0]</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The first column of the 2d array (as a 1d array of its entries).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The first row of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The top-left element of the 2d array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the whole 2d array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare row-major and column-major order.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In row-major order the outer array holds rows and you write <code>arr[r][c]</code>; in column-major order the outer array holds columns and you write <code>arr[c][r]</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Row-major order uses <code>arr[r][c]</code> and column-major order uses <code>arr[r, c]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In row-major order the inner arrays are rows; in column-major order the inner arrays are individual elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Row-major order is used in Java; column-major order is not possible in Java at all.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All algorithms that work with 1d arrays will work with 2d arrays, as long as they apply to arrays whose elements are arrays.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do 1d-array algorithms also work on 2d arrays?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a 2d array is just a 1d array whose elements are arrays, so any 1d-array algorithm applies — it just operates on elements that happen to be arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java automatically translates 1d-array algorithms into 2d-array algorithms at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because every 2d array has exactly the same number of elements as a 1d array of the same total size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because 1d and 2d arrays both implement the same <code>Iterable</code> interface.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What condition must a 1d-array algorithm meet to work on a 2d array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It must apply to arrays whose elements are themselves arrays.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It must only use the enhanced <code>for</code> loop and not indexed access.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be written recursively rather than iteratively.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must already know the number of rows and columns ahead of time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you apply a 1d-array "find the max element" algorithm to a 2d <code>int</code> array without adjustment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It treats each row (a 1d array reference) as an element, which isn't meaningful for finding a max <code>int</code>; you'd need to apply the algorithm at the inner level too.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It correctly finds the largest <code>int</code> in the entire 2d array on its own.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>ClassCastException</code> because rows are not <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns only the max of the first row and ignores all other rows.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to reverse the order of rows in a 2d array. Can you reuse a 1d-array reverse algorithm?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. A 1d-array reverse applied to the outer array swaps its elements (the row references), effectively reversing the rows.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. Reversing a 2d array requires a special nested reversal algorithm.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if every row has the same length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but it reverses the elements within each row instead of the row order.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare applying a 1d algorithm to a 1d array vs. the outer level of a 2d array.</p></question>
        <answer><p>On a 1d array it manipulates individual values; on the outer level of a 2d array it manipulates entire rows (1d arrays), because those are the outer array's elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On a 1d array it accesses rows; on a 2d array it accesses columns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On a 1d array it is constant time; on the outer level of a 2d array it becomes quadratic.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>On a 1d array it manipulates references; on the outer level of a 2d array it manipulates primitive values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A class defines a common structure for many objects. The structure is made up of variables, constructors, and methods which, collectively, are called the "members" of a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a class define?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A common structure for many objects, made up of variables, constructors, and methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single object and its current state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A fixed list of variables only, without methods or constructors.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A set of static methods that can be called without creating objects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the "members" of a class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The variables, constructors, and methods of the class, collectively.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the instance variables of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the methods of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class's name, package, and access modifier.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two objects are instances of the same class, what do they share?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They share the same structure: the same set of variables, constructors, and methods defined by the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They share the same values for their instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They share a single copy of all their instance variables in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They share the same name but can have completely different methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write a new class in a Java program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You define a template that specifies what variables, constructors, and methods any object of that class will have.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You create a single shared object that all other code uses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You only define a type; no variables, constructors, or methods are introduced.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You replace an existing built-in type of the same name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class to its instances.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class is a blueprint defining structure (members); instances are actual objects created from that blueprint.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A class is a special kind of instance that serves as a prototype for all others.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Instances are blueprints and classes are the concrete objects created from them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class and its instances are the same thing; "instance" is just another word for "class".</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Defining a class also defines a new type that can be used anywhere a type is needed: in variable declarations, as the return type of a method, or as the type of element on an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What else does defining a class create besides a template for objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new type that can be used anywhere a type is needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A new package that groups related classes together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new constructor that can be used without the <code>new</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new keyword that Java treats as a reserved word.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name three places you can use a class as a type.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In variable declarations, as a method return type, and as the element type of an array or <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In constructors, in static initializers, and in comments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in method bodies and nowhere else.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In import statements, in file names, and in the <code>package</code> declaration.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>Point p;</code> after defining a <code>Point</code> class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You declare a variable whose type is the new <code>Point</code> type introduced by the class definition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You create a new <code>Point</code> object immediately.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You call the <code>Point</code> constructor with no arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You declare a static reference to the <code>Point</code> class itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a method to return a <code>Student</code>. What must exist first?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>Student</code> class must be defined, which also defines <code>Student</code> as a type usable as a return type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A pre-existing <code>Student</code> object must be available to copy from.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>Student</code> interface must be defined separately from the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Student</code> type must be imported from <code>java.lang</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a user-defined class type similar to a primitive type like <code>int</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be used anywhere a type is needed: in variable declarations, method return types, parameters, and array element types.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are primitive types and are stored directly in memory rather than by reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are automatically initialized to zero when declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both support the same arithmetic operators like <code>+</code> and <code>-</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object is a single instance of a class whose data lives somewhere in memory distinct from all other objects.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A single instance of a class whose data lives in memory distinct from all other objects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A copy of a class stored at a specific memory address.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A variable that refers to a class definition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A template from which instances are created.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two objects are the same class, do they share the same memory for their data?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, each object's data lives in its own distinct location in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, all objects of a class share one region of memory for their data.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class has only static fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only until one of them changes an instance variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens in memory when you create a new object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A distinct region of memory is allocated to hold that object's data, separate from all other objects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The existing memory of another object is reused for the new one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference is added to a shared pool of objects of that class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No memory is allocated until the first instance variable is assigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "class" and "object" as concepts.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class is a definition of structure; an object is a concrete instance of that class with its own data in memory.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A class is an object created from another class; an object is the class that created it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class is a runtime value; an object is a compile-time definition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class and an object are identical — the terms are interchangeable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can two <code>Point</code> objects hold different x and y values at the same time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because each object has its own distinct memory storing its own copy of the instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because all instance variables are actually stored in the class itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java's garbage collector assigns each object a unique copy on demand.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Point</code> has separate static fields for each possible x and y value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title><code>static</code> members</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Variables and methods can be either static, marked with the `static` keyword, or non-static, without that keyword. Non-static members are also known as "instance variables" and "instance methods".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What keyword marks a member as static?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>static</code> keyword.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>final</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>class</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>public</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are non-static members also called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables and instance methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Class variables and class methods only.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Shared variables and shared methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Global variables and global methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method declaration does not have the <code>static</code> keyword, what kind of method is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An instance method (non-static).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A static method by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An abstract method that must be overridden.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constructor, not a method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you see <code>private int count;</code> in a class. Static or instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variable, because there is no <code>static</code> keyword.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static variable, because <code>private</code> implies <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither — it is a local variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static variable, because all <code>int</code> fields are static in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static and instance members by how they are declared.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static members include the <code>static</code> keyword in their declaration; instance members do not.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static members use the <code>class</code> keyword and instance members use the <code>instance</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static members are declared outside the class body and instance members inside it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static members require the <code>final</code> keyword while instance members do not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static variables and methods can be marked as either `public` or `private` and then marked with the `static` keyword before the variable type or the return type of a method, e.g. `public static int`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does <code>static</code> go relative to <code>public</code> or <code>private</code> and the type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>After the access modifier and before the variable type or return type, e.g. <code>public static int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Before the access modifier, e.g. <code>static public int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>After the type, e.g. <code>public int static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At the end of the declaration, after the variable name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a static method be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Static members can be either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. Static methods must always be <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class itself is also marked <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method takes no arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the declaration <code>public static int count</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It declares a public static variable named <code>count</code> of type <code>int</code> that belongs to the class itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It declares a public instance variable of type <code>int</code> named <code>count</code> that each object has its own copy of.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It declares a public constant named <code>count</code> whose value cannot change.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It declares a public method named <code>count</code> that returns an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to declare a private static <code>double</code> method named <code>rate()</code>. How do you start the declaration?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private static double rate()</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>static private double rate()</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>private double static rate()</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>private rate() static double</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the syntax for declaring a static field vs. an instance field.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They look the same except the static field includes the <code>static</code> keyword between the access modifier and the type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They look exactly the same — the only difference is where the variable is stored.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static field must use the <code>final</code> keyword, while an instance field must not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A static field has no access modifier, while an instance field requires one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each static variable represents a single value stored in the class itself and shared by all instances of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where is a static variable's value stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In the class itself, not in any particular instance.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In the first instance created, and shared with later instances.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a separate hidden object called the "static instance".</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In each instance, but the values are kept in sync automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you create 10 instances of a class with a static variable, how many copies of that variable exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>One, shared by all instances.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Ten, one per instance, but each is initialized to the same value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Zero until the class explicitly allocates them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>One per instance plus one in the class itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when one instance changes a static variable's value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All instances see the change, because they all share the same single value stored in the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the instance that made the change sees the new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new static variable is created for that instance while others keep the old one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The change is rejected because static variables cannot be reassigned.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want every <code>Counter</code> object to share a running total. Static or instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static, so all instances share one value stored in the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Instance, so each <code>Counter</code> has its own independent total.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Instance, because static variables cannot be modified after initialization.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither — use a local variable inside a static method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static variables to instance variables in terms of storage.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each instance variable has its own per-object value; a static variable has one value stored in the class and shared by all instances.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Each instance variable has one value shared by all instances; each static variable has a per-object value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both store one value per object; static variables just use different syntax.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both store one value per class; instance variables just use different syntax.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static methods can only access static variables and call other static methods.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What can a static method directly access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only static variables and other static methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only instance variables and other instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All members of the class, both static and instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only local variables and parameters; no class members at all.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't a static method directly use an instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because a static method is not tied to any particular instance, so there is no specific object whose instance variable it would access.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because static methods run before any instances exist, so there is nothing to access.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because instance variables are stored in a separate memory region that static methods cannot reach.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>static</code> keyword makes all variables read-only to the method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to reference an instance variable directly from inside a static method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The code won't compile, because a static method has no implicit instance to access the variable from.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but always reads the value from the first instance ever created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It reads the value from the most recently created instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles and reads a default value based on the variable's type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a static method needs to call another method in the same class. What must be true of that other method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It must also be static (to be called directly without an instance).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It must be an instance method that can be called on a new object created inside the static method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It can be any method, static or instance — the compiler will add the object automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be declared <code>public</code> regardless of whether it is static.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare static and instance methods in terms of what they can access.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods can access both static and instance members; static methods can only directly access static members.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both can access all members directly; only their calling syntax differs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Instance methods can only access instance members; static methods can access both.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither can access instance variables without a getter method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Static members are typically accessed with the class name and the dot operator, e.g. `Math.PI` and `Math.abs()`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are static members typically accessed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using the class name and the dot operator, e.g. <code>Math.PI</code> or <code>Math.abs()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Using the <code>new</code> keyword, e.g. <code>new Math.abs()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using an instance of the class, e.g. <code>m.PI</code> where <code>m</code> is a <code>Math</code> object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the <code>static</code> keyword as a prefix, e.g. <code>static Math.PI</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.PI</code> access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A static variable named <code>PI</code> defined in the <code>Math</code> class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An instance variable named <code>PI</code> on a default <code>Math</code> object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns the value of pi.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constant local variable in whatever method is calling it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens conceptually when you write <code>Math.abs(-5)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You call the static <code>abs</code> method on the <code>Math</code> class itself, not on any instance.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>You create a new <code>Math</code> object whose <code>abs</code> method is immediately called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You call an instance method named <code>abs</code> on a hidden instance of <code>Math</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You cast <code>-5</code> to a <code>Math</code> object and then to its absolute value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class <code>Counter</code> has a static method <code>reset()</code>. How do you call it from another class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Counter.reset();</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>new Counter().reset();</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>reset.Counter();</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Counter::reset();</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the typical way of calling static vs. instance methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods are called on the class name (<code>Math.abs()</code>); instance methods are called on an object reference (<code>p.getX()</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are called on the class name; the difference is only whether arguments are required.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods are called with <code>new</code>; instance methods are called with the dot operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods need an object reference as a first argument; instance methods do not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Instance variables</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object's state is stored in its instance variables and each object has its own values its instance variable.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where is an object's state stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In its instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In its static variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the class itself, shared across all objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a separate state object associated with the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do two different objects of the same class share instance variable values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, each object has its own values for its instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, all instances of a class automatically share the same values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the instance variables are marked <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for primitive types; reference types are shared.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you change one object's instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only that object's state changes; other objects of the same class are unaffected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The change applies to every object of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The change is rejected unless the variable is marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new object is created with the updated state and the old one is discarded.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>Point p1</code> has x=3 and <code>Point p2</code> has x=7. Why can they differ?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>x</code> is an instance variable, so each <code>Point</code> object has its own copy.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>x</code> is a local variable inside the <code>Point</code> constructor, so each call produces a new value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Point</code> is a static class and Java assigns different copies to each instance automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java re-runs the constructor every time an instance variable is read.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "state" and "instance variables".</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance variables are the storage; the state of an object is the collective values currently held in those variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Instance variables describe behavior; state describes what methods the object has.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>State is the name of the class; instance variables are the members inside it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>State and instance variables are two different words for the methods of a class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance variables create a "has-a" relationship between the object and the values stored in its instance variables, as in a `Point` has an x and y value. (This is often contrasted to the "is-a" relationship created when one class `extends` another.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of relationship do instance variables create?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A "has-a" relationship between the object and the values stored in its instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An "is-a" relationship between the object and the values stored in its instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A "uses-a" relationship that only exists when a method runs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No relationship at all — instance variables are independent of the object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an example of a "has-a" relationship?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>Point</code> has an x value and a y value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>Student</code> is a <code>Person</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>Dog</code> barks.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>Circle</code> can be drawn.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is an "is-a" relationship?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The relationship created when one class <code>extends</code> another (inheritance).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The relationship between an object and its instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The relationship between a class and its static members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The relationship between a method and its parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Car</code> class has an <code>Engine</code> instance variable. What kind of relationship is this?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A "has-a" relationship: a <code>Car</code> has an <code>Engine</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An "is-a" relationship: a <code>Car</code> is an <code>Engine</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A "uses-a" relationship that only applies while the engine is running.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No relationship — instance variables never create relationships between classes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "has-a" and "is-a" relationships.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Has-a" comes from instance variables (composition); "is-a" comes from one class <code>extends</code>ing another (inheritance).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both come from instance variables — "has-a" for primitives and "is-a" for references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>"Is-a" comes from composition and "has-a" comes from inheritance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same relationship described in two different ways.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance variables can be marked as either `public` or `private` before the variable type, e.g `private int n`. Typically they are made `private`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What access modifiers can be applied to instance variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>public</code>; instance variables cannot be <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>, <code>private</code>, or <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code> or <code>volatile</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are instance variables typically public or private?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Typically <code>public</code>, so any code can read and write them directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Typically <code>static</code>, so they can be shared by all objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Typically <code>final</code>, so they cannot be changed once set.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the access modifier go in a declaration like <code>private int n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Before the variable type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>After the variable name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside the class's constructor, never in the field declaration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Between the variable type and the variable name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to prevent code outside the class from directly reading or writing a field. How do you declare it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Mark it <code>private</code>, e.g. <code>private int n;</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Mark it <code>public</code>, so that only methods can modify it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Mark it <code>static</code>, so that outside code gets a shared copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Mark it <code>final</code>, so that outside code cannot assign to it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do programmers usually prefer <code>private</code> instance variables to <code>public</code> ones?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To hide implementation details and protect the object's state from being changed directly by outside code.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To save memory, because <code>private</code> fields take less space than <code>public</code> ones.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java only supports getters and setters on <code>private</code> fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To make the fields accessible from any class in the program.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Constructors</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are invoked to create objects. A constructor's signature consists of the constructor name, which always matches the class name, and a parameter list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a constructor's signature consist of?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The constructor name (which always matches the class name) and a parameter list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The constructor name (which may differ from the class name) and a return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A return type, a parameter list, and the <code>new</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the class name; constructors never have parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must a constructor's name always match?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the package the class belongs to.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The return type of the constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The name of the first instance variable declared in the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a constructor is invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new object is created.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A new class is created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An existing object is copied and reinitialized.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The constructor runs only if no other instance of the class exists.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class is named <code>Point</code>. What must its constructors be named?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Point</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>new</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Anything, as long as it ends with <code>Constructor</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The lowercase form of the class name, e.g. <code>point</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a constructor's signature to a regular method's signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both have a name and a parameter list, but a constructor's name must match the class name and it has no return type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both have a return type, but a constructor's return type is always the class itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constructor's signature includes a <code>static</code> keyword; a method's does not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constructor has only a name; a method has both a name and a parameter list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Every object is created by calling a constructor using the keyword `new` followed by the class name and an argument list that corresponds to one of the class's constructors.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What keyword is used to create a new object?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>create</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>alloc</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>class</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What follows the <code>new</code> keyword in an object creation expression?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class name and an argument list matching one of the class's constructors.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A return type followed by the class name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An instance of the class already in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>static</code> keyword and a method name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>new Point(3, 4)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java creates a new <code>Point</code> object by calling the <code>Point</code> constructor that takes two arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Java copies an existing <code>Point</code> object with x=3 and y=4 and returns the copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java declares a static <code>Point</code> with coordinates (3, 4) that all code shares.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java calls a static method named <code>Point</code> that returns an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class <code>Dog</code> has a constructor <code>Dog(String name)</code>. How do you create a new <code>Dog</code> named "Rex"?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>new Dog("Rex")</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Dog d = Dog("Rex");</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Dog d = new Dog.name("Rex");</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>new Dog Rex;</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does Java know which constructor to call when you use <code>new</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It matches the argument list to one of the class's constructors by the number and types of arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It always calls the first constructor declared in the class, regardless of arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It calls the constructor whose name most closely matches the variable name on the left side.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It calls each constructor in turn until one succeeds.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The job of a constructor is to initialize the state of an object and leave it in a usable state. Often constructors assign the values passed as arguments to the constructor to the object's instance variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the job of a constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To initialize the state of a new object and leave it in a usable state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To allocate memory for a new object and nothing else — initialization is done later.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To create the class itself so that instances can be made.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To register the new object in a global list of all instances.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do constructors often do with their arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Assign the argument values to the object's instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Ignore them and rely on Java's default values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return them to the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Print them to the console for debugging.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a constructor fails to initialize an object's state?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object may be left in an unusable or invalid state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program will not compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The object is silently replaced with a null reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java will automatically assign sensible values based on the class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> constructor takes <code>int x</code> and <code>int y</code>. What should it typically do inside the body?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Assign <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> to the corresponding instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Print the values of <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return a new <code>Point</code> object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declare <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> as new instance variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a constructor's job to a regular method's job.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A regular method performs behavior on an existing object; a constructor's job is specifically to initialize a new object's state so it is usable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are invoked on existing objects; the only difference is the name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A constructor returns a value like any other method; its job is just to compute that value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A regular method creates objects and a constructor performs behavior on them.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors have parameter lists that work just like method parameter lists, defining local variables that are initialized with the values of the arguments passed to a call to the constructor. The arguments should provide the data needed to initialize the object's state.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do constructor parameter lists compare to method parameter lists?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They work the same way: each parameter is a local variable initialized with the value of the corresponding argument.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are completely different — constructor parameters are permanent fields of the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They work the same, but constructor parameters are always <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They work the same, but constructor parameters are stored in the class itself rather than on the stack.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What should the arguments passed to a constructor provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The data needed to initialize the object's state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The name of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The return type of the constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to another object to copy.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to constructor parameters when the constructor is called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are created as local variables and initialized with the argument values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They become new instance variables of the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are stored in the class itself and shared by all objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are discarded and the constructor body runs without access to them.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a <code>Circle</code> constructor that sets the radius. What should its parameter list include?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A parameter for the radius, e.g. <code>Circle(double radius)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single <code>Circle</code> parameter, e.g. <code>Circle(Circle c)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No parameters; the radius must be set with a setter afterward.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Two parameters — one for the center and one for the radius.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are constructor parameters visible outside the constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, they are local variables scoped to the constructor body, just like method parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, they remain accessible as instance variables of the new object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, they become static variables of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as they are marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When no constructor is written, Java provides a no-argument constructor and all instance variables are set to the default value for their type. (0 for int, 0.0 for double, false for boolean, and null for all reference types.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does Java do if you don't write any constructors?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It provides a no-argument constructor that sets all instance variables to their type's default value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It refuses to compile the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It generates a constructor that takes every instance variable as a parameter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It provides a no-argument constructor that leaves all instance variables uninitialized.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of an <code>int</code> instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An undefined value that varies between runs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of a <code>boolean</code> instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the default value of a reference type instance variable like <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>null</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An empty string <code>""</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new instance of that reference type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write a class with no constructors and one <code>double</code> field. What value does that field have right after <code>new</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An undefined value that must not be read.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When a mutable object is passed as an argument to a constructor and stored in an instance variable, any mutations made to that object by code in the class will change the state for all code that has a reference to that object. Sometimes it's necessary to instead store a copy of the argument to avoid changing the original object out from under other code. Other times that's the whole point of being passed the object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a mutable object is passed to a constructor and stored in an instance variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class and the caller share a reference to the same object, so mutations by either side are visible to both.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The class gets a private copy of the object that the caller cannot see.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class gets a frozen snapshot of the object at the moment of the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class receives a deep copy automatically created by Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a constructor store a copy of a mutable argument instead of the argument itself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To avoid the class mutating the original object from under other code that holds a reference to it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make the constructor run faster by avoiding a reference assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires all constructor arguments to be copied before being stored.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To ensure the stored object has the same type as the declared instance variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might sharing the same mutable object between caller and class actually be desired?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When the whole point is for both sides to see changes made through the shared reference.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When the object is immutable and cannot be changed by either side anyway.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the object is small enough that copying would be wasteful.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the constructor has no other arguments to initialize the object with.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: your class stores an <code>ArrayList</code> passed into its constructor. Later the caller adds items to that list. What does the class see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class sees the added items, because both hold the same reference to one list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The class sees an empty list, because its reference was captured before the additions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class sees the original list contents only; new items go to the caller's copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class throws a <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> the next time it reads the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare storing a reference directly vs. storing a copy of a mutable argument.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Storing the reference shares state and mutations between caller and class; storing a copy isolates them so each has independent state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Storing the reference always produces a compile error for mutable types; storing a copy is the only legal option.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Storing a copy shares state between caller and class; storing the reference isolates them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both behave identically for mutable objects; the difference only matters for immutable ones.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Methods in classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>An object's behavior—what we can do with the object—is defined by the methods in its class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What defines an object's behavior?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The methods defined in its class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The instance variables of its class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The constructors of its class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The package the class is declared in.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "behavior" mean in the context of objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What you can do with the object, as defined by its class's methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The memory layout of the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The names of the object's instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class's static variables and their values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two classes have different methods, what differs between their objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their behavior—what can be done with those objects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Their size in memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The names of their instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether they can be garbage collected.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>BankAccount</code> class defines <code>deposit</code> and <code>withdraw</code>. What does that tell you about <code>BankAccount</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their behavior includes the ability to have money deposited into and withdrawn from them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Their state is limited to a balance field.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They cannot be created with <code>new</code>, only with a factory method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They automatically share a single balance across all accounts.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "state" and "behavior" of an object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>State is stored in instance variables; behavior is defined by the methods in the object's class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>State is defined by methods and behavior is stored in instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both state and behavior are stored in instance variables of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Behavior changes over time but state does not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods are called on objects of the class while `static` methods are called on the class itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are instance methods called on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Objects of the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The class itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The package containing the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any object, even of an unrelated class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are static methods called on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An instance of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whichever object was most recently created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first object created from the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you try to call an instance method without an object reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile—instance methods require an object to be called on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but always runs on the first instance of the class ever created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles and runs on a default object provided by Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles only if the method takes no arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you see <code>p.distance(q)</code>. Is <code>distance</code> static or instance?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance, because it is called on the object <code>p</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static, because it uses the dot operator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static, because the object name comes before the method name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both — the call is ambiguous without more information.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how you invoke static vs. instance methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods: <code>ClassName.method()</code>. Instance methods: <code>object.method()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static methods: <code>object.method()</code>. Instance methods: <code>ClassName.method()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are called the same way; the only difference is their return type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods use <code>::</code>; instance methods use <code>.</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Instance methods have access to all an object's instance variables.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do instance methods have access to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>All of the object's instance variables.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the <code>public</code> instance variables of the object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only static variables of the class, not instance variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only instance variables it explicitly takes as parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an instance method read a <code>private</code> instance variable of its own object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—instance methods have access to all of the object's instance variables regardless of access modifier.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — instance methods can only read <code>public</code> fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the method is marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only from within a constructor, not a regular method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an instance method refers to an instance variable by name?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It accesses that variable on the object the method was called on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It always reads the variable from the first instance ever created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It creates a new local variable with the same name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The code fails to compile unless the variable is qualified with the class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: an instance method of <code>Point</code> needs to use <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>. Can it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because instance methods have access to all instance variables of the object they are called on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> are marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the instance method is itself marked <code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No, instance methods cannot access instance variables directly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare instance and static methods in terms of access to instance variables.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods have direct access to the object's instance variables; static methods do not (they have no implicit object).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both have identical access; the only difference is the calling syntax.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods have access to instance variables of any object of the class; instance methods do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither can directly access instance variables — both require getters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that take no arguments and simply return the value of an instance variable are called "getters" or, more formally, "accessors". They are used to give code outside the class access to the object's state without making instance variables public.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "getter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that takes no arguments and returns the value of an instance variable. Also called an "accessor".</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that takes one argument and assigns it to an instance variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that creates and returns a new object of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns a static variable of the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why use getters instead of making instance variables public?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To give outside code read access to state without exposing the instance variables directly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To avoid having to write a constructor for the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To let the class automatically synchronize its fields with other classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not allow fields to be marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the more formal name for a getter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An accessor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A mutator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A setter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A selector.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>Point</code> has a <code>private int x</code>. How would you typically expose its value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Define a getter like <code>public int getX() { return x; }</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Make <code>x</code> <code>public</code> so outside code can read it directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Define a setter like <code>public void setX(int x) { this.x = x; }</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Return the whole <code>Point</code> object from a method and let the caller read the field.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare making a field public vs. providing a getter.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A public field lets outside code both read and write it directly; a getter lets outside code only read, while keeping the field private.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A public field can only be read while a getter can only be written.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are identical; the only difference is that a getter has an extra method call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A public field is faster but a getter is required for primitive types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods that return `void`, take a single argument, and assign it to the value of an instance variable are called "setters". More generally, methods that change any part of an object's state are called "mutators".</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "setter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that returns <code>void</code>, takes a single argument, and assigns it to an instance variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that takes no arguments and returns the value of an instance variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that creates a new object of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that only reads from an instance variable without changing it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "mutator"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>More generally, any method that changes some part of an object's state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that only reads an object's state without changing it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A synonym for "getter" — the two words mean the same thing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that changes a static variable of the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is every mutator a setter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Every setter is a mutator, but mutators include any method that changes state, not just simple single-argument assignments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Every mutator is a setter because both change state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. A mutator is a read-only method, so it cannot be a setter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the class has exactly one instance variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a method <code>deposit(double amount)</code> adds to a balance field. Setter, mutator, or both?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A mutator (it changes state), but not a simple setter, because it doesn't just assign the argument to a field.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A setter, because it takes a single argument and modifies state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither — it only reads the balance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A getter, because it returns the new balance.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare setters and mutators.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Setters are a specific kind of mutator: <code>void</code>, one argument, assigned to an instance variable. Mutators are any methods that change state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are the same thing — "setter" and "mutator" are two names for the same concept.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A mutator returns <code>void</code> and takes no arguments, while a setter returns a value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A setter can change any field while a mutator can only change one specific field.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Access modifiers</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keywords `public` and `private` control what code can access class members.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do the keywords <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They control what code can access class members.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They control the order in which class members are initialized.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They control whether class members are inherited by subclasses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They control whether class members can be modified after construction.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> applied to classes or to members?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both can be applied to members; <code>public</code> can also be applied to top-level classes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both can be applied only to members, never to classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both can be applied only to top-level classes, never to members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code> applies only to members and <code>private</code> applies only to classes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to code that tries to access a member it isn't allowed to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but throws a runtime exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but silently returns a default value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles with a warning but runs normally.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to restrict who can call a helper method. Which keyword do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>public</code> and <code>private</code> conceptually.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are access modifiers that define boundaries: <code>public</code> opens a member to all code; <code>private</code> restricts it to the declaring class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are scope modifiers that determine how long a member lives in memory, with <code>public</code> meaning permanent and <code>private</code> meaning temporary.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are inheritance modifiers where <code>public</code> members are inherited and <code>private</code> members are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are lifetime modifiers where <code>public</code> members outlive the object and <code>private</code> members do not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keyword `private` restricts access to only code within the declaring class, while the keyword `public` allows access from any code.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What code can access a <code>private</code> member?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only code within the declaring class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only code within the declaring package.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only code within subclasses of the declaring class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only code within the same source file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What code can access a <code>public</code> member?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any code.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only code within the same package.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only code within subclasses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only code within the same source file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when code outside the class tries to use a <code>private</code> field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It fails to compile.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but throws <code>IllegalAccessException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but silently returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles with a warning but still runs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: class <code>A</code> has a private method. Can class <code>B</code> call it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No, only code within class <code>A</code> can call it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, any class in the same package can call it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as class <code>B</code> extends class <code>A</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only through reflection.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the access scope of <code>public</code> vs. <code>private</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>: accessible from anywhere. <code>private</code>: accessible only from within the declaring class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>: accessible from the same package. <code>private</code>: accessible only from subclasses.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>: accessible from subclasses. <code>private</code>: accessible only from the same object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>: accessible at runtime. <code>private</code>: accessible only at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes cannot be marked `private` and are typically marked `public`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can a top-level class be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if it has no public members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only in a file with a matching name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if it is nested inside another class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How are top-level classes typically marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to write <code>private class Foo { }</code> at the top level?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It won't compile; top-level classes cannot be <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but the class is invisible at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but the class behaves as <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles with a warning about unused access modifiers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want a class to be usable from any other class. Which modifier do you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare access modifier options for members vs. top-level classes.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Members can be <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>; top-level classes can be <code>public</code> but not <code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both members and top-level classes can be either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Members can only be <code>public</code>; top-level classes can be either <code>public</code> or <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Members can be <code>private</code> only; top-level classes must always be <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Access to variables should usually be kept internal to the class. Therefore, instance variables are usually made `private`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are instance variables usually marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are instance variables usually made <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because access to variables should usually be kept internal to the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>private</code> variables are faster to access than <code>public</code> ones.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires instance variables to be <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>private</code> variables are automatically initialized to sensible defaults.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to a design that makes all instance variables <code>public</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It loses the benefit of keeping variable access internal to the class, letting outside code read and modify state directly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It causes a compile-time error because instance variables cannot be <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It improves performance because outside code can bypass accessor methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It forces all methods in the class to also be <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you're writing a new class and are about to declare an instance variable. Default choice for modifier?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare designs with public vs. private instance variables.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public variables expose internal state to outside code; private variables keep state internal and force outside access to go through methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Public variables are shared across all instances; private variables are unique to each instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public variables are faster to access; private variables require method calls so are slower at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public variables are initialized automatically; private variables must always be initialized explicitly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are typically made `public` but sometimes classes will have `private` constructors that are only used within the class, either from other constructors or from methods that construct new instances of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are constructors typically marked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>public</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When might a constructor be marked <code>private</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When it is only meant to be used within the class, from other constructors or from methods that construct new instances.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When the class is abstract and cannot be instantiated.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the constructor takes no parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the class extends another class with a <code>private</code> constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What can call a <code>private</code> constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only code within the same class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only code within the same package.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only code within subclasses of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only other constructors, never methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class wants to control how its instances are created, providing only static factory methods. Useful modifier for its constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>, so outside code cannot call it directly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>, so the factory methods can call it from outside.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>, so it can be called without an instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>, so it cannot be overridden.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare typical usage of <code>public</code> vs. <code>private</code> constructors.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public constructors let any code create instances; private constructors restrict instance creation to code inside the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Public constructors are inherited by subclasses; private constructors are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public constructors are called automatically; private constructors must be called explicitly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public constructors allocate memory; private constructors do not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods are equally likely to be `public` or `private`. The `public` methods define what we can do with instances of a class but `private` methods are useful for breaking up big methods into sub-methods that are only useful within a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>public</code> methods define?</p></question>
        <answer><p>What outside code can do with instances of a class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>What code inside the class can do with its own state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Which methods the class inherits from its superclass.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Which fields the class can store.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why write <code>private</code> methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To break up big methods into smaller sub-methods that are only useful within the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To hide methods from the class's own code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To prevent the methods from being called at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To make the methods run faster than <code>public</code> methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are methods more commonly public or private?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are about equally common; each has its typical role.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Public methods are much more common because they form the interface.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Private methods are much more common because they hide implementation details.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public methods are rare and only used for static utilities.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you extract a helper used only by one method inside a class. What modifier should the helper usually have?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>private</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>static</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the roles of public and private methods.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Public methods form the class's external interface; private methods are internal helpers used to organize the class's own code.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Public methods run faster than private methods because they skip access checks.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public methods are inherited while private methods are not, which is their main distinction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Public methods can modify state while private methods can only read it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Code within a class can access the `private` variables and methods of any instance of the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Whose <code>private</code> members can code inside a class access?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The private members of any instance of that class, not just <code>this</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the private members of <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the private members of instances passed in as parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the private members of instances created inside the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a method of <code>Point</code> access a private field of a different <code>Point</code> object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—code within a class can access private members of any instance of the same class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—<code>private</code> access is per object, not per class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the other <code>Point</code> was created by <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only through a public getter method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method compares <code>this.x</code> to <code>other.x</code> where both are <code>Point</code> objects?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It works, even if <code>x</code> is private, because the access rule is per-class, not per-object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It fails to compile because <code>private</code> means per-object access.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compiles but throws <code>IllegalAccessException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It works only if <code>other</code> is the same object as <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: writing an <code>equals</code> method for <code>Point</code> that reads another <code>Point</code>'s private fields. Allowed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because both objects are of the same class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No, because <code>private</code> access is restricted to <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>equals</code> is declared <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the other <code>Point</code> was passed by reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "private per object" with Java's actual rule.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java's rule is per class, not per object: any code in a class can see any instance of that class's private members.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Java's rule is per object: a method can only see its own object's private members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java's rule is per package: any code in the same package can see private members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java's rule is per file: any class in the same source file can see private members.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Encapsulation</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Encapsulation is a technique in which implementation details of a class are kept hidden from code outside the class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is encapsulation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A technique in which implementation details of a class are kept hidden from code outside the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A technique in which a class's methods are all made <code>public</code> so they can be reused.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A technique in which all state is stored in a single wrapper object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A technique in which a class inherits behavior from its superclass.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does encapsulation hide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Implementation details of a class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The public interface of a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The inheritance relationships of a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The static members of a class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a class is well-encapsulated and you change its internal implementation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outside code is unaffected because it doesn't depend on the hidden details.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Outside code must be recompiled to match the new implementation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outside code breaks because it directly accesses the private fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outside code runs faster because the new implementation is exposed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class exposes only a few public methods and keeps its fields private. Is this good encapsulation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it hides implementation details behind a small public interface.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—good encapsulation requires all fields to be <code>public</code> for transparency.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class also extends another class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class has no constructors.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare encapsulated and non-encapsulated designs.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Encapsulated designs hide implementation behind a public interface; non-encapsulated designs expose internals, letting outside code depend on them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Encapsulated designs run faster; non-encapsulated designs run slower.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Encapsulated designs use inheritance; non-encapsulated designs do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Encapsulated designs are required by Java; non-encapsulated designs will not compile.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When designing a class, programmers make decisions about what parts of its state to make accessible and modifiable from an external class. Data can be either accessible, modifiable, both, or neither.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What four combinations of accessibility and modifiability can a piece of state have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Accessible only, modifiable only, both accessible and modifiable, or neither.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Public, private, protected, or package-private.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Readable, writable, executable, or hidden.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static, instance, local, or parameter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What decision are programmers making when they design a class's interface?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Which parts of the object's state external code should be able to read and/or modify.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Which methods should be <code>static</code> versus instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Which classes the new class should extend.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Which packages the class should belong to.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "accessible but not modifiable" look like in practice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A getter with no corresponding setter—outside code can read the value but not change it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>public</code> field that outside code can see but not assign to.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>private</code> field with no methods at all.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>final</code> field that is initialized in the constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a piece of state has neither a getter nor a setter. What's its external visibility?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Neither accessible nor modifiable from outside the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Accessible but not modifiable from outside the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Modifiable but not accessible from outside the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both accessible and modifiable through reflection.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare "accessible" and "modifiable" as separate design choices.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Accessibility means outside code can read a piece of state; modifiability means outside code can change it. Each can be granted or denied independently.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Accessibility and modifiability always come together in Java—you cannot have one without the other.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Accessibility means the field is <code>public</code>; modifiability means the field is not <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Accessibility refers to runtime permissions; modifiability refers to compile-time permissions.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>State can be encapsulated by storing it in `private` instance variables and access controlled by what getter, setter, and other mutator methods are provided.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is state typically encapsulated in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By storing it in <code>private</code> instance variables and exposing only the getters, setters, or other mutators you choose.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By storing it in <code>public</code> instance variables and documenting which ones are safe to modify.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By storing it in <code>static</code> variables shared across all instances.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By storing it in local variables inside the constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What controls how outside code can access encapsulated state?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The set of getter, setter, and mutator methods provided by the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The access modifiers on the class itself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The order in which the class's fields are declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of instances of the class that have been created.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a <code>private</code> field has a getter but no setter?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Outside code can read the value but cannot change it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Outside code can change the value but cannot read it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outside code can neither read nor change the value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Outside code can read the value but only through reflection.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want an immutable-looking <code>Point</code> where outside code can read <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> but not change them. How do you design it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Make <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> private, provide <code>getX</code> and <code>getY</code>, and provide no setters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Make <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> <code>public</code> so outside code can read them directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Make <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> <code>final</code> and <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Make <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> <code>static</code> and provide no methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class with only getters to one with getters and setters.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only getters: read-only state from outside. Getters plus setters: state is both readable and writable from outside.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only getters: state is hidden from outside. Getters plus setters: state is exposed as <code>public</code> fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only getters: the class is immutable. Getters plus setters: the class is automatically thread-safe.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only getters: the class cannot be subclassed. Getters plus setters: the class must be subclassed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title><code>toString</code></title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `toString` method is inherited from `java.lang.Object` and is frequently overridden to provide a concise, human-readable representation of an object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the <code>toString</code> method come from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is inherited from <code>java.lang.Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is inherited from <code>java.lang.String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a built-in Java keyword, not a method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is automatically generated by the compiler for each class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>toString</code> frequently overridden?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a concise, human-readable representation of an object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To convert the object into a byte array for serialization.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To compare the object to another object for equality.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To compute a hash code for the object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you don't override <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The inherited <code>Object.toString</code> is used, which is usually not human-readable (class name plus hash).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program fails to compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program throws a <code>NullPointerException</code> when printing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The object is printed as an empty string.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want <code>Point</code> objects to print as "(3, 4)". What should you do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Override <code>toString</code> in the <code>Point</code> class to return a string like <code>"(" + x + ", " + y + ")"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Override <code>equals</code> in the <code>Point</code> class to return the formatted string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declare a <code>public</code> field named <code>toString</code> holding the formatted string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Add a <code>static</code> method named <code>print</code> that formats the coordinates.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare the default <code>toString</code> to a custom one.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The default from <code>Object</code> returns a technical identifier; a custom override returns a concise, human-readable representation of the object's state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The default returns an empty string; a custom override returns the object's fields.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The default throws an exception; a custom override must catch it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The default returns the object's memory address in hex; a custom override cannot change that.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>If System.out.print or System.out.println is passed an object, that object's `toString` method is called, and the returned `String` is printed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you pass an object to <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object's <code>toString</code> method is called and the returned <code>String</code> is printed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The object's <code>equals</code> method is called against a default object and the result is printed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The object's memory address is printed directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime error occurs because <code>println</code> only accepts <code>String</code> values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which method is invoked to convert an object to text when printing?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>toString</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>print</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>hashCode</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What gets printed if you call <code>System.out.print(p)</code> on a <code>Point p</code> that overrides <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whatever string is returned by <code>p.toString()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The memory address of <code>p</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class name of <code>p</code> followed by its hash code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An empty string, because <code>print</code> does not call <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you print an object and see something like <code>Point@1a2b3c</code>. What does that tell you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The class hasn't overridden <code>toString</code>, so you're seeing <code>Object</code>'s default implementation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The object's <code>toString</code> method threw an exception.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The object is <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM is in debug mode.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare printing a primitive vs. printing an object with <code>println</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitives are converted to text using built-in conversions; objects are converted by calling their <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Primitives cannot be printed with <code>println</code>; only objects can.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both primitives and objects are printed by calling <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitives are printed as their memory address; objects are printed as their field values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`toString` is also used when a reference type is include in a `String` concatenation expression.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When else besides printing is <code>toString</code> called automatically?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a reference type is included in a <code>String</code> concatenation expression.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When the object is compared with <code>==</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the object is passed as a method argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the object is stored in an array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>"Point: " + p</code> where <code>p</code> is an object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java calls <code>p.toString()</code> and concatenates the result with the string.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Java throws a <code>ClassCastException</code> because <code>p</code> is not a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java prints the memory address of <code>p</code> after the string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java calls <code>p.equals("Point: ")</code> and uses the result.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>"value=" + someObject</code> not cause a type error?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because Java automatically calls the object's <code>toString</code> to get a <code>String</code> for concatenation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>+</code> operator is overloaded for any two types in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java silently ignores the object and just uses the string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because all objects are implicitly convertible to <code>String</code> at compile time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you override <code>toString</code> on <code>Point</code> to return "(x,y)". What does <code>"p=" + new Point(1,2)</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"p=(1,2)"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>"p=Point@1a2b3c"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"p="</code> followed by a runtime error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"p=null"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how <code>toString</code> is used in <code>println</code> vs. in string concatenation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>In both cases Java calls the object's <code>toString</code> automatically to convert the object to a printable <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In <code>println</code> it calls <code>toString</code>, but in concatenation it calls <code>equals</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In <code>println</code> it prints the memory address; in concatenation it calls <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In <code>println</code> it calls <code>toString</code>, but in concatenation you must call <code>toString</code> yourself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>`this`</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Within a non-`static` method or a constructor, the keyword `this` is a name for the reference to the current object—the object on which the method was called or the object being constructed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In a non-<code>static</code> method, what does the keyword <code>this</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A reference to the current object—the object on which the method was called.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the class itself, used to access <code>static</code> members.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the superclass of the current object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the most recently created object of the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a constructor, what does <code>this</code> refer to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object currently being constructed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The superclass constructor being called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The class being instantiated, not a specific object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A temporary placeholder that becomes <code>null</code> after construction finishes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>this</code> not available in a <code>static</code> method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Static methods are not called on an instance, so there is no current object for <code>this</code> to refer to.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Static methods run before any objects exist, so <code>this</code> has not been initialized yet.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods cannot access any fields, so <code>this</code> would be useless.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Static methods are forbidden from using <code>this</code> by the Java specification for readability.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Given <code>void setX(int x) { this.x = x; }</code>, what does <code>this.x</code> distinguish from just <code>x</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>this.x</code> refers to the instance field of the current object, while <code>x</code> alone refers to the parameter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>this.x</code> refers to the parameter, while <code>x</code> alone refers to the instance field.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>this.x</code> refers to a static field, while <code>x</code> alone refers to the instance field.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>this.x</code> and <code>x</code> are identical in this context—the distinction is only stylistic.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>this</code> in a constructor differ from <code>this</code> in a regular non-static method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In a constructor it refers to the object being constructed; in a non-static method it refers to the object the method was called on. In both cases it names the current object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In a constructor it refers to the class; in a non-static method it refers to an instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a constructor it is <code>null</code> until construction completes; in a non-static method it is always non-null.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In a constructor it refers to the superclass object; in a non-static method it refers to the current object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The keyword `this` can be used to pass a reference to the current object as an argument to a method or constructor or as a value to be assigned anywhere a value of the type of the current class is needed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can you pass <code>this</code> as an argument to another method? What does that accomplish?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. It passes a reference to the current object so the called method can operate on it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. <code>this</code> can only be used on the left side of an assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the parameter type is explicitly declared as <code>this</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside constructors, not in regular methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where can <code>this</code> be used as a value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Anywhere a value of the type of the current class is needed—as an argument, as an assignment source, or as a return value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only as the first argument to another method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only on the left side of a field assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside the constructor of the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when an object calls <code>list.add(this)</code> from inside one of its own methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The object adds a reference to itself to the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The object creates a copy of itself and adds it to the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>NullPointerException</code> is thrown because <code>this</code> is not a valid argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The list is replaced by the current object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Node</code> method needs to register itself with a <code>Graph</code>. How might <code>this</code> help?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method can call <code>graph.register(this)</code> to pass its own reference to the graph.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method can call <code>graph.register(Node)</code> to pass its class to the graph.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method can assign <code>this = graph</code> to link them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method can return <code>this</code> from the graph's constructor.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare using <code>this</code> as an argument versus using a separately stored reference to the same object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>They refer to the same object, but <code>this</code> is always guaranteed to name the current object without needing an extra variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>this</code> is slower to access than a stored reference because it is computed at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>this</code> can be reassigned, while a stored reference cannot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>this</code> refers to a copy of the current object, while a stored reference refers to the original.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Comments</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Comments are ignored by the compiler and are not executed when the program is run.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the Java compiler do with comments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It ignores them—they are not part of the compiled program.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It parses them and stores them in the class file for runtime lookup.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It executes them as documentation hints before running the program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It reports each comment as a warning unless marked with a tag.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are comments executed at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Since the compiler strips them, there is nothing to execute at runtime.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only Javadoc comments are executed at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, comments are executed once when the class is first loaded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but they have no observable effect on the program.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you write invalid Java syntax inside a comment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing—the compiler ignores the contents of comments, so syntax inside them does not matter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The compiler reports a syntax error inside the comment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler warns but still compiles the file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM throws a runtime error when the comment is reached.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you "comment out" a line that called a method. Will that method still run?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Commented-out code is ignored by the compiler and never executed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, commented-out code still runs but its output is discarded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the comment uses <code>//</code> instead of <code>/* */</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method has no other callers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare comments to <code>System.out.println</code> calls as a way to document behavior.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Comments are ignored by the compiler and have no runtime effect; <code>println</code> calls actually execute and produce output when the program runs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both comments and <code>println</code> calls produce output at runtime, but comments are faster.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Comments are compiled into the class file while <code>println</code> calls are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Comments run before the program starts; <code>println</code> calls run during execution.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Three types of comments in Java include `/* */`, which generates a block of comments, `//`, which generates a comment on one line, and `/** */`, which are Javadoc comments and are used to create API documentation.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What are the three types of comments in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Block comments <code>/* */</code>, line comments <code>//</code>, and Javadoc comments <code>/** */</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Line comments <code>//</code>, hash comments <code>#</code>, and Javadoc comments <code>/** */</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Block comments <code>/* */</code>, line comments <code>//</code>, and XML comments <code>&lt;\!-- --&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Single-line <code>//</code>, multi-line <code>/* */</code>, and preprocessor <code>#if</code> comments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the purpose of a Javadoc comment?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To create API documentation from specially formatted comments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To mark code that should be executed only in debug mode.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To embed unit tests directly in the source code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To hide code from the compiler while still running it at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which comment style would you use for a single-line note?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>//</code>, the line comment.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>/* */</code>, the block comment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>/** */</code>, the Javadoc comment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>#</code>, the hash comment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you want to temporarily disable a 10-line block of code. Which comment style is most convenient?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A block comment <code>/* */</code> around the entire region.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Ten consecutive <code>//</code> line comments, one per line.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A Javadoc comment <code>/** */</code> around the entire region.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A preprocessor <code>#if 0</code> directive.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>/* */</code> and <code>/** */</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both are block comments, but <code>/** */</code> is a Javadoc comment intended to be processed into API documentation, while <code>/* */</code> is a plain comment.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>/* */</code> is a line comment; <code>/** */</code> is a block comment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>/* */</code> is ignored by the compiler; <code>/** */</code> is executed at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>/* */</code> is for single-line notes; <code>/** */</code> is for multi-line notes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Invariants</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Invariants are things that must be true if the program is working correctly. They help us think about how different parts of a program work together.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is an invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Something that must be true if the program is working correctly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Something that must be checked every time a method is called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A variable whose value never changes after it is assigned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that cannot be overridden by subclasses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are invariants useful when reasoning about a program?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They help us think about how different parts of a program work together by stating what must always hold.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They make the program run faster by letting the compiler skip checks.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are required by the Java compiler to produce bytecode.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are automatically enforced by the JVM at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if an invariant is violated at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The program is not working correctly—there is a bug somewhere.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The JVM automatically throws an <code>InvariantViolationException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The program halts and rolls back to the last known good state.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing happens, because invariants are only documentation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a bank account class claims its balance is never negative. What is that statement?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An invariant of the class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A precondition of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A postcondition of the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime assertion of the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an invariant to a regular boolean expression in the code.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A boolean expression just evaluates at one point; an invariant is a claim that some condition must always hold whenever the program is in a correct state.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A boolean expression is stored in a variable; an invariant is stored in a comment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A boolean expression is checked by the compiler; an invariant is checked by the JVM.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A boolean expression returns a value; an invariant returns <code>void</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A precondition is a kind of invariant that defines a condition that must be true before a method is called.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a precondition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A condition that must be true before a method is called.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A condition that must be true after a method returns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A condition that is checked inside the method body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A condition that is passed as the first argument to a method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a precondition a kind of invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it is an invariant that applies at the moment just before the method is called.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—preconditions are checked at runtime while invariants are only documentation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No—preconditions apply to methods while invariants apply to classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method declares the precondition with a keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when a method is called and its precondition is not true?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller has a bug; the method is not obligated to behave correctly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method automatically throws an <code>IllegalArgumentException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method's bug: it must always handle any input gracefully.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The JVM rolls back the call and retries with default arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>sqrt(x)</code> requires <code>x &gt;= 0</code>. What is that requirement called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A precondition of <code>sqrt</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A postcondition of <code>sqrt</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop invariant of <code>sqrt</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A runtime assertion of <code>sqrt</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a precondition to a regular <code>if</code> check inside a method.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A precondition is a contractual requirement on the caller; an <code>if</code> check inside the method is runtime logic the method itself performs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A precondition is checked automatically by Java; an <code>if</code> check must be written by hand.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A precondition is a keyword in Java; an <code>if</code> check is an ordinary statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A precondition runs before compilation; an <code>if</code> check runs during execution.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A postcondition is kind of invariant that defines a condition that must always be true after a method returns successfully. Postconditions describe the outcome of the execution in terms of the value returned and/or any changes to the state of the world.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a postcondition?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A condition that must be true after a method returns successfully.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A condition that must be true before a method is called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A condition that is checked at the start of every loop iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A condition that describes the method's parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do postconditions describe?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The outcome of the method's execution—the value returned and/or any changes to the state of the world.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The arguments that were passed to the method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The preconditions that the caller had to satisfy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The exceptions that the method might throw.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a postcondition a kind of invariant?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—it is an invariant that must hold at the moment just after a successful return.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—postconditions are only checked at runtime, while invariants never are.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No—postconditions apply to return values, while invariants apply to parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method is declared with a special keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>sort(list)</code> guarantees that the list is in ascending order when it returns. What is that guarantee called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A postcondition of <code>sort</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A precondition of <code>sort</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop invariant of <code>sort</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class invariant of <code>sort</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare preconditions and postconditions.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Preconditions must be true before the method is called (caller's responsibility); postconditions must be true after the method returns successfully (method's responsibility).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Preconditions are checked automatically by Java; postconditions must be checked by the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Preconditions apply to return values; postconditions apply to arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Preconditions are documentation only; postconditions are enforced at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The job of a method is to satisfy its postconditions assuming its preconditions have been met. If the preconditions are not met, it is a bug in the code that called the method. If the preconditions were met and the postconditions are not satisfied it is a bug in the method. Methods may or may not actually check that their preconditions have been met.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a method's job, stated in terms of conditions?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To satisfy its postconditions, assuming its preconditions have been met.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To check its preconditions and throw an exception if they are not met.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To satisfy its preconditions before it is called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To document its behavior in a Javadoc comment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a method is called without its preconditions being met, whose bug is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller's bug.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method's bug.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A bug in the Java runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither—it is undefined behavior with no responsible party.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If preconditions were met but postconditions are not satisfied, whose bug is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The method's bug.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The caller's bug.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A bug in the Java runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither—it is undefined behavior with no responsible party.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a method required to check its preconditions at runtime?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. A method may or may not actually check that its preconditions have been met.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Java requires every method to check its preconditions at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if the method is <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the preconditions are declared with a special keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: <code>divide(a, b)</code> has precondition <code>b != 0</code>. A caller passes <code>0</code> and the program crashes. Whose fault is it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The caller's, because the precondition was violated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The method's, because it should have handled division by zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The Java runtime's, because it should have prevented the crash.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither—dividing by zero is undefined behavior and has no responsible party.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Overloading</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Constructors are said to be overloaded when there are multiple constructors in the same class with different numbers or types of parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are constructors considered overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When a class has multiple constructors with different numbers or types of parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When a class has multiple constructors with the same parameters but different return types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a class has a single constructor that can accept any number of arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a class inherits constructors from its superclass.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two constructors in the same class have exactly the same parameter list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—to be overloaded they must differ in the number or types of parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as they have different return types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as they have different access modifiers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as they are declared in different source files.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does overloading constructors allow a class to offer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiple ways to construct an instance, depending on which arguments are available.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The ability to construct an instance from any other class's type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The ability to change the type of an instance after it is constructed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The ability to construct an instance without using the <code>new</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> class has <code>Point()</code> and <code>Point(int x, int y)</code>. Are these overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. They are constructors in the same class with different numbers of parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. Overloading requires at least three constructors.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. Overloading requires the constructors to have different return types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the parameterless constructor is declared <code>private</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloaded constructors to having a single constructor with default values.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java has no default parameter values, so overloading is the standard way to provide multiple construction options.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Java supports default parameter values, so overloading is rarely needed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloading is required by the Java compiler for every class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Default values and overloading are equivalent features in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Methods are said to be overloaded when there are multiple methods in the same class (or inheritance hierarchy) with the same name but different numbers or types of parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>When are methods considered overloaded?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When there are multiple methods with the same name but different numbers or types of parameters in the same class or inheritance hierarchy.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When there are multiple methods with the same name and the same parameters but different return types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a method is called more times than it is declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When a method is declared in both a class and an interface it implements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can two overloaded methods differ only in return type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—they must differ in the number or types of their parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, as long as their return types are compatible.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because the compiler uses return type to distinguish them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if one return type is <code>void</code> and the other is not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does overloading work across a class and its superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—overloading applies within a class or its inheritance hierarchy.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—overloading is limited to methods within a single class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the subclass declares the method with the <code>@Overload</code> annotation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if both methods have the same return type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class has <code>print(int x)</code> and <code>print(String s)</code>. Is this overloading?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. Same name, different parameter types.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. These are two unrelated methods that just share a name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. Overloading requires at least three methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class also defines <code>print()</code> with no arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloaded methods to methods with different names.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Overloaded methods share a name and are distinguished by parameter lists; differently named methods are distinguished by name alone.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Overloaded methods run faster because the compiler can inline them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloaded methods are inherited by subclasses while differently named methods are not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloaded methods must share a return type; differently named methods need not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When an overloaded constructor or method is called, which one is invoked is determined by finding the constructor or method whose parameter types match the types of the arguments in the call.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How does Java decide which overloaded method to invoke at a call site?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It finds the method whose parameter types match the types of the arguments in the call.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It finds the method whose return type matches the expected result of the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It picks the first matching method in source order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It picks the method with the most parameters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What information is used to resolve overloading?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The argument types at the call site, matched against the parameter types of the candidate methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The runtime types of the arguments, determined when the call is executed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The return type expected by the caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The declaration order of the methods in the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>At what time is overload resolution performed—compile time or run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At compile time, based on the static types of the arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At run time, based on the dynamic types of the arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At class-load time, based on the method declarations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At link time, based on the method signatures in the class file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a class has <code>f(int)</code> and <code>f(double)</code>. You call <code>f(3)</code>. Which is invoked?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>f(int)</code>, because the literal <code>3</code> has type <code>int</code>, which matches the <code>int</code> parameter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>f(double)</code>, because Java prefers the more precise type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is ambiguous and fails to compile.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a runtime exception because both overloads match.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overload resolution to method dispatch by name alone.</p></question>
        <answer><p>With unique names, the name alone selects the method; with overloading, the name plus parameter types together select the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>With unique names, resolution is at run time; with overloading, it is at compile time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>With unique names, the compiler picks the method; with overloading, the JVM picks it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Unique names are faster to resolve; overloading is slower at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Overloading of methods doesn't allow you to do anything you couldn't do by just giving the different methods different names.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Does method overloading give Java any new capabilities?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Anything you can do with overloading you could also do by giving the methods different names.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Overloading lets you return different types from a single method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Overloading lets methods dispatch at run time based on argument types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Overloading lets a method take arguments of any type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If method overloading gives no new capabilities beyond what distinct method names could provide, why is it used at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>For readability and convenience—related operations can share a single intuitive name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>For performance—overloaded methods are faster than separately named ones.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires it for methods that take multiple types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM treats overloaded methods specially at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is overloading a runtime feature that changes program behavior beyond naming?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No—it is purely a naming convenience resolved by the compiler.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes—it lets methods be dispatched at runtime based on argument types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes—it changes the behavior of methods depending on the caller's context.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes—it makes methods polymorphic across different argument types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: instead of overloading <code>print</code>, you write <code>printInt</code> and <code>printString</code>. Have you lost any capability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. You have exactly the same capability, just with longer, more specific names.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You lose the ability to pass arguments of different types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You lose the ability to call the method at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You lose the ability to inherit the method in subclasses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare overloading to using distinct method names for each signature.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Overloading shares a name for related operations; distinct names make the differences explicit. Both can express the same programs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Overloading is more powerful because it supports runtime dispatch; distinct names do not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloading is faster at runtime; distinct names are faster at compile time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloading is required for methods with different parameter types; distinct names are not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Inheritance</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `Object` class in the `java.lang` package is the direct or indirect superclass of all other classes in Java. Other than that, you don't need to know about inheritance for the AP exam.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the ultimate superclass of every class in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>, in the <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Class</code>, in the <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code>, in the <code>java.util</code> package.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Super</code>, in the <code>java.lang</code> package.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>Object</code> is a "direct or indirect" superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A class's superclass chain always eventually reaches <code>Object</code>, whether directly or through other classes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A class can choose at runtime whether <code>Object</code> is its superclass.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class may have <code>Object</code> as a superclass only if it declares it explicitly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A class that extends an interface is direct; a class that extends another class is indirect.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In which package does <code>Object</code> live?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>java.util</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.io</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.base</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write <code>class Dog {}</code> with no <code>extends</code> clause. What is its superclass?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Object</code>, implicitly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It has no superclass.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Class</code>, implicitly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The most recently declared class in the file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare a class that directly extends <code>Object</code> to one that extends another class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both ultimately have <code>Object</code> as an ancestor; one reaches it directly, the other through one or more intermediate superclasses.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The directly extending class inherits all of <code>Object</code>'s methods; the indirectly extending class inherits none.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the directly extending class can call <code>Object</code>'s methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The directly extending class is faster at runtime because it skips intermediate lookups.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>All classes inherit from `Object` the methods `boolean equals(Object other)` and `String toString()` which are described in the [AP Java Quick Reference].</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which two methods does every class inherit from <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> and <code>String toString()</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int compareTo(Object other)</code> and <code>String toString()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> and <code>int hashCode()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String toString()</code> and <code>void finalize()</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>equals</code>, and what parameter does it take?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns <code>boolean</code> and takes a single <code>Object</code> parameter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>int</code> and takes a single <code>Object</code> parameter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>boolean</code> and takes two <code>Object</code> parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>boolean</code> and takes a parameter of the same type as the class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>char[]</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you write a new class and never declare <code>equals</code> or <code>toString</code>. Are those methods available on its instances?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—they are inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—you must declare them explicitly in every class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class extends another class that declares them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class is marked <code>public</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>equals</code> and <code>toString</code> in terms of purpose.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code> tests whether two objects are considered equal; <code>toString</code> produces a <code>String</code> representation of an object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code> copies one object to another; <code>toString</code> converts an object to an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code> compares memory addresses; <code>toString</code> compares field values.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code> is used only by collections; <code>toString</code> is used only by <code>println</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes often override the `equals` and `toString` methods with class-specific implementations.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to override <code>equals</code> or <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a class-specific implementation that replaces the one inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To provide a class-specific implementation that runs in addition to the inherited one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To rename the inherited method to something more meaningful.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To prevent subclasses from calling the inherited method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do classes often override <code>toString</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To provide a more informative, class-specific <code>String</code> representation than the default from <code>Object</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make the class run faster when it is printed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires every class to override <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To prevent outside code from calling <code>toString</code> directly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do classes often override <code>equals</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To define equality based on the class's own notion of value, not just reference identity.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To make <code>equals</code> run faster than the default implementation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires every class to override <code>equals</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To allow <code>equals</code> to accept arguments of any type, not just <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: a <code>Point</code> class overrides <code>equals</code> so that two points with the same coordinates compare equal. Is that allowed?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes—that is a typical class-specific override of the inherited <code>equals</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No—<code>equals</code> cannot be overridden because it is inherited from <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class also overrides <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the class is declared <code>final</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare an overridden <code>toString</code> with the default one from <code>Object</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The default shows generic information like the class name and a hash; an overridden version typically shows meaningful, class-specific field values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The default is faster; the overridden version is slower but more informative.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The default is inherited at compile time; the overridden version is dispatched at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The default returns an empty string; the overridden version returns the class name.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Built in classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>Classes in Java are grouped into packages. The classes `String`, `Math`, `System`, `Integer`, `Double`, `Boolean`, and `Object` are all from the `java.lang` package which is always available in all Java programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How are classes organized in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are grouped into packages.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are grouped into namespaces.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are grouped into modules.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are stored in a single global classpath with no grouping.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which package contains <code>String</code>, <code>Math</code>, <code>System</code>, <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, <code>Boolean</code>, and <code>Object</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>java.util</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.base</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.core</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is special about the <code>java.lang</code> package?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is always available in all Java programs without needing an import.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is the only package that contains <code>static</code> classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It must be imported explicitly at the top of every Java file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is the package that contains the <code>main</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you use <code>Math.sqrt</code> without importing anything. Why does this work?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is implicitly available in every Java program.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The compiler automatically adds an <code>import java.util.Math;</code> behind the scenes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math</code> is a built-in keyword in Java, not a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math</code> is in the same package as your program by default.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>java.lang</code> to other packages in terms of availability.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.lang</code> is automatically available everywhere; classes in other packages must be imported (or referred to by fully qualified name) before use.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>java.lang</code> must always be imported, while other packages are automatically available.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.lang</code> is available only inside the <code>main</code> method; other packages are available everywhere.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>All standard packages are automatically available; <code>java.lang</code> is not special.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The only class we use from another package is `ArrayList` which needs to be imported from `java.util`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which class used in AP CSA comes from a package other than <code>java.lang</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Scanner</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>HashMap</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>From which package is <code>ArrayList</code> imported?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.util</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>java.lang</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.collections</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.arraylist</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>ArrayList</code> require an import while <code>String</code> does not?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList</code> lives in <code>java.util</code>, which is not automatically available; <code>String</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList</code> is a generic class, and generic classes always require imports.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> is a primitive type, so it needs no import, while <code>ArrayList</code> is an object and must be imported.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList</code> was added to Java later, so only newer classes need to be imported.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you use <code>ArrayList</code> without an import and get a compile error. What should you add?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code> statement at the top of the file.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>package java.util;</code> statement at the top of the file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>import java.lang.ArrayList;</code> statement at the top of the file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>#include java.util.ArrayList</code> directive at the top of the file.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare importing <code>ArrayList</code> from <code>java.util</code> to using classes from <code>java.lang</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes from <code>java.lang</code> need no import; classes from <code>java.util</code> (and other packages) must be imported or fully qualified.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both kinds of classes require explicit imports before they can be used.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither kind of class requires an import; Java finds all standard classes automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.lang</code> classes must be imported, while <code>java.util</code> classes are available by default.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Application program interfaces (APIs) and libraries provide classes we can use in our programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does API stand for?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Application Program Interface.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Applied Programming Instructions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Abstract Program Interface.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Application Programming Internals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What do APIs and libraries provide to our programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Classes (and methods) we can use without writing them ourselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the <code>main</code> method for starting a program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The Java compiler and runtime environment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Keywords and operators for writing Java programs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is using library classes valuable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It saves us from reimplementing common functionality and lets us build on well-tested code.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Library classes always run faster than any code you could write yourself.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Library classes are the only way to use objects in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Library classes are required by the Java language specification for every program.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Scenario: you need a resizable list and use <code>ArrayList</code> from the standard library. What are you making use of?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A library class provided by Java's API.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A built-in Java language feature, not a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A user-defined class from your own program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive type provided by Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare writing a class yourself to using one from an API or library.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Writing it yourself gives full control but takes effort and risks bugs; using a library class gives you tested, ready-made functionality at the cost of learning its interface.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing it yourself is always faster and easier than using library classes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using a library class means you cannot customize behavior at all, while writing your own always gives perfect results.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>There is no practical difference; the two approaches always produce identical code.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>Strings</title>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects are typically created with <code>String</code> literals but can be constructed via constructors defined in the <code>String</code> class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the most common way to create a <code>String</code> object in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Using a <code>String</code> literal, such as <code>"hello"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Calling <code>new String()</code> with no arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Calling <code>String.create("hello")</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declaring a <code>char[]</code> and assigning it to a <code>String</code> variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Besides literals, how else can a <code>String</code> object be created?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By calling a constructor defined in the <code>String</code> class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By casting a <code>char</code> to a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By calling <code>String.valueOf</code> on another <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By concatenating an empty literal with itself.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>"hello"</code> a <code>String</code> object?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. A <code>String</code> literal creates a <code>String</code> object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. A <code>String</code> literal is a primitive value, not an object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No. Literals become <code>String</code> objects only after being assigned to a variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you wrap it with <code>new String("hello")</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare creating a <code>String</code> via a literal versus via <code>new String(...)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both produce <code>String</code> objects, but literals are the typical and preferred way; using the constructor is rarely needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the constructor form produces a real <code>String</code> object; literals produce primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the literal form produces a <code>String</code> object; the constructor form produces a <code>char[]</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The literal form is deprecated in modern Java and should be avoided.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you write <code>String s = "cat";</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> literal creates a <code>String</code> object and <code>s</code> is set to reference it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char</code> array containing <code>'c'</code>, <code>'a'</code>, and <code>'t'</code> is assigned directly to <code>s</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>s</code> becomes a primitive value holding the text <code>cat</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The literal <code>"cat"</code> is copied into <code>s</code>'s memory as raw bytes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects are immutable; many methods on <code>String</code>s produce new <code>String</code>s that are related to the original (such as the original converted to all upper case) but the original <code>String</code> cannot be changed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>String</code> objects are immutable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Once created, a <code>String</code> object's contents cannot be changed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> cannot be reassigned to a new value after it is declared.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> object cannot be passed as an argument to a method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> can only be changed by calling its <code>set</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>s.toUpperCase()</code>, what happens to <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing — <code>s</code> is unchanged. A new <code>String</code> with the uppercase version is returned.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>s</code> is modified in place to hold the uppercase version of its characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>s</code> becomes <code>null</code> until you reassign it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>s</code> is converted to a <code>char[]</code> with uppercase letters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you call a method like <code>toUpperCase()</code> on a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> is produced that is related to the original; the original is not modified.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The original <code>String</code> is modified in place to hold the new characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method throws an exception because <code>String</code>s are immutable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new <code>char[]</code> is returned instead of a new <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why must <code>String</code> methods return new <code>String</code>s instead of modifying the original?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code> objects are immutable and cannot be changed after they are created.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> methods are all <code>static</code> and cannot modify an instance.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because returning a new <code>String</code> is always faster than modifying in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not allow methods to have <code>void</code> return types on <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast mutability of <code>String</code> with a typical mutable object.</p></question>
        <answer><p>A mutable object's state can be changed by calling methods on it; a <code>String</code>'s state cannot — methods only produce new <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A mutable object's state is fixed once created; a <code>String</code>'s state can be changed any time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Mutable objects can only be changed by the garbage collector; <code>String</code>s can be changed by any method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>There is no real difference; all Java objects behave the same way with respect to mutability.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String</code> objects can be concatenated using the <code>+</code> or <code>+=</code> operator, resulting in a new <code>String</code> object.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What operators can be used to concatenate <code>String</code>s in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>+</code> and <code>+=</code> operators.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>.</code> and <code>.=</code> operators.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>&amp;</code> and <code>&amp;=</code> operators.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>concat</code> and <code>append</code> operators.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the result of <code>"foo" + "bar"</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object containing <code>"foobar"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The original <code>String</code> <code>"foo"</code> with <code>"bar"</code> appended in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char[]</code> containing the characters of both literals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error because you cannot add two literals.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>s += "x"</code> change the original <code>String</code> that <code>s</code> referenced?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It creates a new <code>String</code> and reassigns <code>s</code> to reference it. <code>String</code>s are immutable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. <code>+=</code> modifies the <code>String</code> in place by appending <code>"x"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>+=</code> is the one exception to <code>String</code> immutability.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No, and no new <code>String</code> is created either; the statement has no effect.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of value does <code>+</code> produce when both operands are <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object formed by concatenation.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A reference to the original left-hand <code>String</code> after modification.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char[]</code> containing the characters of both operands.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive value representing the combined characters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>+</code> and <code>+=</code> on <code>String</code>s.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both concatenate and produce a new <code>String</code>; <code>+=</code> additionally reassigns the result back to the left-hand variable.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>+</code> modifies the left operand in place, while <code>+=</code> creates a new <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>+</code> works only with <code>String</code>s, while <code>+=</code> works with any type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>+=</code> is a shortcut that avoids creating a new <code>String</code> object.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Non-<code>String</code> values can also be concatenated with a <code>String</code> object. This causes an implicit conversion of the values to <code>String</code> objects. Primitive values and <code>null</code> are converted to their standard literal form and reference types are converted using their <code>toString</code> method.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you concatenate an <code>int</code> with a <code>String</code> using <code>+</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> is implicitly converted to its standard literal form as a <code>String</code> and then concatenated.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>int</code> is automatically cast to a <code>char</code> and appended.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler reports an error because you cannot add an <code>int</code> to a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>String</code> is converted to an <code>int</code> and the values are added numerically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a reference type converted to a <code>String</code> during concatenation?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By calling its <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By calling its <code>hashCode</code> method and converting the result to a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By casting it directly to a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By using reflection to read each field and join them together.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"x=" + null</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>String</code> <code>"x=null"</code> — <code>null</code> is converted to its literal form <code>"null"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>NullPointerException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>String</code> <code>"x="</code> by itself, since <code>null</code> is skipped.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error because <code>null</code> cannot be concatenated.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>"value: " + 42</code> compile even though <code>42</code> isn't a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because concatenation with a <code>String</code> implicitly converts non-<code>String</code> values to <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler treats <code>42</code> as a <code>String</code> literal inside concatenation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code>s and <code>String</code>s are the same type in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>+</code> operator is overloaded only for <code>int</code>s and <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare how primitives and reference types are converted in <code>String</code> concatenation.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitives (and <code>null</code>) are converted to their standard literal form; reference types are converted by calling their <code>toString</code> method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both are converted by calling their <code>toString</code> methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Primitives cannot be concatenated with <code>String</code>s; only reference types can.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Reference types use their literal form; primitives use their <code>toString</code> method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Escape sequences in Strings start with a <code>\</code> and have a special meaning in Java. Escape sequences used in this course include <code>\"</code>, <code>\\</code>, and <code>\n</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What character begins an escape sequence in a Java <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The backslash character <code>\</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The forward slash character <code>/</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The caret character <code>^</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The ampersand character <code>&amp;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the escape sequence <code>\n</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A newline character.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A null character.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A literal backslash followed by the letter <code>n</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A non-breaking space.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you include a double quote inside a <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use the escape sequence <code>\"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use two double quotes in a row, like <code>""</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the escape sequence <code>\'</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Enclose the quote with parentheses, like <code>(")</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you include a single backslash in a <code>String</code> literal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>\\</code>, because <code>\</code> alone begins an escape sequence.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>\</code> by itself; it represents one backslash.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>/\</code>, which escapes to a single backslash.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>\b</code>, which represents a literal backslash.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you just write <code>"</code> inside a <code>String</code> literal to include a quote?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because an unescaped <code>"</code> would end the literal; you must write <code>\"</code> instead.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>"</code> is reserved as an escape-sequence character in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>"</code> is automatically converted to whitespace in literals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java <code>String</code> literals cannot contain any punctuation characters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A <code>String</code> object has index values from 0 to length – 1. Attempting to access indexes outside this range (i.e. less than 0 or greater than or equal to the length of the String) will result in an <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the range of valid indexes for a <code>String</code> of length <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>n - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>From <code>1</code> to <code>n</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>n</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From <code>1</code> to <code>n - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown when you access an invalid index in a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IndexOutOfRangeException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IllegalArgumentException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is index <code>length()</code> a valid index into a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Valid indexes only go up to <code>length() - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Indexes go from <code>0</code> to <code>length()</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for reading, not for modification.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>String</code> is non-empty.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(-1)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> because the index is outside the valid range.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns the last character of <code>s</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns an empty <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It silently wraps around to the end of the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is a negative index invalid on a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code> indexes start at 0; anything less than 0 is outside the valid range and causes a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because negative indexes are reserved for counting from the end of the <code>String</code>, which Java does not support on <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java converts negative indexes to zero, which is technically a different operation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code>s internally store only positive integer indexes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You can think of the index as the number that tells you how far from the front of the string a given character is. Thus the second character in a <code>String</code> has index 1 because there is one character ahead of it. And the first character has index 0 because there are zero characters ahead of it. The length of the string is not a valid index because there is no character in an n-character string that has n characters in front of it.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Conceptually, what does a <code>String</code> index represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>How far from the front of the <code>String</code> a given character is — i.e., how many characters are ahead of it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The ASCII code of the character at that position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of characters behind the given character.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A unique identifier assigned randomly to each character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the first character of a <code>String</code> have index 0?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because there are zero characters ahead of it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java counts from 1, but subtracts 1 for historical reasons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because index 0 is reserved as a placeholder in every <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the first slot in memory is always index 0 regardless of content.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What index does the second character of a <code>String</code> have, and why?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Index 1, because there is one character ahead of it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Index 2, because it is the second character in the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Index 0, because both the first and second characters are at the start.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Index 1, because Java assigns indexes based on ASCII order.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>length()</code> never a valid character index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because no character in an n-character <code>String</code> has n characters in front of it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>length()</code> always returns zero for a well-formed <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java reserves index <code>length()</code> for an internal terminator character.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>length()</code> counts only non-whitespace characters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>"cat"</code>, what index does <code>'t'</code> have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Index 2, because there are two characters (<code>'c'</code> and <code>'a'</code>) ahead of it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Index 3, because it is the third character.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Index 1, because it is one position from the end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Index 0, because it is the last character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String(String str)</code> — Constructs a new String object that represents the same sequence of characters as str. There is almost no reason to ever use this constructor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the constructor <code>String(String str)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It constructs a new <code>String</code> object representing the same sequence of characters as <code>str</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It modifies <code>str</code> in place to include new characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns a reference to <code>str</code> itself without creating a new object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It converts <code>str</code> to a <code>char[]</code> and returns that.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is there almost no reason to use <code>new String(str)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>str</code> is already a <code>String</code>, and <code>String</code>s are immutable, so making a copy serves no practical purpose.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java will not let you call constructors on immutable types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>String</code> class does not actually have a <code>String(String)</code> constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the constructor is deprecated and will be removed in a future version.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of object is produced by <code>new String("hi")</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>String</code> object with the same characters as <code>"hi"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The original literal <code>"hi"</code>, with no new object created.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char[]</code> containing <code>'h'</code> and <code>'i'</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A primitive value holding the text <code>hi</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast <code>String s = "hi";</code> with <code>String s = new String("hi");</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both give <code>s</code> a <code>String</code> with the characters <code>h</code> and <code>i</code>; the literal form is preferred because the constructor adds no real value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The literal form creates a primitive; the constructor form creates an object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the constructor form makes the <code>String</code> immutable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two forms produce <code>String</code>s with different character contents.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the <code>String(String str)</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, it is listed on the AP Java Quick Reference.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No, it has been removed from the reference in recent updates.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No, only methods (not constructors) are listed on the reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the <code>String()</code> no-argument constructor is on the reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int length()</code> — Returns the number of characters in a String object</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>String</code> method <code>length()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of characters in the <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The number of bytes used to store the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The last valid index in the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of words in the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>String.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hello".length()</code> evaluate to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>5</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>4</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>6</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"hello"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If <code>s.length()</code> returns <code>n</code>, what is the largest valid index into <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>n</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n + 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n / 2</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"".length()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code>, because the empty <code>String</code> contains zero characters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code>, because the empty <code>String</code> still counts its terminator.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code>, because there are no characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String substring(int from, int to)</code> — Returns the substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to − 1</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>substring(int from, int to)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The substring beginning at index <code>from</code> and ending at index <code>to</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The substring beginning at index <code>from + 1</code> and ending at index <code>to</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The characters of the <code>String</code> between positions <code>from</code> and <code>to</code>, counting from the end.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is the <code>to</code> index in <code>substring(from, to)</code> inclusive or exclusive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Exclusive — the character at index <code>to</code> is not included.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inclusive; the character at index <code>to</code> is included.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on whether <code>to</code> is greater than <code>from</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Exclusive only when <code>to</code> equals <code>length()</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"abcdef".substring(1, 4)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"bcd"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>"bcde"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"abcd"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"cde"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many characters are in the result of <code>s.substring(from, to)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>to - from</code> characters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>to - from + 1</code> characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>to - from - 1</code> characters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Always the same number of characters as the original <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(from, to)</code> with <code>to</code> greater than <code>s.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It silently truncates to <code>s.length()</code> and returns the valid portion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns an empty <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String substring(int from)</code> — Equivalent to <code>substring(from, length())</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the single-argument <code>substring(int from)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The substring from index <code>from</code> to the end of the <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> containing only the character at index <code>from</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The substring from the beginning of the <code>String</code> to index <code>from</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The substring starting at index <code>from + 1</code> and continuing to the end.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What call is <code>s.substring(from)</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>s.substring(from, s.length())</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>s.substring(0, from)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>s.substring(from, from + 1)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>s.substring(from, s.length() - 1)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hello".substring(2)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>"llo"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>"he"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"ll"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>"l"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>s.substring(0)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> equal to <code>s</code> — the entire original <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An empty <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Just the first character of <code>s</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>substring(int from)</code> with <code>substring(int from, int to)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-argument form always runs from <code>from</code> to the end; the two-argument form lets you specify both a start and an exclusive end index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The one-argument form takes only an end index; the two-argument form takes a start and an end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two-argument form includes both endpoints; the one-argument form excludes the start.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The one-argument form is deprecated in favor of the two-argument form.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int indexOf(String str)</code> — Returns the index of the first occurrence of str; returns <code>-1</code> if not found</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>indexOf(String str)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The index of the first occurrence of <code>str</code> in the <code>String</code>, or <code>-1</code> if it is not found.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The index of the last occurrence of <code>str</code>, or <code>0</code> if not found.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>boolean</code> indicating whether <code>str</code> is present.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of occurrences of <code>str</code> in the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How can you tell, using <code>indexOf</code>, whether a <code>String</code> contains another <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether <code>indexOf</code> returns a value other than <code>-1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Check whether <code>indexOf</code> returns <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Check whether <code>indexOf</code> returns a value greater than the <code>String</code>'s length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>indexOf</code> twice and compare the results.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"banana".indexOf("na")</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>2</code>, the index of the first occurrence of <code>"na"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>4</code>, the index of the last occurrence.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code>, the index just before the first occurrence.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code>, because <code>"na"</code> is not a single character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>indexOf</code> return if the target string is not found?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>-1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The length of the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a <code>String</code> contains several occurrences of <code>str</code>, which index does <code>indexOf(str)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The index of the first (leftmost) occurrence.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The index of the last (rightmost) occurrence.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the middle occurrence.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A random index among the matching occurrences.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>boolean equals(Object other)</code> — Returns <code>true</code> if other is a String and its text is the same as the text of the <code>String</code> <code>equals</code> was called on. Otherwise returns <code>false</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>String.equals(Object other)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code> if <code>other</code> is a <code>String</code> with the same text as the receiver; <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code> if <code>other</code> references the same object as the receiver; <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code> if <code>other</code> is any kind of object with the same <code>hashCode</code>; <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> indicating how many characters differ between the two.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why should you use <code>equals</code> instead of <code>==</code> to compare <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>==</code> compares references; <code>equals</code> compares the actual text of the <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code> is faster than <code>==</code> for comparing <code>String</code> objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code> does not compile when used with <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>equals</code> ignores capitalization, while <code>==</code> does not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hi".equals("hi")</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code>, because the two literals are distinct objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>, because the <code>String</code>s are equal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because you cannot call <code>equals</code> on a literal.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"hi".equals(new Object())</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code>, because the argument is not a <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>, because any non-<code>null</code> object is considered equal to a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile-time error, because <code>equals</code> requires a <code>String</code> argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>ClassCastException</code> at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>equals</code> consider capitalization when comparing <code>String</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. <code>"Hi".equals("hi")</code> returns <code>false</code> because the text must be the same.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. <code>equals</code> compares <code>String</code>s ignoring case.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when comparing single-character <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if one of the <code>String</code>s is empty.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int compareTo(String other)</code> — Returns a value &lt; 0 if the <code>String</code> is alphabetically less than <code>other</code>; returns zero if it is <code>equals</code> to <code>other</code>; and returns a value &gt; 0 if it is greater than <code>other</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>compareTo</code> return when two <code>String</code>s are equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Zero.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A positive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A negative value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a negative return value from <code>s.compareTo(other)</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically less than <code>other</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically greater than <code>other</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> and <code>other</code> have the same characters in different order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> is shorter than <code>other</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a positive return value from <code>s.compareTo(other)</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically greater than <code>other</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> is alphabetically less than <code>other</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> contains all the characters of <code>other</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That <code>s</code> is longer than <code>other</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast <code>equals</code> and <code>compareTo</code> for <code>String</code>s.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code> returns a <code>boolean</code> indicating whether two <code>String</code>s have the same text; <code>compareTo</code> returns an <code>int</code> indicating their alphabetical ordering.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both return <code>boolean</code>s, but <code>compareTo</code> ignores capitalization.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both return <code>int</code>s, with <code>equals</code> returning <code>1</code> or <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>compareTo</code> returns a <code>boolean</code>, while <code>equals</code> returns an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you test whether <code>s</code> comes before <code>t</code> alphabetically using <code>compareTo</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Check whether <code>s.compareTo(t) &lt; 0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Check whether <code>s.compareTo(t) &gt; 0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Check whether <code>s.equals(t)</code> returns <code>false</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Check whether <code>s.indexOf(t) == 0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>String[] split(String del)</code> — Returns a <code>String</code> array where each element is a substring of this <code>String</code>, which has been split around matches of the given expression <code>del</code></ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>split(String del)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> array whose elements are the pieces of the original <code>String</code> split around matches of <code>del</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single <code>String</code> with the delimiters removed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> of the pieces between delimiters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the first delimiter in the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>String.split</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String[]</code> — an array of <code>String</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>List&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a likely result of <code>"a,b,c".split(",")</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An array of three <code>String</code>s: <code>"a"</code>, <code>"b"</code>, and <code>"c"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A single <code>String</code> <code>"abc"</code> with the commas removed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An array of six <code>String</code>s including the commas as separate elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An array of two <code>String</code>s: <code>"a,"</code> and <code>"b,c"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role does the argument <code>del</code> play in <code>split</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is the delimiter expression; the <code>String</code> is split around matches of <code>del</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is the separator character that is inserted between pieces of the result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is a prefix that must appear at the start of the <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is the number of pieces to split the <code>String</code> into.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you want to break a sentence into words separated by spaces, what method could you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>split</code>, passing a space (or whitespace pattern) as the delimiter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>substring</code>, repeatedly called at each space.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>indexOf</code>, which returns the array of words directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>length</code>, combined with a <code>for</code> loop over each character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>A one-character <code>String</code> at index <code>i</code> in the <code>String</code> <code>s</code> can be obtained by calling <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code>.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you get a one-character <code>String</code> at index <code>i</code> of <code>String</code> <code>s</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Call <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>s.charAt(i)</code>, which returns a one-character <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>s.substring(i)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>s.indexOf(i)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> yield exactly one character?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>substring</code>'s second argument is exclusive, so the result has length <code>(i + 1) - i = 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>substring</code>'s second argument is inclusive, so both index <code>i</code> and <code>i + 1</code> are returned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java always returns one character when the two arguments differ by one, regardless of inclusivity.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>substring</code> internally uses <code>charAt</code> when the arguments are adjacent.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>"cat".substring(1, 2)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-character <code>String</code> <code>"a"</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The one-character <code>String</code> <code>"c"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two-character <code>String</code> <code>"at"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>char</code> value <code>'a'</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type is produced by <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> — a <code>char</code> or a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>String</code> (of length 1), not a <code>char</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char</code>, not a <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>char[]</code> containing a single element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> representing the character code.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>s.substring(i, i + 1)</code> with <code>i</code> equal to <code>s.length()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws a <code>StringIndexOutOfBoundsException</code> because <code>i</code> is outside the valid index range.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns an empty <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns the last character of <code>s</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>The <code>System</code> class</title>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> display information on the computer monitor.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They display information on the computer monitor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They read input from the keyboard.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They write data into a file on disk.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They return a <code>String</code> representation of their arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where is output from <code>System.out.print</code> sent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To the computer monitor (standard output).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To a text file named <code>System.out</code> in the current directory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To the keyboard input buffer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To the Java compiler as a log message.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In AP CSA, which class are <code>print</code> and <code>println</code> typically accessed through?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>System</code> class, via <code>System.out</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Console</code> class, via <code>Console.print</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>String</code> class, via <code>String.out</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Output</code> class, via <code>Output.print</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you wanted to display a message to the user in a simple Java program, which methods would you use?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>System.out.print</code> or <code>System.out.println</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Scanner.print</code> or <code>Scanner.println</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Console.write</code> or <code>Console.writeLine</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>System.in.print</code> or <code>System.in.println</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of information can <code>System.out.print</code> display?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Any information that can be converted to a <code>String</code>, which is then shown on the monitor.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>String</code> values; primitives must be converted manually first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only values that are already <code>String</code>s; anything else causes a compile error.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only primitive values, not objects.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>System.out.println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after the information has been displayed, while <code>System.out.print</code> does not.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the difference between <code>System.out.print</code> and <code>System.out.println</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>println</code> moves the cursor to a new line after displaying the information; <code>print</code> does not.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>print</code> adds a space after the output while <code>println</code> does not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>print</code> writes to the console and <code>println</code> writes to a file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>println</code> flushes the output buffer while <code>print</code> does not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>System.out.print("Hi")</code> twice in a row, what appears on screen?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>HiHi</code> on a single line, because <code>print</code> does not advance to a new line.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Hi</code> on one line and <code>Hi</code> on the next line.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only one <code>Hi</code>, because <code>print</code> does not actually produce output until <code>println</code> is called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compile error, because <code>print</code> cannot be called twice in a row.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you call <code>System.out.println("Hi")</code> twice in a row, what appears on screen?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Hi</code> on one line and <code>Hi</code> on the next, because <code>println</code> advances the cursor to a new line after each call.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>HiHi</code> on a single line, because <code>println</code> does not separate calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Hi Hi</code> on one line with a space between them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only one <code>Hi</code>, because the second call overwrites the first.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which method would you use to display output without ending the current line?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>System.out.print</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>System.out.println</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>System.out.write</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>System.out.display</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the cursor after <code>System.out.println("done")</code> runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It moves to the start of the next line.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It stays at the end of the word <code>done</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns to the start of the current line without advancing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It moves two lines down to leave a blank line.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>The <code>Math</code> class</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The <code>Math</code> class is part of Java and is available in all Java programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does the <code>Math</code> class come from?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is part of Java itself and is available in all Java programs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is a user-defined class that must be written by the programmer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is part of the <code>java.util</code> package and must be imported.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is provided by the operating system, not Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to import the <code>Math</code> class explicitly to use it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is part of Java and available in all Java programs without special setup.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You must write <code>import java.lang.Math;</code> at the top of every file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You must write <code>import java.util.Math;</code> at the top of every file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you are using static methods like <code>Math.sqrt</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math</code> a class you have to write yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is provided as part of Java's standard library.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. Every Java program must define its own <code>Math</code> class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you want to use methods other than <code>sqrt</code> and <code>abs</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, unless you import it from an external library.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you are writing a brand-new Java program, can you use <code>Math</code> right away?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, because <code>Math</code> is available in all Java programs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. You must first add an import statement and compile separately.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only after creating an instance with <code>new Math()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only after enabling the <code>java.math</code> module in your build settings.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of functionality does the <code>Math</code> class provide?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Common mathematical operations and constants, available to every Java program.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Classes for reading and writing files.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Methods for parsing <code>String</code>s into numeric types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Graphical drawing primitives for mathematical figures.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The <code>Math</code> class contains only static methods.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of methods does the <code>Math</code> class contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only <code>static</code> methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A mix of <code>static</code> and instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>abstract</code> methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you need to create a <code>Math</code> object to call its methods?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Because all of <code>Math</code>'s methods are <code>static</code>, you call them on the class itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. You must write <code>new Math().sqrt(x)</code> to call any <code>Math</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for methods that return a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method takes more than one argument.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the correct way to call <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the class: <code>Math.sqrt(x)</code>. You do not need an instance of <code>Math</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On an instance: <code>new Math().sqrt(x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the <code>this</code> reference: <code>this.sqrt(x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Through <code>System.Math.sqrt(x)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>new Math()</code> not something you see in typical code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>Math</code> contains only <code>static</code> methods, so there is no reason to create an instance.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Math</code> is a <code>final</code> class that cannot be instantiated.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>Math</code> constructor throws an exception if called.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Math</code> is an interface, and interfaces cannot be instantiated.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Contrast calling an instance method on a <code>String</code> with calling a method on the <code>Math</code> class.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Instance methods on a <code>String</code> are called on a specific <code>String</code> object; <code>Math</code> methods are <code>static</code> and are called on the class itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> methods are <code>static</code>; <code>Math</code> methods are instance methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both <code>String</code> and <code>Math</code> methods are <code>static</code> and called on the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> methods require an import; <code>Math</code> methods do not.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You should know how to use the methods <code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, and <code>Math.random</code>. (You should also know about the variable—not a method—<code>Math.PI</code> whose value is the double value that best approximates the value of π.)</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which four <code>Math</code> methods should you know how to use for the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.abs</code>, <code>Math.pow</code>, <code>Math.sqrt</code>, and <code>Math.random</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.min</code>, <code>Math.max</code>, <code>Math.floor</code>, and <code>Math.ceil</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.sin</code>, <code>Math.cos</code>, <code>Math.tan</code>, and <code>Math.log</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.add</code>, <code>Math.sub</code>, <code>Math.mul</code>, and <code>Math.div</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Math.PI</code> a method or a variable?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A variable, not a method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns <code>Math.PI</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword built into the Java language.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>static</code> method that must be called with parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does <code>Math.PI</code> hold?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>double</code> value that best approximates π.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Exactly the mathematical value of pi, with infinite precision.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> approximation of pi rounded to the nearest whole number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>float</code> value <code>3.14f</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which <code>Math</code> member would you use to get the value of π in a calculation?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.PI</code> — it is a variable, not a method, so you don't write parentheses.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pi()</code>; a method that returns pi.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.PI()</code>; with parentheses because it is a method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.getPi()</code>; a getter method for the constant.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might <code>Math.PI()</code> fail to compile?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>PI</code> is a variable, not a method, so you cannot call it with parentheses.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Math.PI</code> requires an argument that is missing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Math.PI</code> is <code>private</code> and cannot be called from outside the class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>PI</code> is not part of the <code>Math</code> class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>int abs(int x)</code> — Returns the absolute value of an int value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.abs(int x)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The absolute value of <code>x</code>, as an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The square root of <code>x</code>, as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>x</code> with its sign flipped, whether positive or negative.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The value of <code>x</code> rounded toward zero.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.abs(-7)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>7</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>-7</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>49</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of the <code>int</code> version of <code>Math.abs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.abs</code> do to a non-negative <code>int</code> value?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It returns the value unchanged.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It negates it, producing a negative value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>0</code> regardless of the input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It increments it by one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Conceptually, what is the "absolute value" that <code>Math.abs</code> computes?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The magnitude of the number, ignoring its sign.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The value after removing the decimal portion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The value rounded to the nearest integer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The distance between the number and the next whole number.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double abs(double x)</code> — Returns the absolute value of a double value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>double</code> version of <code>Math.abs</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The absolute value of the <code>double</code> argument, as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The absolute value of the <code>double</code> argument, converted to an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The integer portion of the <code>double</code> argument with no sign.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code> that is always positive, even if the input was <code>NaN</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.abs(-3.5)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>3.5</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>-3.5</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>3</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>4.0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does <code>Math</code> have both an <code>int</code> and a <code>double</code> version of <code>abs</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that it can take the absolute value of either <code>int</code> or <code>double</code> arguments and return the same type it received.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>int</code> version is deprecated and will be removed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>double</code> version is internally implemented using the <code>int</code> version.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not allow a single method to accept multiple numeric types.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type does <code>Math.abs(2.0)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compare <code>Math.abs(int)</code> and <code>Math.abs(double)</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both return the absolute value of their argument; one takes and returns an <code>int</code>, the other takes and returns a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>int</code> version returns a <code>double</code>; the <code>double</code> version returns an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the <code>double</code> version is on the AP Java Quick Reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are the same method with different names; Java picks one automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double pow(double base, double exponent)</code> — Returns the value of the first parameter raised to the power of the second parameter</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.pow(base, exponent)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value of <code>base</code> raised to the power of <code>exponent</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The product of <code>base</code> and <code>exponent</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The logarithm of <code>base</code> with respect to <code>exponent</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>base</code> multiplied by itself <code>exponent</code> times, as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It depends on the types of the arguments.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.pow(2, 3)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>8.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>6.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>9.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>8</code> as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How would you compute x squared using <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.pow(x, 2)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(2, x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(x, x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(x * 2)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are the parameter types of <code>Math.pow</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Two <code>double</code>s: the base and the exponent.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Two <code>int</code>s: the base and the exponent.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> base and a <code>double</code> exponent.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code> base and an <code>int</code> exponent.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double sqrt(double x)</code> — Returns the positive square root of a double value</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Math.sqrt(x)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The positive square root of <code>x</code>, as a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The positive square root of <code>x</code>, as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both the positive and negative square roots of <code>x</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The value of <code>x</code> divided by 2.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is <code>Math.sqrt(16)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>4.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>4</code> as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>8.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>16.0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>Math.sqrt</code> return both positive and negative roots?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It returns only the positive square root.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. It returns an array of both roots.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only for perfect squares.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the argument is negative.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you compute the square root of <code>x</code> using <code>Math.pow</code> instead of <code>Math.sqrt</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Math.pow(x, 0.5)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(x, 2)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(0.5, x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Math.pow(x, -2)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek><code>double random()</code> — Returns a double value greater than or equal to 0.0 and less than 1.0.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What range of values does <code>Math.random()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>double</code> greater than or equal to <code>0.0</code> and strictly less than <code>1.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code> greater than <code>0.0</code> and less than or equal to <code>1.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>double</code> greater than or equal to <code>0.0</code> and less than or equal to <code>1.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> between <code>0</code> and <code>1</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>Math.random()</code> ever return exactly <code>1.0</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Its range is <code>[0.0, 1.0)</code>, so <code>1.0</code> is excluded.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. <code>1.0</code> is the maximum value it can return.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only once per program run.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if no previous call has returned a value greater than <code>0.5</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can <code>Math.random()</code> return <code>0.0</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes. The lower bound <code>0.0</code> is included in its range.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No. The lower bound is exclusive, so <code>0.0</code> is never returned.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only as the very first call in a program.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No, because <code>0.0</code> is reserved to indicate an error.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>Math.random()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>Math.random()</code> take any arguments?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It is called with no arguments.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes. It takes an upper bound as an argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. It takes a lower and upper bound as two arguments.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes. It takes a seed value to make the sequence reproducible.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Values returned from <code>Math.random</code> are in the range 0.0 to 1.0 but can be manipulated to produce a random int or double in any desired range by scaling (multiplying) and shifting (adding).</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two operations let you turn <code>Math.random()</code> into a value in any desired range?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scaling (multiplying) and shifting (adding).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Casting and rounding.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Dividing and subtracting.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Taking the absolute value and scaling.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "scaling" a value from <code>Math.random()</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiplying it by some number to stretch its range from <code>[0.0, 1.0)</code> to a wider (or narrower) range.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Dividing it by some number to shrink the range.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rounding it to the nearest integer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Taking its square root to reduce its magnitude.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does "shifting" a value from <code>Math.random()</code> mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Adding a constant to move the range up or down.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Multiplying it by a constant to change the range's width.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rotating the bits of its binary representation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Subtracting it from <code>1.0</code> to invert its range.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you produce a random <code>double</code> in the range <code>[0.0, 10.0)</code> using <code>Math.random</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Multiply <code>Math.random()</code> by <code>10.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Add <code>10.0</code> to <code>Math.random()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>Math.random() * Math.random() * 10.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>Math.pow(Math.random(), 10)</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How could you produce a random <code>double</code> in the range <code>[5.0, 15.0)</code> using <code>Math.random</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scale by 10 and shift by 5: <code>Math.random() * 10.0 + 5.0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Multiply <code>Math.random()</code> by <code>15.0</code> and subtract <code>5.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Multiply <code>Math.random()</code> by <code>5.0</code> and add <code>15.0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Add <code>5.0</code> to <code>Math.random()</code> without scaling.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>ArrayLists</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `ArrayList` class is part of the `java.util` package and needs to be imported to be used in a class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which package contains the <code>ArrayList</code> class?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>java.util</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>java.lang</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.io</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>java.collections</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What must you do before you can use <code>ArrayList</code> in a class?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Import it from <code>java.util</code> (e.g. <code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Nothing — it is in <code>java.lang</code> and imported automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declare it with the keyword <code>generic</code> before use.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>ArrayList.init()</code> at the start of <code>main</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can you use <code>String</code> without an import but not <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> lives in <code>java.lang</code>, which is imported automatically. <code>ArrayList</code> lives in <code>java.util</code>, which must be imported explicitly.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> is a primitive type, while <code>ArrayList</code> is a class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> is built into the JVM, while <code>ArrayList</code> lives in a third-party library.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> is imported by every file automatically, while <code>ArrayList</code> must be declared in a package statement.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you try to use <code>ArrayList</code> in a file without importing it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler reports an error saying the symbol <code>ArrayList</code> cannot be found.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program runs but every element comes out as <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A warning is printed and <code>ArrayList</code> is treated as a raw <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>ClassNotFoundException</code> is thrown at run time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What import statement brings in <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>import java.util.ArrayList;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>import java.util.*;</code> only — <code>ArrayList</code> itself cannot be imported by name.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>#include java.util.ArrayList;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>import ArrayList from java.util;</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>An `ArrayList` object is mutable and contains object references.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say an <code>ArrayList</code> is "mutable"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its contents can be changed after it is created: you can add, remove, and replace elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It means new elements can be added only while the list is being constructed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means the list automatically sorts itself whenever an element changes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means the list's type parameter can be changed at run time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does an <code>ArrayList</code> store objects directly or references to them?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It stores object references, not the objects themselves.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It stores the objects themselves, copying each one into the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It stores both a copy and a reference, depending on the element type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It stores primitive values directly and objects by reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If two <code>ArrayList</code>s both contain a reference to the same object and that object is mutated, what do both lists see?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both lists see the mutation, because they hold references to the same underlying object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only the first list sees the mutation; the second keeps the old value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither list sees the mutation, because each list has its own private copy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both lists throw <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> on the next access.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does an <code>ArrayList</code> being mutable contrast with a <code>String</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> is immutable: its characters can't change. An <code>ArrayList</code>'s contents can be modified in place.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They're the same: both can be modified in place through their methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> is mutable through <code>concat</code>; <code>ArrayList</code> is immutable once constructed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> stores characters by reference, while <code>ArrayList</code> stores them by value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can an <code>ArrayList</code> hold primitive <code>int</code> values directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It stores object references, so primitives must be wrapped (e.g. in <code>Integer</code>).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, using <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only if you call <code>ArrayList.allowPrimitives()</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>int</code> values are automatically stored as references.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The no-argument `ArrayList` constructor constructs an empty list.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;()</code> produce?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new, empty <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> containing zero elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A new <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> pre-populated with an empty string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A reference to a shared, global empty string list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> with a default capacity of 10 nulls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the size of a newly constructed <code>ArrayList</code> made with the no-argument constructor?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>10</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code>, what does <code>nums.size()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>10</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you create an empty list of <code>Double</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Double[] list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList list = new ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;();</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you call <code>get(0)</code> on a freshly constructed empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code> is thrown because there is no element at index 0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>0</code> as a default value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>NullPointerException</code> is thrown.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Indexes for an `ArrayList` start at `0` and end at `size() − 1`, inclusive.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the first element of an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>size() - 1</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the last element of a non-empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 1</code></p></answer>
