    <cards>
      <ek>`ArrayList` is a generic type which means we can write the type `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` to mean an `ArrayList` that can only contain values of the type `E`. E.g. `ArrayList&lt;String&gt;` is a list of `String`s.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean that <code>ArrayList</code> is a "generic" type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is parameterized by a type; you write <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> to specify what kind of elements the list contains.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It means the list can hold any mix of types at the same time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means the list is optimized for generic, general-purpose data.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means the list's element type is decided at run time based on the first <code>add</code> call.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What type of elements does an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> contain?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only <code>String</code> references.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both <code>String</code> and <code>char</code> references.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code> objects by value (copied in).</p></distractor>
