        <distractor><p>The value is silently converted to a <code>String</code> via <code>toString()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The <code>add</code> method returns <code>false</code> and the list is unchanged.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> differ from <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They differ only in the element type they accept; the list behavior is the same.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> is faster because it stores primitives directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> supports <code>add</code>/<code>remove</code>, while <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> only supports <code>get</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> has a larger default capacity than <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Compared to a plain <code>ArrayList</code>, what does parameterizing with a type give you?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Compile-time type checking so that only the right element type can go in, and no casts are needed when taking elements out.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Faster element access at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Automatic sorting of the elements by type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The ability to store primitive values directly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E` is called a "type parameter" because it is filled in with a specific type like `String`. Type parameters have to be reference types.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code>, what is <code>E</code> called?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A type parameter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A generic variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A type argument.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A placeholder class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of types are allowed as type parameters in Java generics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only reference types (classes, interfaces, other generics). Primitive types are not allowed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Primitive types only; reference types are not allowed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any type, including primitives like <code>int</code> and <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only classes — interfaces and other generics are not allowed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you write <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. <code>int</code> is a primitive type, and type parameters must be reference types. Use <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code> instead.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — <code>int</code> is allowed as a type parameter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only inside a method body, not as a field.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but the compiler silently converts it to <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is a type parameter "filled in"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By supplying a specific reference type at the use site, e.g. <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code> fills <code>E</code> with <code>String</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By calling <code>setType(Class&lt;?&gt;)</code> on the <code>ArrayList</code> after construction.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By passing a <code>Class</code> object to the constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By inferring the type from the first element added to the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is the type parameter a "parameter"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because, like a method parameter takes a value, a type parameter takes a type — supplied by the code that uses the generic class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because it is a special kind of method parameter that holds a type at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM reserves a parameter slot on the stack for the type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it is passed by reference to every generic method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` is specified, the types of the parameters in methods that accept elements, e.g. `add`, and the return types of methods that return elements, e.g. `get`, will be `E`.</ek>

