    <cards>
      <ek>The type `ArrayList&lt;E&gt;` is preferred over the so-called "raw" type `ArrayList` because it allows the compiler to find errors that would otherwise be found at run-time.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "raw" <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> written without a type parameter, like plain <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> declared with <code>&lt;?&gt;</code> as its type parameter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> whose elements have not yet been initialized.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>ArrayList</code> that stores primitive values directly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>ArrayList&lt;E&gt;</code> preferred over the raw type?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because it lets the compiler catch type errors at compile time instead of failing at run time.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because raw <code>ArrayList</code>s are slower at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because raw <code>ArrayList</code>s can only hold <code>String</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the raw type has been removed from modern Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of errors does using the raw type tend to push into run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ClassCastException</code>s and other type mismatches that could have been caught statically.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>NullPointerException</code>s from uninitialized elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException</code>s from shifted positions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>StackOverflowError</code>s from recursive generic resolution.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If you assign a mixed bag of objects into a raw <code>ArrayList</code>, when do problems usually surface?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At run time, when code pulls an element out and casts it to the wrong type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At compile time, because the compiler rejects the mixed <code>add</code> calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the program starts, during class loading.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Never — raw lists silently coerce every element to <code>Object</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the general lesson about compile-time vs run-time errors from generics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Catching errors at compile time is better: the problem is found before the program runs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Runtime errors are preferable because they show the real data that caused the problem.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compile-time errors are cosmetic; runtime errors are what really matter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both happen at the same time with generics, so it doesn't matter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Typically you invoke the `ArrayList` constructor as `ArrayList&lt;&gt;()`, i.e. with nothing between the `&lt;&gt;`s as the Java compiler will infer the correct element type.</ek>

