    <cards>
      <ek>Iteration statements can be used to access all the elements in an `ArrayList`. This is called traversing the `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is meant by "traversing" an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Visiting each element in turn using an iteration statement.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Copying every element into a new list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sorting the list into ascending order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Searching for a single specific element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which kinds of loops can be used to traverse an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Indexed <code>for</code> loops, <code>while</code> loops, and enhanced <code>for</code> loops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Only enhanced <code>for</code> loops — indexed loops are not allowed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only indexed <code>for</code> loops — <code>while</code> and enhanced <code>for</code> don't work on <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>do-while</code> loops exclusively, because they always run at least once.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Write a simple traversal of <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt; xs</code> using an enhanced <code>for</code> loop.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (String s : xs) { System.out.println(s); }</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for (int i : xs) { System.out.println(xs.get(i)); }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for (String s = 0; s &lt; xs.size(); s++) { System.out.println(s); }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>xs.forEach(s -&gt; System.out.println(i));</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is traversing an <code>ArrayList</code> similar to traversing an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You visit elements in order by index, typically from 0 to the last valid index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both use <code>.length</code> to get the bound.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both require an explicit <code>Iterator</code> to step through elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both store elements contiguously in raw memory accessed via pointer arithmetic.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is traversal important for list algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Most list algorithms need to examine or process every element, which requires some form of traversal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM only allows element access inside a loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because traversal is the only way to get the list's size.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because without traversal, elements would be garbage collected.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>There are standard `ArrayList` algorithms that utilize traversals to insert and delete elements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What do standard <code>ArrayList</code> insertion/deletion algorithms rely on?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing the list to find the right position(s) and then inserting or deleting elements there.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Calling <code>sort</code> on the list first, then operating on it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A special <code>modify</code> method that does the work atomically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Converting the list to an array, editing it, and converting it back.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an insertion task on an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inserting a new value into a sorted list so the list stays in order.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Replacing every element with its square.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Removing duplicates from an unsorted list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Counting how many elements are negative.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a deletion task on an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Removing all elements that meet some condition, such as all negative numbers.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Swapping the first and last elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Appending a new element to the end of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Finding the sum of all the elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are insertion and deletion often bundled with traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You must traverse the list to locate the elements that need to be inserted next to or removed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>ArrayList</code> doesn't have any direct <code>add</code> or <code>remove</code> methods.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because insertion and deletion require the list to be sorted first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because traversal is the only way to change the size of the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does an insertion into the middle of an <code>ArrayList</code> do to following elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It shifts them one position to the right to make room.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It overwrites the element currently at that index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It leaves the following elements alone but makes the list smaller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It swaps the new element with the one at that index.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Deleting elements during a traversal of an `ArrayList` requires using special techniques to avoid skipping elements.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why does naive deletion during traversal skip elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Removing an element shifts later elements left by one, so advancing the index normally jumps over the element that moved into the current position.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the list is re-sorted after every removal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>remove</code> returns a new list, leaving the old one unchanged.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the iterator caches element positions from before the loop started.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>One standard technique for deleting from an <code>ArrayList</code> during traversal is...?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Don't increment the index on iterations where you remove an element, so the next iteration examines the shifted-in element.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Always increment the index after a removal and accept that one element will be skipped.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>remove</code> twice for every element you want to delete.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use two indexes that always move at the same rate.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is another technique for safely deleting from an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traverse from the end toward the beginning, so removals don't affect indexes you haven't visited yet.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Skip every other element on the way forward to avoid the shift.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Increment the index by two after every removal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Remove every element and then add back the ones you wanted to keep.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you just use an enhanced <code>for</code> loop to delete elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It throws <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> when the list's size changes during iteration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>remove</code> is not defined on <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the loop variable is a copy, so changes to it don't affect the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because enhanced <code>for</code> loops hide the index, so you don't know which element to remove.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What bug appears if you delete an element with <code>remove(i)</code> and then write <code>i++</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You skip over the element that was shifted into index <code>i</code>, failing to examine it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program throws <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element at index <code>i - 1</code> is removed a second time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The loop runs forever because the index never reaches the end.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Most algorithms that work with arrays work equally well with `ArrayList`s after switching `.length` to `.size()` and array accesses and assignments to `get` and `set` calls.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a.length</code> from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.size()</code> instead.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>a.length()</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a.count</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList.length(a)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a[i]</code> (read) from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.get(i)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>a[i]</code> — the same syntax works for both.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a.read(i)</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a.at(i)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you translate <code>a[i] = x</code> from an array to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use <code>a.set(i, x)</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>a.add(i, x)</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a[i] = x</code> — the same syntax works for both.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a.put(i, x)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do you usually have to rewrite the logic of an array algorithm when porting it to an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — the structure stays the same; only the syntax for length and element access changes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — the underlying data structures are different enough to require a full rewrite.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>ArrayList</code> traversal uses iterators instead of indexes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sometimes — it depends on whether the algorithm removes elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the straightforward syntactic translation between array and <code>ArrayList</code> algorithms work without rewriting the logic?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s both provide O(1) indexed access to elements; only the syntax differs.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM secretly represents every <code>ArrayList</code> as an array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s have identical method names once compiled.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>ArrayList</code> inherits from the array type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Some algorithms require multiple `String`, array, or `ArrayList` objects to be traversed simultaneously.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a "parallel traversal"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Traversing two or more collections at the same time, typically stepping through them in lockstep by index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Traversing a single collection twice, once forward and once backward.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Traversing one collection using two threads at the same time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Traversing a collection and simultaneously sorting it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an algorithm needing parallel traversal.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Comparing two arrays element by element to decide whether they are equal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Counting how many times a single value appears in one array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sorting a single list into ascending order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Finding the largest element in an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When parallel-traversing two <code>ArrayList</code>s, what should you typically check first?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That they have compatible sizes for the operation you're performing.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That both lists have the same type parameter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the first element of each list is equal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That neither list is currently being iterated by anyone else.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't an enhanced <code>for</code> loop always handle parallel traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It exposes only one element at a time from one collection; you usually need an index to access both collections at the same position.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because enhanced <code>for</code> loops run in parallel threads by default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because an enhanced <code>for</code> loop stops at the end of the shorter collection without warning.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because enhanced <code>for</code> loops cannot iterate over <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name another scenario that requires simultaneous traversal of two sequences.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Merging two sorted lists into one sorted list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Doubling every element in an array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Reversing the order of a single list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Finding whether an array contains a specific value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`int size()` — Returns the number of elements in the list</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>ArrayList.size()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of elements currently in the list, as an <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The maximum capacity of the list, as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index just past the last valid position, always <code>1</code> less than <code>length</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of bytes the list occupies in memory.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>size()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>short</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>size()</code> on an <code>ArrayList</code> different from <code>length</code> on an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size()</code> is a method call with parentheses; <code>length</code> is a field access without parentheses.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>size()</code> returns a <code>long</code>; <code>length</code> returns an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>size()</code> can change after construction; <code>length</code> cannot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They're identical — both are fields accessed without parentheses.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>size()</code> return for a freshly constructed empty <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In an indexed loop, how would you use <code>size()</code> to traverse an <code>ArrayList</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt; list.size(); i++) { ... }</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>for (int i = 1; i &lt;= list.size(); i++) { ... }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for (int i = 0; i &lt;= list.size(); i++) { ... }</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>for (int i = list.size(); i &gt; 0; i--) { ... }</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`boolean add(E obj)` — Appends `obj` to end of list; returns `true`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does <code>add(E obj)</code> place the new element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the end of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At the front of the list, shifting existing elements right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At the next empty slot, which may be anywhere in the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At a random position, determined by the list's hash function.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>add(E obj)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The index at which the element was inserted.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element that was just added.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> — it doesn't return anything.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After calling <code>list.add(x)</code>, by how much does <code>size()</code> increase?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By the number of elements currently in the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It doesn't change — <code>add</code> overwrites an existing position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By two, because a new slot is reserved.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the index of the element just appended with <code>add(obj)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 1</code> after the call.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>size()</code> after the call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code> — new elements always go to the front.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whatever index the caller supplied.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does the one-argument <code>add</code> differ from the two-argument <code>add</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The one-argument form always appends at the end; the two-argument form inserts at a specific index.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The one-argument form returns <code>void</code>; the two-argument form returns the inserted element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are identical — the one-argument form just uses a default index of <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The two-argument form replaces the element at the given index instead of inserting.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`void add(int index, E obj)` — Inserts `obj` at position `index` which must be a valid index or the current size of the list, increasing the size of the list by one.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>add(int index, E obj)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Inserts <code>obj</code> at position <code>index</code>, shifting existing elements from that position onward one step to the right.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Replaces the element at <code>index</code> with <code>obj</code>, leaving the size unchanged.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Appends <code>obj</code> to the end of the list, ignoring <code>index</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inserts <code>obj</code> at <code>index</code>, overwriting the element already there.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What range of indexes is valid for <code>add(int, E)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>size()</code> inclusive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>size() - 1</code> inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>From <code>0</code> to <code>size() + 1</code> inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any non-negative <code>int</code>; gaps are filled with <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is <code>size()</code> itself a valid index for <code>add(int, E)</code> but not for <code>get</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because inserting at <code>size()</code> means appending at the end, which is a valid position; there's no element at <code>size()</code> yet to read with <code>get</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>add</code> ignores its index argument when the list is empty.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>get</code> requires a strictly positive index, while <code>add</code> allows zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>get</code> is deprecated for index <code>size()</code>; use <code>getLast</code> instead.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>By how much does the list's size change after a call to <code>add(int, E)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It increases by one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It stays the same because an existing element is replaced.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It doubles, because the list's capacity is expanded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It decreases by one if <code>obj</code> is <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to the element formerly at index <code>i</code> when you call <code>add(i, x)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It moves to index <code>i + 1</code> (along with all following elements).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is overwritten by <code>x</code> and lost.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It stays at index <code>i</code>, and <code>x</code> goes to the end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is returned by the method as the result.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E get(int index)` — Returns the element at position `index` in the list</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>get(int index)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element at the given position in the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A copy of the element at the given position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the element at the given position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code> if the element is absent, otherwise the element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>, what type does <code>get</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code> — the list's element type <code>E</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Object</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>CharSequence</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>char[]</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What exception is thrown if the index passed to <code>get</code> is out of range?</p></question>
