      <card>
        <question><p>Does <code>get</code> remove the element from the list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It just returns a reference to it, leaving the list unchanged.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — <code>get</code> removes and returns the element in one call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the list is full; otherwise it leaves the list unchanged.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only at the ends of the list; middle <code>get</code>s leave the list unchanged.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the <code>ArrayList</code> equivalent of the array expression <code>a[i]</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>a.get(i)</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>a.at(i)</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a[i]</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>a.read(i)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E set(int index, E obj)` — Replaces the element at position `index` with `obj`; returns the element formerly at position index.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>set(int index, E obj)</code> do to the list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Replaces the element at <code>index</code> with <code>obj</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Inserts <code>obj</code> at <code>index</code>, shifting later elements one step right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Removes the element at <code>index</code> and replaces it with <code>obj</code> at the end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Swaps the element at <code>index</code> with the element at position <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>set</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was previously at that position.</p></answer>
