    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`E remove(int index)` — Removes the element from position `index`, moving elements at position `index + 1` and higher to the left, and decreases the size of the list by one. Returns the element formerly at position `index`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>remove(int index)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was at position <code>index</code> before removal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code> — it doesn't return anything.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code> if an element was removed, <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The new element that was shifted into that position.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to elements after the removed index?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They all shift one position to the left.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They stay at their original indexes and a <code>null</code> fills the gap.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They all shift one position to the right.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the immediate neighbor moves; the rest stay put.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does <code>remove(int)</code> affect the list's size?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It decreases the size by one.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It stays the same — the removed slot is filled with <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It doubles, because internal bookkeeping duplicates the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It decreases by two if the removed element was itself a list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After <code>list.remove(i)</code>, what's at index <code>i</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The element that was previously at index <code>i + 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code>, leaving a gap.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element that was previously at index <code>i - 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The element that was just removed.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can <code>remove(int)</code> cause index-skipping bugs during an indexed traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If you still increment the index after a removal, you skip over the element that was shifted into the current position.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>remove(int)</code> removes a random element, not the one at that index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>remove(int)</code> throws an exception at the end of the list and exits the loop early.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>remove(int)</code> silently re-sorts the list, invalidating all indexes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Wrapper classes</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>The College Board is weirdly obsessed with wrapper classes.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Which topic does the College Board place unusual emphasis on for AP CSA?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Wrapper classes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Recursion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>String manipulation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Inheritance.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What are "wrapper classes" in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Reference classes like <code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code> that wrap primitive values as objects.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Helper classes that wrap an <code>ArrayList</code> with thread-safety features.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Subclasses of <code>Object</code> used to represent arrays as objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Utility classes that provide static helper methods for primitive values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why does the AP curriculum care so much about wrapper classes even though real code rarely uses them directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They're the only way to put primitive values into generic collections like <code>ArrayList</code>, so they show up on the exam.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because real-world Java code uses them constantly in place of primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because they replace primitive types in the Java standard library.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM is implemented on top of the wrapper classes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name the three wrapper classes you need to know for AP CSA.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer</code>, <code>Double</code>, and <code>Boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Int</code>, <code>Float</code>, and <code>Char</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code>, <code>Character</code>, and <code>String</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code>, <code>Long</code>, and <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is wrapper-class mastery practically critical in day-to-day Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not really — autoboxing handles most of it — but it's a recurring AP exam topic.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — professional Java code cannot function without explicit wrapper calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because primitives have been deprecated in favor of wrappers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, since every <code>ArrayList</code> operation goes through wrapper methods by hand.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The `Integer`, `Double`, and `Boolean` classes exist primarily because generic types like `ArrayList` can only use reference types as their type parameters. The wrapper classes exist to "wrap" a primitive value in an object so it can be put into an `ArrayList` or used with another generic class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do wrapper classes like <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code> exist?</p></question>
        <answer><p>So that primitive values can be represented as objects and used with generic classes that require reference types.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>So that primitive values can be garbage collected when no longer in use.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So that primitives can have methods like <code>toString</code> called on them directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So that the JVM can store primitive values in a single unified heap.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't generics use primitive types directly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Java's generic type parameters are restricted to reference types.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because primitive types have no <code>toString</code> method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM runs out of memory when primitive generics are instantiated.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because primitive types are too small to hold a type parameter tag.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to "wrap" a primitive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To put its value inside an object of the corresponding wrapper class so it can be treated as a reference.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To convert the primitive into a <code>String</code> via <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To store the primitive inside an <code>Object[]</code> of length one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To pass the primitive by reference instead of by value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which wrapper would you use to store a list of <code>boolean</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Boolean</code>, in an <code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Bool</code>, in an <code>ArrayList&lt;Bool&gt;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>boolean</code>, directly, because booleans are already objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code>, storing <code>"true"</code> or <code>"false"</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you write <code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code> is a primitive type. You need the reference wrapper <code>Double</code>: <code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code> is too large to fit in a type parameter slot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code> has been deprecated in favor of <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList</code> specifically disallows floating-point primitives.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>In general you do not need to explicitly use wrapper classes because the Java compiler will automatically wrap a primitive type used in a context where its wrapper type is expected. This is called "autoboxing". Conversely, if a wrapper type is used in a context where the corresponding primitive type is expected it will be automatically "unboxed" and converted to the primitive value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is "autoboxing"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The automatic conversion by the compiler of a primitive value into its wrapper object when a wrapper type is expected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The automatic conversion of a wrapper object into its primitive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The automatic sorting of values as they are added to a list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The process of copying an <code>ArrayList</code> into an array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is "unboxing"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The automatic conversion of a wrapper object back into its primitive value when a primitive type is expected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Removing an element from a wrapper-type <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Converting a <code>String</code> into its underlying <code>char</code> array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Stripping the generic type parameter off a raw <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; xs = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(); xs.add(5);</code>, which mechanism is at work?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Autoboxing: the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code> is wrapped into an <code>Integer</code> automatically.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Unboxing: the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code> is unpacked from a wrapper.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Implicit casting: the <code>int</code> is cast to <code>Integer</code> via a <code>(Integer)</code> cast.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Overloading: a special <code>add(int)</code> method is chosen by the compiler.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int n = xs.get(0);</code> where <code>xs</code> is an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, what happens?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing: the returned <code>Integer</code> is automatically converted to its underlying <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Autoboxing: the <code>int</code> is wrapped in an <code>Integer</code> before assignment.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>ClassCastException</code> is thrown at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Nothing special — <code>int</code> and <code>Integer</code> are the same type to the JVM.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do autoboxing and unboxing happen at compile time or run time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler inserts the conversion calls, but the actual boxing/unboxing executes at run time.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Purely at compile time: the conversion is baked in and nothing runs at run time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Purely at run time: the compiler doesn't know about boxing.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At link time, when the class file is loaded by the JVM.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>You will almost never write code where you declare the type of a variable or parameter or the return type of a method to be one of the wrapper types; just use primitive types and let autoboxing take care of things.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>In idiomatic Java, what types should you prefer for variables, parameters, and return values?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Primitive types like <code>int</code>, <code>double</code>, and <code>boolean</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Wrapper types like <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A mix — wrappers for fields and primitives for locals.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whatever type the method's callers happen to pass in.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Should you usually declare a method that returns a count as returning <code>int</code> or <code>Integer</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code> — use the primitive and let autoboxing handle conversion if needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code> — it handles <code>null</code> gracefully for missing counts.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code> — it's the most general numeric type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whichever is shorter to type in context.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why prefer primitives to wrapper types for locals and parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are simpler, faster, and avoid <code>null</code>; autoboxing handles the few places a wrapper is actually needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM cannot autobox in performance-critical code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because wrappers cannot be passed to methods, only returned from them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because primitives support more arithmetic operators than wrappers do.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If primitives are preferred, why do wrapper types ever appear at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>In places that require reference types, most commonly the type parameters of generic collections.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>In places that require primitive types, like method parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only in legacy code from before generics were added to Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Mostly in the <code>main</code> method's argument list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What problem does using <code>Integer</code> as a parameter type introduce that <code>int</code> avoids?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An <code>Integer</code> parameter can be <code>null</code>, which can cause <code>NullPointerException</code> on unboxing.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>Integer</code> parameter is slower to pass because it is copied by value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>Integer</code> parameter cannot be used in arithmetic expressions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>Integer</code> parameter can hold only positive values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Then one place you will have to use `Integer` and `Double` is when you declare an `ArrayList`: You have to write `ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;int&gt;`, `ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;double&gt;` and `ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;` rather than `ArrayList&lt;boolean&gt;`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you declare an <code>ArrayList</code> of integers?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, using the wrapper type.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>, using the primitive type.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Number&gt;</code>, using the supertype.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>IntegerArrayList</code>, a specialized subclass.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't you write <code>ArrayList&lt;int&gt;</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because type parameters must be reference types, and <code>int</code> is a primitive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> values are too small to use as generic elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>ArrayList</code> class does not define a constructor for <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>int</code> and <code>Integer</code> are the same type and the duplicate is rejected.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct list type for <code>double</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Double&gt;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;double&gt;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Number&gt;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>DoubleArrayList</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the correct list type for <code>boolean</code> values?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;bool&gt;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>ArrayList&lt;boolean&gt;</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>BooleanList</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Once you've declared an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>, can you still add plain <code>int</code> values to it?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — autoboxing wraps each <code>int</code> into an <code>Integer</code> automatically.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — you must explicitly wrap each <code>int</code> using <code>new Integer(x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — the compiler rejects <code>int</code> arguments to <code>add</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only for <code>int</code> literals, not for <code>int</code> variables.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer(int value)` — Constructs a new Integer object that represents the specified int value. This is roughly equivalent to what happens when an int is autoboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the constructor <code>Integer(int value)</code> do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Constructs a new <code>Integer</code> object that represents the given <code>int</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Returns the <code>int</code> value stored in an existing <code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parses a <code>String</code> into its numeric value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Converts the <code>int</code> into a <code>String</code> for printing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the rough equivalent of <code>new Integer(5)</code> in modern Java code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just using the <code>int</code> literal <code>5</code> in a context where an <code>Integer</code> is expected, letting autoboxing create the object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Calling <code>Integer.toInt(5)</code>, which the compiler inserts automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using the static factory <code>Integer.of(5)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Declaring an <code>int</code> variable and assigning <code>5</code> to it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is explicit use of <code>new Integer(x)</code> related to autoboxing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Autoboxing does roughly what that constructor call does: wrap the <code>int</code> inside an <code>Integer</code> object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Autoboxing avoids the constructor entirely by storing the <code>int</code> in a special slot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are unrelated — autoboxing uses a different class under the hood.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Autoboxing calls <code>toString()</code> and parses the result back into an <code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is calling <code>new Integer(x)</code> necessary in day-to-day Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — autoboxing handles it automatically wherever an <code>Integer</code> is needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — autoboxing doesn't work when adding to an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, whenever the value needs to be stored in a collection.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, for any <code>int</code> value greater than <code>127</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the parameter type of the <code>Integer</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`int intValue()` — Returns the value of an Integer as an int. This is equivalent to what happens when an Integer is unboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>intValue()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>int</code> value represented by the <code>Integer</code> object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Integer</code> object itself, for method chaining.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index at which the <code>Integer</code> is stored in its containing list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> representation of the wrapped value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What autoboxing operation is <code>intValue()</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing — converting an <code>Integer</code> back into its underlying <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Autoboxing — wrapping an <code>int</code> inside an <code>Integer</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Construction — calling <code>new Integer(x)</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parsing — converting a <code>String</code> to an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>int n = someInteger;</code>, which method is conceptually being called?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>intValue()</code> on the <code>Integer</code>, inserted automatically as part of unboxing.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer.parseInt</code> on the wrapper.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>toString()</code> followed by <code>Integer.valueOf</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer.intValue(someInteger)</code> as a static method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>intValue()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>long</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why don't you usually need to call <code>intValue()</code> explicitly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because unboxing happens automatically whenever you use an <code>Integer</code> where an <code>int</code> is expected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>intValue()</code> is <code>protected</code> and cannot be called from outside.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Integer</code> overrides <code>==</code> so comparison works directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM rewrites explicit calls to use the faster autoboxing path.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer.MAX_VALUE` — The maximum value that can be represented by an int.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The largest value that can be stored in a Java <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The largest number the <code>Integer</code> class can wrap, which is unbounded.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The maximum number of elements an <code>ArrayList</code> can hold.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The largest <code>long</code> value, rounded down to fit an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> a method or a field?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A static field (constant) of the <code>Integer</code> class.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that returns a fresh <code>Integer</code> on each call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An instance field that depends on the particular <code>Integer</code> object.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A keyword built into the Java language.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> commonly used in "find the minimum" algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As an initial value for the running minimum, so that any real element will be smaller.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As the final answer when no smaller element is found.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a sentinel to mark the end of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As the array index where the minimum is stored.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if you add 1 to <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows and wraps around to <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It throws an <code>ArithmeticException</code> for integer overflow.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It saturates and stays at <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It promotes the result to a <code>long</code> automatically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Roughly how large is <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About 2.1 billion (2^31 - 1).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>About 65,000 (2^16 - 1).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>About 4.3 billion (2^32 - 1).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>About 9.2 quintillion (2^63 - 1).</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Integer.MIN_VALUE` — The minimum value that can be represented by an int.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> represent?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The smallest (most negative) value that can be stored in a Java <code>int</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Zero, which is the smallest non-negative <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code>, the smallest negative <code>int</code> used as a sentinel.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The negation of <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> commonly used in "find the maximum" algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>As an initial value for the running maximum, so that any real element will be larger.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>As the final answer when the array is empty.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As a marker placed at the end of the array.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>As the default value inside every uninitialized <code>int</code> variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>-Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> equal to <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> is one less than <code>-Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> because of two's-complement asymmetry.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — they are exactly equal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, because <code>Integer</code> uses sign-magnitude representation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only on 32-bit JVMs; 64-bit JVMs make them differ.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens when you compute <code>-Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It overflows and gives back <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> again.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It returns <code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code> exactly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws an <code>ArithmeticException</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It promotes the result to a <code>long</code> to avoid overflow.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code> positive or negative?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Negative.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Positive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Positive, because <code>MIN_VALUE</code> means "minimum magnitude".</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`Double(double value)` — Constructs a new Double object that represents the specified double value. This is roughly equivalent to what happens when a double is autoboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the <code>Double(double value)</code> constructor do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Creates a new <code>Double</code> object wrapping the given <code>double</code> value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Parses a <code>String</code> into its <code>double</code> value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Returns the <code>double</code> held inside an existing <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rounds a <code>double</code> to the nearest representable value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why would autoboxing replace most uses of <code>new Double(x)</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the compiler automatically wraps a <code>double</code> in a <code>Double</code> wherever a <code>Double</code> is expected.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>new Double(x)</code> has been removed from the Java language.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the <code>Double</code> constructor is <code>private</code> in modern Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because autoboxing is the only way to create a <code>Double</code> in a generic context.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In modern Java, how would you turn a <code>double</code> into a <code>Double</code> idiomatically?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Just use the <code>double</code> where a <code>Double</code> is expected and let autoboxing do it.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>Double.fromPrimitive(x)</code> explicitly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Use the cast <code>(Double) x</code> on the primitive value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Wrap it with <code>new Double(x)</code>, which is still the idiomatic way.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the parameter type of the <code>Double</code> constructor on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Double</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>new Double(3.14)</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new <code>Double</code> object representing the value <code>3.14</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The primitive <code>double</code> value <code>3.14</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> containing <code>"3.14"</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An <code>Integer</code> representing the rounded value <code>3</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>`double doubleValue()` — Returns the value of a Double as a double. This is equivalent to what happens when a Double is unboxed.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does <code>doubleValue()</code> return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The <code>double</code> value held by a <code>Double</code> object.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The <code>Double</code> object itself, for method chaining.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> representation of the wrapped value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the <code>Double</code> in its containing collection.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which autoboxing operation is <code>doubleValue()</code> equivalent to?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Unboxing — converting a <code>Double</code> back into its underlying <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Autoboxing — wrapping a <code>double</code> inside a <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Calling the <code>Double(double)</code> constructor.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parsing a <code>String</code> into a <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type of <code>doubleValue()</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>double</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>Double</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>float</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Number</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When would you call <code>doubleValue()</code> explicitly?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Almost never in modern code — unboxing happens automatically wherever a <code>double</code> is needed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whenever you store a <code>double</code> in an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whenever you want to compare two <code>Double</code> objects with <code>==</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Every time you print a <code>Double</code> with <code>System.out.println</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>double d = someDouble;</code>, what is conceptually happening?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The compiler invokes <code>doubleValue()</code> on the <code>Double</code> to unbox it to a <code>double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The compiler calls <code>Double.parseDouble</code> on the wrapper.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The compiler inserts a cast from <code>Double</code> to <code>double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The wrapper is copied bit-for-bit into the primitive variable.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The College Board does not expect you to know about any methods from the `Boolean` class.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does the College Board expect you to know about <code>Boolean</code> methods on the AP CSA exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Nothing — no <code>Boolean</code> methods are required.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>All of <code>Boolean</code>'s instance methods, including <code>booleanValue</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the static methods like <code>Boolean.parseBoolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The constructor <code>Boolean(boolean)</code> and the method <code>toString</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Despite not needing its methods, why should you still know about the <code>Boolean</code> class at all?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you need it to store <code>boolean</code> values in generic collections, like <code>ArrayList&lt;Boolean&gt;</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>Boolean</code> is the primitive type used in <code>if</code> statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because every method that returns a condition must return a <code>Boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler auto-imports it only when <code>ArrayList</code> is also imported.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is <code>Boolean</code> on the AP Java Quick Reference?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Only as a wrapper type for use with generics; no specific methods are listed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — with a full list of its methods alongside <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — <code>Boolean</code> is not mentioned anywhere on the Quick Reference.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but only the static <code>Boolean.TRUE</code> and <code>Boolean.FALSE</code> fields.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you still autobox a <code>boolean</code> into a <code>Boolean</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — autoboxing works for <code>Boolean</code> just like for <code>Integer</code> and <code>Double</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — autoboxing only works for numeric types.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only inside an <code>if</code> statement condition.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only when the target type is declared as <code>Object</code>, not <code>Boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If the exam asks about a <code>Boolean</code> method, what's a reasonable assumption?</p></question>
        <answer><p>That the question is out of scope — the AP curriculum does not test <code>Boolean</code> class methods.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>That you should answer based on the corresponding <code>Integer</code> method's behavior.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the question is testing your memorization of <code>parseBoolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>That the answer is always <code>toString()</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Algorithms</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>We can compare algorithms informally by counting statement executions. For instance, sometimes it's useful to analyze a loop to determine either exactly or approximately how many times it will execute its body. More rigorously we can characterize algorithms by how their run time grows as the size of the problem grows.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is one informal way to compare algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By counting how many statements each one executes for a given input.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By timing how long each one takes on a single benchmark machine.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By looking at which one has fewer lines of source code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By counting how many variables each method declares.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a more rigorous way to characterize an algorithm's performance?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By describing how its run time grows as the size of the problem grows.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By measuring its wall-clock time on a sample input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By counting the exact number of statements for one specific input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By noting how much memory it uses on a typical machine.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why analyze how many times a loop body runs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the number of loop-body executions is often the dominant cost of an algorithm.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the loop body is the only part of a method that can have bugs.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because loops are the only construct that the compiler can optimize.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the number of loop iterations determines the number of variables used.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to describe an algorithm in terms of growth rate rather than exact counts?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You focus on how work scales with input size, not the exact number of operations for a specific input.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It means you count every machine instruction exactly for one representative input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means you measure elapsed time in milliseconds on a specific computer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means you describe how much RAM the algorithm uses at peak.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is growth rate more useful than exact statement counts in practice?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Growth rate is independent of specific machines and constants and predicts behavior as inputs get large.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because growth rate tells you the exact number of nanoseconds per operation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it lets you avoid having to understand the algorithm at all.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because it depends on the specific CPU and compiler being used.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Compute statistics about numbers in an array or `ArrayList` such as the sum, average, minimum, and maximum value.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name four standard statistics that array/<code>ArrayList</code> algorithms compute.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Sum, average, minimum, and maximum.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Count, range, median, and mode.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Mean, variance, standard deviation, and median.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>First, last, middle, and length.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is the average of a list computed in terms of other statistics?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Sum of the elements divided by the count of elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The midpoint between the minimum and the maximum.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The median value of the sorted elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The sum divided by the maximum value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a common initial value for a running maximum when scanning a list of <code>int</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>, or the first element of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>, since it is a safe neutral starting value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, so any element will be smaller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code>, as a sentinel meaning &quot;no max yet&quot;.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a common initial value for a running minimum when scanning a list of <code>int</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>Integer.MAX_VALUE</code>, or the first element of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code>, since it is a safe neutral starting value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>Integer.MIN_VALUE</code>, so any element will be larger.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code>, as a sentinel meaning &quot;no min yet&quot;.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of loop shape is used for summing a list's elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal that keeps a running total, adding each element on every iteration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A nested loop that adds each pair of elements together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A recursive call that splits the list in half and sums each side.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A loop that repeatedly multiplies the current element into an accumulator.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine if at least one element of an array or `ArrayList` has a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does an "exists"-style traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether at least one element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether every element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of elements in the collection that satisfy a property.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the first element satisfying the property.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's a typical return value of an "exists"-style traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A <code>boolean</code>: <code>true</code> if a matching element is found, <code>false</code> otherwise.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>An <code>int</code> count of matching elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first matching element itself, or <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> description of the match.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What optimization can an "exists" traversal use as soon as it finds a match?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It can return <code>true</code> immediately without checking the remaining elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It must continue scanning to confirm there are no more matches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It should reset the counter and restart the traversal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It should remove the matching element from the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If an "exists"-style traversal's loop finishes without finding a matching element, what should it return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an "exists" query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Is there any negative number in the list?"</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>&quot;How many negative numbers are in the list?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;What is the smallest number in the list?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;Sort the list of numbers in ascending order.&quot;</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine if all elements of an array or `ArrayList` have a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a "for-all"-style traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether every element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether at least one element in the collection satisfies a given property.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>How many elements satisfy the property.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first index at which the property holds.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a "for-all"-style traversal, as soon as you find a single counter-example, what can the algorithm do?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Return <code>false</code> immediately.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Return <code>true</code> immediately.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Continue scanning to count all counter-examples.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Remove the counter-example and keep searching.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a "for-all"-style traversal's loop finishes without finding a counter-example, what should it return?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>true</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The last element checked.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The number of elements checked.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How is the "all" check logically related to the "exists" check?</p></question>
        <answer><p>"All elements have property P" is the same as "no element fails to have property P" — the negation of an "exists not-P" check.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>&quot;All have P&quot; is equivalent to &quot;exists an element with P&quot;.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;All have P&quot; means the same as &quot;count of P is zero&quot;.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;All have P&quot; is unrelated to any exists-style check.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an "all" query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"Are all strings in this list non-empty?"</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>&quot;Is there any empty string in this list?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;How many strings in the list are non-empty?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;Remove all empty strings from the list.&quot;</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Access all consecutive pairs of elements of an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to access "consecutive pairs" of elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To look at elements at indexes <code>i</code> and <code>i+1</code> together for each valid <code>i</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To look at pairs <code>(i, j)</code> where <code>j</code> is any later index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To look at the first and last elements of the list together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To look at elements at even indexes paired with elements at odd indexes.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the last valid value of <code>i</code> in a consecutive-pair loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>size() - 2</code> (so that <code>i+1</code> is still a valid index).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>size() - 1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>size()</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>size() / 2</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example algorithm that uses consecutive pairs.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Checking whether a list is in strictly increasing order by comparing each element to the next.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Finding the sum of all elements of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Returning the element at the middle index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Reversing a string by swapping characters end-to-end.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you easily traverse consecutive pairs with an enhanced <code>for</code> loop alone?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Not easily — you'd need to remember the previous element yourself; an indexed loop is more natural.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — an enhanced <code>for</code> loop directly exposes both current and next element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — you can just call <code>next()</code> twice inside the loop body.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — an enhanced <code>for</code> loop cannot visit any elements of a list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>For a list of size <code>n</code>, how many consecutive pairs are there?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n - 1</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>n</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n + 1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n * (n - 1) / 2</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the presence or absence of duplicate elements in an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What question does a duplicate-detection algorithm answer?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether the collection contains two or more equal elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether the list is in sorted order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the list contains a specific target value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>How many elements the list has in total.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a straightforward nested-loop approach to duplicate detection.</p></question>
        <answer><p>For each index <code>i</code>, compare <code>list.get(i)</code> to every <code>list.get(j)</code> with <code>j &gt; i</code>, returning <code>true</code> on a match.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sort the list, then return the first element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Loop once through the list counting the length.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>For each index, compare it to index <code>i - 1</code> only.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What Java operator should you typically use to compare object elements for equality in these algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>equals</code>, not <code>==</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>==</code>, because it compares references which is what you want.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>compareTo</code>, which returns a boolean for equality.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>hashCode</code>, which returns <code>true</code> if the objects match.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's one way to detect duplicates more efficiently if the list is sorted?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Scan consecutive pairs and check whether any adjacent pair is equal.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use binary search to find each element in the rest of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Loop over all pairs <code>(i, j)</code> where <code>j &gt; i</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compare only the first and last elements of the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What should a duplicate-detection method return if no duplicates are found?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>false</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>true</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>0</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the number of elements in an array or `ArrayList` meeting specific criteria</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a "counting" traversal compute?</p></question>
        <answer><p>How many elements of the collection satisfy some criterion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether at least one element satisfies a criterion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The sum of all elements satisfying a criterion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The index of the last element satisfying a criterion.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a counting traversal of a collection, what data type is typically used for the running count?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>int</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>boolean</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>double</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a counting traversal of a collection, what is the initial value of the counter?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>list.size()</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Inside a counting traversal's loop, what do you do when an element matches the criterion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Increment the counter by 1.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Return the element immediately.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Set the counter equal to the element's value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Double the current counter value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example counting query on an <code>ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>"How many values in the list are even?"</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>&quot;Is there any even value in the list?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;What is the largest even value in the list?&quot;</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>&quot;Return a new list containing only the even values.&quot;</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Shift or rotate elements of an array or `ArrayList` left or right.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does "shifting" elements of a list mean?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Moving elements to adjacent positions in a consistent direction, typically leaving a gap or dropping an element at one end.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sorting elements into ascending order in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Randomly permuting elements within the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Swapping each element with the element at the mirrored index.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does "rotation" differ from shifting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Rotation wraps elements around: an element that falls off one end is placed at the other end.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Rotation sorts the elements while shifting leaves them in original order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rotation only works on arrays, while shifting only works on <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Rotation drops an element off one end, while shifting always wraps around.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After rotating a list one position to the right, where does the last element end up?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At index 0, as the new first element.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At the same index it started, since rotation leaves endpoints alone.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At index <code>n - 2</code>, one position before its original spot.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is removed from the list entirely.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does a left shift by 1 move elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Each element at index <code>i &gt; 0</code> moves to index <code>i - 1</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Each element at index <code>i</code> moves to index <code>i + 1</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the first and last elements are swapped with each other.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Elements are moved to random new positions within the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In a left shift (not rotation), what typically happens to the leftmost element?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It is dropped off the front (or conceptually lost), and some default value may fill the last spot.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It is moved to the end of the list, wrapping around.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is duplicated into the second position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It stays in place while all other elements move.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Reverse the order of the elements of an array or `ArrayList`.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does a reversal algorithm do to a list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Puts the elements in the opposite order: the first becomes last, the second becomes second-to-last, and so on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sorts the list in ascending order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Removes duplicate elements from the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Shuffles the elements into random order.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe an in-place reversal using two indexes.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Use indexes at the two ends, swap their elements, then move inward until they meet in the middle.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Start both indexes at 0 and walk them both forward until they reach the end.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Copy each element one at a time to a new list in the same order.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Swap each element with the element at index 0, advancing through the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How many swaps does an in-place reversal perform on a list of size <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About <code>n / 2</code> swaps.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Exactly <code>n</code> swaps.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>About <code>n * n</code> swaps.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Exactly <code>1</code> swap regardless of size.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can you reverse a list by copying into a new list?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — traverse the original list from the end and append each element to the new list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — reversal must always be performed in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — copy each element to the same index in a new list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the elements are of a primitive type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's one off-by-one pitfall in in-place reversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Stopping the loop too late and swapping elements back to their original positions.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Forgetting to initialize the accumulator variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using <code>equals</code> instead of <code>==</code> on the indexes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Failing to sort the list before reversing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the frequency with which a specific criterion is met by elements within an array or `ArrayList`</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is determining "frequency" similar to counting?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both tally how many elements meet a criterion, producing an integer count.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both return a boolean indicating whether any element matches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both require the list to be sorted first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both ignore any elements that do not match the criterion, returning <code>-1</code> if none match.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the "frequency" of a value in a list, informally?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of elements in the list equal to that value.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The index of the first occurrence of the value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the value appears in the list at all.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The largest value in the list that equals the target.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a traversal that counts how often a specific <code>String</code> appears in an <code>ArrayList&lt;String&gt;</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Loop through each element, and each time it <code>equals</code> the target, increment a counter.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Use <code>indexOf</code> once and return the result directly.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sort the list and return the first element that matches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>contains</code> on the list and return the result as an <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In list-algorithm vocabulary, what's the difference between a "count" traversal and a "frequency" traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They are essentially the same operation; "frequency" typically emphasizes counting specific matching values.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Count returns an <code>int</code>; frequency returns a <code>boolean</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Count requires a sorted list; frequency does not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Count works only on numbers; frequency works only on strings.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value should a frequency method return if the target is not present?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>0</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>-1</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>false</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Identify the individual digits in an integer</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How do you extract the last digit of a positive integer <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n % 10</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>n / 10</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n % 100</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n - 10</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How do you "remove" the last digit from a positive integer <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n / 10</code> (integer division).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>n % 10</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n - (n % 10)</code>, which yields a number ending in zero.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n - 1</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What loop pattern extracts digits of an integer one at a time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly take <code>n % 10</code>, then set <code>n = n / 10</code>, until <code>n</code> becomes 0.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Take <code>n / 10</code>, then set <code>n = n % 10</code>, until <code>n</code> is 0.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Convert <code>n</code> to a <code>String</code> and call <code>reverse()</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Subtract 1 from <code>n</code> repeatedly, counting iterations.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In what order do digits come out of a <code>% 10</code>/<code>/ 10</code> loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>From least significant to most significant.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>From most significant to least significant.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In arbitrary order depending on the value of <code>n</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In alphabetical order of the digit names.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What special case should a digit-extraction loop consider?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The value <code>0</code>, which has one digit but whose loop body never runs if you only loop while <code>n &gt; 0</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Negative numbers, which always produce zero digits.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Single-digit numbers, which must be converted to a <code>String</code> first.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Even numbers, which can't be divided by 10.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Find if one or more substrings has a particular property</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of string algorithm checks whether "one or more substrings" has a property?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A traversal that looks at substrings of the string and tests each for the property.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A recursive algorithm that divides the string in half.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A sort algorithm that arranges substrings alphabetically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A hash-based algorithm that returns the hash of the string.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What method is commonly used to extract substrings in Java?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>substring</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>charAt</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>split</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>indexOf</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a property such an algorithm might check.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Whether any substring is a palindrome, or whether a particular target substring appears.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Whether the entire string is in uppercase.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the string's length is an even number.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Whether the string has been sorted alphabetically.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the return type typical of an "exists substring with property" check?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>boolean</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>String</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>void</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What loop bounds would you use to visit every substring of length <code>k</code> in a string of length <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Start indexes from 0 to <code>n - k</code>, inclusive.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Start indexes from 0 to <code>n</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Start indexes from 1 to <code>n - 1</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Start indexes from <code>k</code> to <code>n</code>, inclusive.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Determine the number of substrings that meet specific criteria</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How is counting substrings similar to counting list elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both involve traversing all candidates and incrementing a counter whenever one meets the criterion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Both require the input to be sorted before counting.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both return a <code>boolean</code> indicating whether any candidate matches.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both only count distinct values, ignoring duplicates.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does a substring-counting algorithm return?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The number of substrings that satisfy the given condition.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>boolean</code> indicating whether any substring matched.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A new string containing all the matching substrings joined together.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first substring that satisfies the condition.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a substring-counting problem.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Counting the number of occurrences of the letter <code>"a"</code> in a string.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Sorting the characters of the string alphabetically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Returning the longest substring in the string.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Checking whether the string starts with a vowel.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why might a substring-counting loop be nested?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you may need to iterate over all possible start indexes and possibly end indexes (or lengths).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires all string operations to use nested loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> is immutable so each substring requires two loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because a single loop can never visit every character in the string.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the total number of substrings of a string of length <code>n</code> (all lengths &gt;= 1)?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n * (n + 1) / 2</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>n</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>n * n</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>2^n</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Create a new `String` with the characters reversed</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why do you have to create a new <code>String</code> when "reversing" a string?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because <code>String</code>s are immutable, so you can't modify the original in place.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because reversing always requires more memory than the original allocation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the JVM forbids any in-place modification of character arrays.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because <code>String</code> has no method that takes an index parameter.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Describe a loop-based approach to reversing a string <code>s</code>.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Build up a result by traversing <code>s</code> from the last index back to 0, appending each character to the result.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Call <code>s.sort()</code> in descending order and return the result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Traverse <code>s</code> from index 0 forward, appending each character to a result.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Swap <code>s.charAt(0)</code> with <code>s.charAt(s.length() - 1)</code> in place.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Which <code>String</code> method returns a character at a given index?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>charAt(int index)</code></p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>substring(int index)</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>get(int index)</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>indexOf(int index)</code></p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What value does the reverse of an empty string equal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The empty string <code>""</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>null</code></p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A single space character <code>&quot; &quot;</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> of length 1 containing the null character.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is "reverse a string" the same operation as "reverse an <code>ArrayList</code>"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Conceptually yes, but strings are immutable so you must produce a new string rather than swapping in place.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes, and in both cases you modify the original in place.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — reversing a list always requires recursion while reversing a string does not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — reversing a string only affects uppercase letters.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Sequential/linear search algorithms check each element in order until the desired value is found or all elements in the array or `ArrayList` have been checked. You should be able to write code that performs a linear search.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>How does linear (sequential) search work?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It checks each element in order from the start until it finds the target or reaches the end.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It jumps to the middle element and compares it to the target.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It sorts the list first and then returns the middle element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It uses a hash table to look up the target in constant time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does linear search return when the target is not present?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically <code>-1</code> or <code>false</code>, depending on the signature.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The number of comparisons it performed.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The first element of the list as a default.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It throws an exception rather than returning a value.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Does linear search require the list to be sorted?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. It works on any list, sorted or unsorted.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — the list must be sorted for linear search to work.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the elements are objects rather than primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the list has more than 10 elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the worst-case number of comparisons for linear search on a list of size <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>n</code> comparisons.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p><code>log N</code> comparisons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>N / 2</code> comparisons.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>N * N</code> comparisons.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>On the AP exam, should you be prepared to write a linear search yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — you should be able to write code that performs a linear search.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — linear search is never discussed on the AP exam.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — the exam will always provide a linear search implementation for you.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you are taking the AP Computer Science Principles exam.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Binary search algorithms can search sorted lists much more efficiently than linear search, finding elements in log N time where N is the size of the list. You are unlikely to need to write a binary search yourself for the exam.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Why is binary search faster than linear search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its run time grows as <code>log N</code> rather than <code>N</code>, so it scales much better to large lists.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It uses a hash table to locate elements in constant time.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It compares elements in parallel using multiple CPU cores.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It skips elements whose values are too small to be the target.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What precondition does binary search require?</p></question>
        <answer><p>The list must already be sorted.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The list must contain only unique elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The list must have length equal to a power of two.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The list must contain only primitive <code>int</code> values.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the big-O running time of binary search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>O(log N), where N is the size of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>O(N), where N is the size of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>O(N log N), where N is the size of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>O(1), regardless of the size of the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are you expected to write a binary search from scratch on the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — it's unlikely you'll have to write one, but you should understand how it works.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — you must be able to write it from memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — but only the recursive version is tested.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the list has more than 100 elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Roughly how many steps does binary search need for a list of a million elements?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About 20 (since <code>log2(1,000,000)</code> is about 20).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>About 1,000 (since <code>sqrt(1,000,000)</code> is 1000).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>About 500,000 (half of a million).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>About 6 (since <code>log10(1,000,000)</code> is 6).</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The binary search algorithm starts at the middle of a sorted array or `ArrayList` and on average eliminates half of the elements in each iteration until the desired value is found or all elements have been eliminated.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Where does binary search begin its search?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At the middle element of the sorted list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>At the first element of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At the last element of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>At a randomly chosen element within the list.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How much of the remaining search space is eliminated each iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>About half.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>About a third.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Exactly one element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The whole list, if the target is not the middle element.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>After comparing the target to the middle element, how does binary search decide which half to continue searching?</p></question>
        <answer><p>If the target is less than the middle, search the left half; if greater, search the right half.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Always search the left half first, then the right half if not found.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compare the target to the first element and search from there.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Randomly pick a half and recurse into it.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>When does binary search stop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>When it finds the target or the search range becomes empty.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>When it has checked every element in the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the current index reaches the end of the list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>When the loop variable reaches zero.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is halving the list each step what gives binary search its log N running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because you can halve <code>N</code> only about <code>log2 N</code> times before reaching 1.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because each step halves the number of comparisons needed per element.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because log N is the running time of any divide-and-conquer algorithm.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the list must be halved exactly <code>N</code> times to find the target.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The binary search algorithm can be written either iteratively or recursively.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can binary search be implemented with a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the iterative version uses a loop that updates <code>low</code> and <code>high</code> bounds.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — binary search is inherently recursive and cannot use loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the list is an array, not an <code>ArrayList</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but the iterative version has a different running time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can binary search be implemented recursively?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the recursive version calls itself on a smaller half of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — binary search cannot be written recursively.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the list contains at most 100 elements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes, but the recursive version is slower than the iterative one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In the recursive version, what is the base case?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An empty range (the target isn't present) or the middle element equals the target.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The full list (it returns the answer for the entire range immediately).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Any range of size 2 or smaller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A list whose first and last elements are equal.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Do the iterative and recursive versions of binary search have the same running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — both are O(log N).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — the recursive version is O(N) due to stack overhead.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — the iterative version is O(1) while the recursive version is O(log N).</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — the iterative version is O(log N) but the recursive version is O(N log N).</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is binary search a good example of "iteration vs recursion"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because the same algorithm can be expressed naturally in either style with equivalent behavior.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because binary search can only be written recursively, highlighting recursion's power.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because iteration is always faster than recursion for this algorithm.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the recursive version uses completely different logic from the iterative one.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Selection sort and insertion sort are iterative sorting algorithms that can be used to sort elements in an array or ArrayList. You should be able to recognize them but will not have to write them yourself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Are selection sort and insertion sort iterative or recursive algorithms?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Iterative — they use loops rather than recursion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Recursive — they repeatedly call themselves on smaller lists.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Selection sort is iterative but insertion sort is recursive.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Both are implemented using merge sort internally.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are you expected to write selection sort or insertion sort from scratch on the AP exam?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — you only need to be able to recognize them.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — you must be able to write both from memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — but only selection sort is tested on the exam.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if you are taking the AP Computer Science Principles exam.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the basic idea of selection sort?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Repeatedly find the smallest remaining element and swap it into the next position at the front of the list.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Repeatedly insert each new element into its correct sorted position.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Recursively split the list in half, sort each, and merge them.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compare adjacent elements and swap them if they are out of order.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the basic idea of insertion sort?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Grow a sorted prefix by taking each next element and inserting it into its correct spot within the already-sorted portion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Repeatedly find the smallest remaining element and swap it to the front.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Recursively split the list into halves and sort each one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compare all pairs of indexes and swap whenever a smaller value is found later.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can these sorts be applied to an <code>ArrayList</code> as well as an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — the ideas work on either, using <code>get</code>/<code>set</code> instead of array indexing.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — these algorithms only work on arrays of primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only selection sort works on <code>ArrayList</code>; insertion sort does not.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the <code>ArrayList</code> is first converted to an array.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Merge sort is a recursive sorting algorithm that can be used to sort elements in an array or ArrayList. You will not have to be able to write a merge sort.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Is merge sort iterative or recursive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Recursive — it divides the list and recursively sorts each half.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Iterative — it uses a single loop over the entire list.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Iterative for arrays, recursive for <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Neither — merge sort uses no control flow at all.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Will the AP exam ask you to implement merge sort yourself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — you only need to understand its behavior conceptually.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — you must be able to write merge sort from memory.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — but only the merge step is tested.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only on the free-response portion of the exam.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What two phases does merge sort have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A recursive "divide and sort" phase, and a "merge" phase that combines two sorted halves into one sorted result.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A sorting phase and a searching phase.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>An initialization phase and a cleanup phase.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A compare phase and a swap phase.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is merge sort's running time?</p></question>
        <answer><p>O(N log N), which is asymptotically faster than selection or insertion sort on large lists.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>O(N), faster than either selection sort or insertion sort.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>O(log N), the same as binary search.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>O(N * N), slower than selection or insertion sort.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can merge sort be used on both arrays and <code>ArrayList</code>s?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — conceptually it works on any indexable sequence of elements.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — merge sort only works on arrays of primitives.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only on arrays, since <code>ArrayList</code>s cannot be split.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only on <code>ArrayList</code>s, since arrays cannot be recursively halved.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Recursion</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>A recursive method is a method that calls itself.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What is a recursive method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A method that calls itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A method that is called from inside a loop.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that does not return any value.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A method that calls only built-in Java library methods.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In AP CSA, what kind of recursion are you expected to know about?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Simple direct recursion, where a method calls itself by name.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Mutual recursion, where two methods call each other.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Tail recursion, where the recursive call is always the last statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Indirect recursion, where a helper class calls the method back.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Is a method that calls another method that happens to call it considered directly recursive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — that is mutual recursion; AP CSA focuses on direct recursion where the method calls itself.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — any chain of calls that returns to the original is direct recursion.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — as long as the recursive call is in the same file.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — but only if both methods are in the same class.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens at the machine level when a recursive method calls itself?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A new stack frame is pushed with its own copy of local variables and parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The existing stack frame is reused with updated parameters.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java allocates a new thread to run the recursive call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The method's bytecode is recompiled for each call.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Can a recursive method also use loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes — recursion and iteration can appear together in the same method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — recursion and loops are mutually exclusive in a single method.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the loop appears before any recursive call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the method is marked with a special annotation.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recursive methods contain at least one base case, which halts the recursion, and at least one recursive call.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What two things must every recursive method have?</p></question>
        <answer><p>At least one base case and at least one recursive call.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A loop and a <code>return</code> statement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A try/catch block and a recursive call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A base case and an iterative helper method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does the base case do in a recursive method?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It handles a simple input directly without recursing further, stopping the recursion.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It makes the first recursive call with the original input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It catches any exceptions thrown by later recursive calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It increments a counter tracking how deep the recursion has gone.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens if a recursive method has no base case, or the base case is never reached?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Infinite recursion occurs, eventually causing a <code>StackOverflowError</code>.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The program silently returns <code>null</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The recursion terminates as soon as the first call returns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Java automatically inserts a base case at runtime.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is a recursive call?</p></question>
        <answer><p>A call the method makes to itself, usually on a smaller or simpler input.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Any call the method makes to another method in the same class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A call to a method marked with the <code>recursive</code> keyword.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A call that is placed inside the body of a loop.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it important that the recursive call move toward the base case?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Otherwise the recursion won't terminate and the program will run forever (or crash).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because the compiler refuses to compile recursive calls that don't shrink their input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because otherwise the result of the recursion will always be <code>0</code>.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because otherwise each call will use exponentially more memory than the last.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Each recursive call has its own set of local variables, including its parameters.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Do recursive calls share local variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No. Each call has its own independent set of local variables and parameters.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — all recursive calls share the same copies of local variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only the parameters are shared; other local variables are per-call.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only <code>static</code> local variables are shared across calls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is it important that each recursive call have its own independent set of local variables and parameters?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets each recursive call keep its own state, so updates in one call don't clobber another.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java requires every method to have its own local variable area.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To make recursion run faster than iteration would.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>So that the compiler can optimize away the recursive calls.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Where are a recursive method's per-call local variables stored?</p></question>
        <answer><p>On the call stack, in a new stack frame created for each invocation of the method.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>On the heap, in a shared pool of local variable storage.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In static fields of the enclosing class.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>In the CPU's registers for fastest access.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If a recursive method has a parameter <code>int n</code>, does each call share the same <code>n</code>?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — each call has its own <code>n</code>, whose value depends on what was passed in.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — all calls share a single <code>n</code> variable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Yes — but each call is allowed to modify it independently.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if <code>n</code> is passed by reference.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What happens to a call's local variables when that call returns?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Its stack frame is popped and those local variables go out of scope.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They are kept in memory forever for debugging purposes.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are copied into the caller's local variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are merged with the locals of the next recursive call.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Parameter values capture the progress of a recursive process, much like loop control variable values capture the progress of a loop.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What role do parameter values play in recursion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They capture the progress of the recursive process — where in the computation a given call is working.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They store the final result to return to the top-level caller.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They store error messages to display if the recursion fails.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are used only for type checking and have no runtime meaning.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What role do loop control variables play in a loop?</p></question>
        <answer><p>They capture the progress of the loop — which iteration or index it is currently on.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>They store the result of the loop's computation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They are only used to label the loop for <code>break</code> statements.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>They hold the input values that the loop is processing.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What is the analogy between recursive parameters and loop control variables?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Both track "how far along" the computation is; parameters serve that role for recursion that control variables serve for loops.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Parameters store the result of each call, and control variables store the loop's output.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters never change across calls, and control variables never change across iterations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Parameters must always be <code>int</code>, and control variables must always be <code>int</code>.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>In <code>factorial(int n)</code>, what does the parameter <code>n</code> tell you about the recursion's progress?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It indicates which sub-problem (<code>n!</code>) the current call is solving; smaller <code>n</code> means closer to the base case.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It stores the running product of the factorial computed so far.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It stores the result of the base case so it can be returned at the top.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It is unused — <code>factorial</code> uses global state instead.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why shouldn't a recursive method just use global state to track progress?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because parameters per call keep each recursion's state cleanly separated, avoiding interference between calls.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not allow recursive methods to access global variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because global state is always slower than local state in Java.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because global state would make the recursion terminate too quickly.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Recursion can be used to traverse linear structures like `String`s, arrays, and `ArrayList`s but it is most useful for traversing tree structures which are difficult to traverse with simple loops.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can recursion traverse a linear structure like an array?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, by recursing on a smaller subrange of the structure.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — recursion can only traverse tree structures.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the structure is first converted to a tree.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the structure has fewer than 100 elements.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What kind of structure does recursion especially shine at traversing?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Tree structures, where simple loops don't naturally fit.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Linear structures like arrays, which are easier to traverse recursively than with loops.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Hash tables, which are defined recursively.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Single variables, which need recursion to be inspected.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name three linear structures you could traverse recursively.</p></question>
        <answer><p><code>String</code>s, arrays, and <code>ArrayList</code>s.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Trees, graphs, and hash maps.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p><code>int</code>s, <code>double</code>s, and <code>boolean</code>s.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Classes, methods, and fields.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why are trees harder to traverse with simple loops?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because trees branch at each node, so a single loop can't naturally follow all the branches without extra data structures.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because trees contain cycles that confuse simple loop variables.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because trees are not indexable with an integer index.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because Java forbids using loops on tree-shaped data.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What makes recursion a natural fit for trees?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Trees are themselves defined recursively — a tree is a node with subtrees — so a recursive traversal mirrors the structure.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because recursion is faster than iteration for all tree operations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because trees can only be created using recursive method calls.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the Java compiler treats <code>tree</code> as a special recursive type.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Any recursive solution can be replicated through the use of an iterative approach. However some recursions, such as tree recursions, will require maintaining extra data structures to keep track of the information that would otherwise be managed by the process of recursion.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Can every recursive algorithm be rewritten iteratively?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Yes, in principle any recursive solution has an iterative equivalent.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>No — tree recursions cannot be expressed iteratively at all.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the recursion has a single base case.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only if the recursive calls occur at the end of the method.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What's the catch when converting recursive tree algorithms to iterative ones?</p></question>
        <answer><p>You usually need an explicit data structure (like a stack) to keep track of work the recursion was managing automatically.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The iterative version is always asymptotically faster than the recursive one.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>You must use a different algorithm entirely, since iteration can't express tree traversal.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The iterative version must use multiple threads to simulate recursion.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What does recursion manage "for free" compared to iteration?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Bookkeeping — the call stack stores per-call state, saving you from managing it by hand.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Memory allocation — recursive calls never allocate new objects.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Error handling — exceptions in recursive methods are caught automatically.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Concurrency — each recursive call runs on its own thread.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What data structure often replaces the call stack in an iterative version of a tree traversal?</p></question>
        <answer><p>An explicit stack (e.g. an <code>ArrayList</code> or <code>Deque</code> used as a stack).</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>A <code>HashMap</code> keyed by recursion depth.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A single global <code>int</code> counter.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>A <code>String</code> buffer that records the call history.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>If recursion and iteration are equivalent in power, why ever prefer recursion?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because for some problems, especially tree-structured ones, the recursive version is dramatically clearer and easier to reason about.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because recursion is always asymptotically faster than iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because recursion always uses less memory than iteration.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because recursion is the only way to express certain algorithms in Java.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>

  <section>
    <title>Stuff the College Board just had to get off their chest</title>

    <cards>
      <ek>System reliability is limited. Programmers should make an effort to maximize system reliability.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What does it mean to say that "system reliability is limited"?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No software system is perfectly reliable; failures and bugs are always possible.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>It means that only expensive software systems can be reliable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means that reliability depends only on the hardware, not the software.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>It means that software reliability improves automatically over time.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What responsibility do programmers have regarding reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To make an effort to maximize the reliability of the systems they build.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To guarantee their software is 100% reliable before shipping it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To blame hardware vendors when reliability issues occur.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To leave reliability concerns to the quality assurance team.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name one programming practice that helps maximize reliability.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Writing and running tests to catch bugs before the software is deployed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Writing code as quickly as possible to finish before deadlines.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Avoiding documentation so the code stays lean and fast.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Using as many third-party libraries as possible without review.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why can't programmers guarantee 100% reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because software runs on imperfect hardware, handles unpredictable inputs, and is written by humans who make mistakes.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because Java does not provide tools to check reliability.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because reliability is determined solely by the user, not the programmer.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because reliability depends only on how fast the code runs.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does error handling contribute to reliability?</p></question>
        <answer><p>It lets a program recover or fail gracefully instead of crashing when unexpected conditions occur.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By making errors invisible to the user so they don't notice problems.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By preventing the program from ever encountering unexpected input.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By speeding up execution so that errors don't have time to occur.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>Legal issues and intellectual property concerns arise when creating programs.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What kinds of non-technical concerns arise from writing programs?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Legal issues and intellectual property concerns.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Compilation errors and runtime exceptions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Hardware and network concerns.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Memory management and garbage collection.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of an intellectual property concern for programmers.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Respecting software licenses when using third-party libraries.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Choosing which algorithm to implement.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Deciding how many comments to include in your code.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Picking a programming language to use.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a legal issue that can arise from a program.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Handling user data in compliance with privacy laws.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Choosing whether to use tabs or spaces for indentation.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Deciding which IDE to use for development.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Selecting a version of Java to compile against.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why should programmers care about licenses on open-source code they use?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because licenses impose conditions on how the code may be used, modified, and redistributed.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because open-source code is always free of all restrictions.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because open-source licenses are not legally enforceable.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because using open-source code always requires payment.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Who owns the copyright on code a programmer writes at their job, usually?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Typically their employer, depending on the employment contract and jurisdiction.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>The programmer personally, regardless of where they wrote it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>The user of the software, since they pay for it.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No one — code written for a job is automatically public domain.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>The creation of programs has impacts on society, economies, and culture. These impacts can be beneficial and/or harmful.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>Name three domains the creation of programs can impact.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Society, economies, and culture.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Hardware, networks, and operating systems.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Memory, CPU, and disk usage.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Compilation, linking, and execution.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Are the impacts of software always positive?</p></question>
        <answer><p>No — they can be beneficial, harmful, or both at the same time.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Yes — software always improves society.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>No — the impacts are always harmful.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Only beneficial impacts count as &quot;impacts&quot;.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a beneficial societal impact of software.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Medical software that helps doctors diagnose illnesses more accurately.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Software that only runs on expensive hardware.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Software that increases the complexity of everyday tasks.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Software that collects personal data without consent.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Give an example of a harmful economic impact of software.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Automation displacing workers in certain industries.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Software that lowers the cost of communication worldwide.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Software that helps small businesses reach new customers.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Software that makes scientific research more efficient.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why do programmers have to think beyond the technical correctness of their code?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because their work has real-world impacts on people, and those impacts deserve consideration.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because correct code is the only thing programmers should ever consider.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because the Java compiler enforces ethical considerations.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because non-technical concerns are the responsibility of managers, not programmers.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>

    <cards>
      <ek>When using the computer, personal privacy is at risk. Programmers should attempt to safeguard personal privacy.</ek>

      <card>
        <question><p>What risk does using a computer pose to its user?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Their personal privacy can be compromised.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Their hardware may eventually fail.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Their screen may damage their eyesight.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Their keyboard may cause repetitive strain injuries.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>What responsibility do programmers have regarding user privacy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>To attempt to safeguard personal privacy in the systems they build.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>To collect as much user data as possible for future use.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To leave privacy concerns entirely to the end user.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>To share user data freely with advertising partners.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Name one concrete way a programmer can protect user privacy.</p></question>
        <answer><p>Storing only the minimum personal data needed and encrypting sensitive fields.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Making all user data publicly searchable so users can find it themselves.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Sharing user data with as many services as possible for redundancy.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Storing user passwords in plain text for easy recovery.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>Why is privacy especially at risk in networked software?</p></question>
        <answer><p>Because data can be transmitted and aggregated across many systems, widening exposure.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>Because network cables physically carry the user's private data out of the building.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because wireless networks automatically encrypt everything anyway.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>Because only networked software uses personal data at all.</p></distractor>
      </card>
      <card>
        <question><p>How does good authentication help safeguard privacy?</p></question>
        <answer><p>By ensuring only authorized users can access personal information.</p></answer>
        <distractor><p>By making software run faster and therefore leak less data.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By encrypting the data on the hard disk after the user logs in.</p></distractor>
        <distractor><p>By automatically deleting old user accounts after a year.</p></distractor>
      </card>
    </cards>
  </section>
</deck>
